{"title_page": "1943 in jazz", "text_new": "{{Year in music|1943}}\n{{Year in jazz\n |image      = Duke Ellington - Hurricane Ballroom - trio.jpg\n |caption    = A trio of musicians from Duke Ellington's orchestra during the early morning broadcast\n |prioryear  = 1942\n |afteryear  = 1944\n}}\n{{Year nav topic5|1943|jazz}}\n{{Dynamic list}}\nThis is a timeline documenting events of '''[[Jazz]] in the year 1943'''.\n\n==Events==\n* The [[American Federation of Musicians]] recording ban, called by [[James Petrillo]], continued through 1943. [[Django Reinhardt]] records \"[[Cavalerie]]\" on the 17 February 1943 in [[Paris]] after an aborted attempt at recording it in 1937.<ref name=\"Williams1998\">{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Patrick|title=Django Reinhardt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qkgkaD1T4gC&pg=PA182|accessdate=11 February 2012|year=1998|publisher=Editions Parenth\u00e8ses|isbn=978-2-86364-612-0|page=182}}</ref>\n\n==Album releases==\n* [[Duke Ellington]]: ''[[Black, Brown and Beige]]'' (1943)\n\n==Standards==\n{{See also|List of 1940s jazz standards}}\n\n==Deaths==\n[[File:Fats Waller edit.jpg|thumb|[[Fats Waller]]]]\n\n; February\n* '''17''' \u2013 [[Armand J. Piron]], American violinist, band leader, and composer (born 1888).\n* '''22''' \u2013 [[Tamara Drasin]], American singer and actress (born [[1905 in jazz|1905]]).\n\n; April\n* '''4''' \u2013 [[Tiny Parham]], Canadian-born bandleader and pianist (born [[1900 in jazz|1900]]).\n\n; May\n* '''28''' \u2013 [[Vaughn De Leath]], American singer (born 1894).\n\n; June\n* '''8''' \u2013 [[Min Leibrook]], American tubist and bassist (born [[1903 in jazz|1903]]).\n\n; August\n* '''3''' \u2013 [[Corky Cornelius]], American trumpeter (born [[1914 in jazz|1914]]).\n\n; October\n* '''5''' \u2013 [[Leon Roppolo]], American clarinetist (born [[1902 in jazz|1902]]).\n* '''23''' \u2013 [[Ben Bernie]], American violinist and radio personality (born 1891).\n\n; December\n* '''15''' \u2013 [[Fats Waller]], American pianist, organist, composer, singer, and comedic entertainer (born [[1904 in jazz|1904]]).\n\n; Unknown date\n* [[Zue Robertson]], American trombonist (born 1891).\n\n==Births==\n[[File:Larry-coryell-ffm-001.jpg|thumb|right|[[Larry Coryell]]]]\n\n; January\n* '''3''' \u2013 [[Brian Hopper]], British guitarist and saxophonist.\n* '''6''' \u2013 [[Barry Altschul]], American drummer.\n* '''16''' \u2013 [[Gavin Bryars]], English composer and upright bassist.\n* '''17''' \u2013 [[Billy Harper]], American saxophonist.\n* '''18''' \u2013 [[Al Foster]], American drummer.\n* '''20''' \u2013 [[Valery Ponomarev]], Russian trumpeter.\n* '''21'''\n** [[Steve Gilmore (musician)|Steve Gilmore]], American upright bassist.\n** [[Steve Potts (jazz musician)|Steve Potts]], American saxophonist.\n* '''22'''\n** [[Didier Malherbe]], French saxophonist, flautist and duduk player.\n** [[Maarten Altena]], Dutch composer and upright bassist.\n** [[Michal Urbaniak]], American musician and composer.\n** [[Pete Minger]], American trumpeter (died [[2000 in jazz|2000]]).\n** [[Tony Campise]], American saxophonist (died [[2010 in jazz|2010]]).\n* '''23''' \u2013 [[Gary Burton]], American vibraphonist.\n* '''26''' \u2013 [[Leny Andrade]], Brazilian singer and musician.\n\n; February\n* '''4''' \u2013 [[Newman Taylor Baker]], African-American drummer.\n* '''6''' \u2013 [[Calvin Keys]], American guitarist.\n* '''14''' \u2013 [[Maceo Parker]], American saxophonist.\n* '''19''' \u2013 [[Laurie Allan]], English drummer, [[Delivery (band)|Delivery]] and [[Gong (band)|Gong]].\n* '''21''' \u2013 [[Duncan Swift]], British pianist (died [[1997 in jazz|1997]]).\n* '''25''' \u2013 [[Howie Smith]], American saxophonist, composer and educator.\n* '''28''' \u2013 [[Claudio Mattone]], Italian composer, lyricist and music producer.\n\n; March\n* '''4''' \u2013 [[Lucio Dalla]], Italian singer, clarinetist and actor (died [[2012 in jazz|2012]]).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/05/arts/music/lucio-dalla-italian-singer-songwriter-dies-at-68.html | title=Lucio Dalla, Italian Troubadour, Dies at 68 | first=Elisabetta | last=Povoledo | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=2012-03-04 | accessdate=2016-04-15}}</ref>\n* '''9''' \u2013 [[Mayuto Correa]], Brazilian percussionist, guitarist, and composer.\n* '''11''' \u2013 [[Richie Pratt]], American drummer (died [[2015 in jazz|2015]]).\n* '''20''' \u2013 [[Jon Christensen]], Norwegian drummer and percussionist.\n* '''21''' \u2013 [[Vivian Stanshall]], English singer-songwriter, musician, author, poet, and wit, [[Bonzo Dog Doo-Dah Band]] (died [[1995 in jazz|1995]]).\n* '''22'''\n** [[George Benson]], American guitarist.\n** [[Keith Relf]], English singer and harmonica player, [[The Yardbirds]] (died [[1976 in jazz|1976]]).\n\n; April\n* '''2''' \u2013 [[Larry Coryell]], American guitarist (died [[2017 in jazz|2017]]).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7694346/larry-coryell-dies-obituary-legendary-jazz-guitarist-godfather-of-fusion | title=Legendary Jazz Guitarist Larry Coryell, 'Godfather of Fusion,' Dies at 73 | first=Mary J. | last=DiMeglio | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date=2017-02-20 | accessdate=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n* '''6'''\n** [[Noah Howard]], American alto saxophonist (died [[2010 in jazz|2010]]).\n** [[Gerry Niewood]], American saxophonist (died [[2009 in jazz|2009]]).\n* '''8''' \u2013 [[Phil Lee (musician)|Phil Lee]], English guitarist.\n* '''18''' \u2013 [[Clyde Stubblefield]], American drummer best known for his work with [[James Brown]] (kidney failure) (died [[2017 in jazz|2017]]).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/clyde-stubblefield-james-browns-funky-drummer-dead-at-73-w467805 | title=Clyde Stubblefield, James Brown's 'Funky Drummer,' Dead at 73 | first=Daniel | last=Kreps | work=[[Rolling Stone]] | date=2017-02-18 | accessdate=2017-02-20}}</ref>\n* '''27''' \u2013 [[Freddie Waits]], American drummer (died [[1989 in jazz|1989]]).\n\n; May\n* '''8''' \u2013 [[Jerry Rusch]], American trumpeter (died [[2003 in jazz|2003]]).\n* '''14''' \u2013 [[Jack Bruce]], Scottish musician and songwriter (died [[2014 in jazz|2014]]).\n* '''20'''\n** [[Bobby Enriquez]], Filipino pianist (born [[1996 in jazz|1996]]).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/1048621-Bobby-Enriquez | title=Bobby Enriquez | publisher=[[Discogs.com]] | accessdate=2018-01-23}}</ref>\n** [[Terry Smith (guitarist)|Terry Smith]], British guitarist.\n* '''23''' \u2013 [[Felix Slov\u00e1\u010dek]], Czech clarinetist, conductor, film composer and saxophonist.\n* '''24''' \u2013 [[Gary Burghoff]], American actor and singer.\n* '''30''' \u2013 [[Peter Lipa]], Slovak singer, composer and promoter of jazz.\n\n; June\n* '''9''' \u2013 [[Kenny Barron]], American pianist.\n* '''24''' \u2013 [[Frank Lowe]], American saxophonist and composer (died [[2003 in jazz|2003]]).\n* '''26''' \u2013 [[Georgie Fame]], English singer and keyboard player.\n\n; July\n* '''4'''\n** [[Conny Bauer]], German trombonist.\n** [[Fred Wesley]], American trombonist.\n* '''9''' \u2013 [[Manfred Eicher]], German record producer, [[ECM Records]].\n\n; August\n* '''10'''\n** [[Bj\u00f8rn Krokfoss]], Norwegian drummer.\n** [[Michael Mantler]], Austrian trumpeter and composer.\n* '''14''' \u2013 [[Ben Sidran]], American pianist, organist, vocalist and writer.\n* '''20''' \u2013 [[Jiggs Whigham]], American trombonist.\n* '''23''' \u2013 [[Pino Presti]], Italian bassist, arranger, composer, and conductor.\n* '''28''' \u2013 [[Richard Wright (musician)|Richard Wright]], English keyboardist, composer, singer and songwriter (died [[2008 in jazz|2008]]).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/16/arts/music/16wright.html | title=Richard Wright, Member of Pink Floyd, Dies at 65 | first=Jon | last=Pareles | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=2008-09-15 | accessdate=2016-02-27}}</ref>\n* '''29'''\n** [[Dick Halligan]], American musician and composer.\n** [[Edu Lobo]], Brazilian singer, guitarist, and composer.\n\n; September\n* '''1''' \u2013 [[Webster Lewis]], American keyboardist (died [[2002 in jazz|2002]]).\n* '''3''' \u2013 [[Kjell \u00d6hman]], Swedish pianist, Hammond organist, and accordionist (died [[2015 in jazz|2015]]).\n* '''10'''\n** [[David Horler]], English trombonist.\n** [[Garrett List]], American trombonist, vocalist and composer (died [[2019 in jazz|2019]]).\n* '''14''' \u2013 [[Marcos Valle]], Brazilian singer, instrumentalist, and songwriter.\n\n; October\n* '''9''' \u2013 [[Pete Cosey]], American guitarist (died [[2012 in jazz|2012]]).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/blues-jazz-guitarist-pete-cosey-dies-20120611 | title=Jazz Guitar Pioneer Pete Cosey Dead at 68 | work=[[Rolling Stone]] | date=2012-06-11 | accessdate=2016-04-15}}</ref>\n* '''14''' \u2013 [[Fritz Pauer]], Austrian pianist, composer, and bandleader (died [[2012 in jazz|2012]]).\n* '''22''' \u2013 [[Urszula Dudziak]], Polish vocalist.\n* '''27''' \u2013 [[Weldon Irvine]], American composer, playwright, poet, pianist and organist (died [[2002 in jazz|2002]]).\n\n; November\n* '''7''' \u2013 [[Joni Mitchell]], American singer and songwriter.\n* '''12'''\n** [[Claudio Slon]], Brazilian drummer (died [[2002 in jazz|2002]]).\n** [[Thorgeir Stub\u00f8]], Norwegian guitarist (died [[1986 in jazz|1986]]).\n* '''17'''\n** [[Richard Anthony Hewson]], English producer, arranger, conductor.\n** [[Willie Murphy (musician)|Willie Murphy]], American singer and pianist (died [[2019 in jazz|2019]]).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.startribune.com/heart-and-soul-of-minneapolis-music-scene-willie-murphy-dies-at-75/504291622/|title='Heart and soul of Minneapolis music scene' Willie Murphy dies at 75 | first=Chris | last=Riemenschneider | newspaper=[[Star Tribune]] | date=2019-01-13 | accessdate=2019-01-16}}</ref>\n* '''22''' \u2013 [[Ricky May]], New Zealand musician (died [[1988 in jazz|1988]]).\n* '''23''' \u2013 [[Alan Lawrence Turnbull]], Australian drummer (died [[2014 in jazz|2014]]).\n* '''28''' \u2013 [[Butch Thompson]], American pianist and clarinetist.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/artist/butch-thompson/2589466 | title=Butch Thompson | publisher=[[iTunes]] | accessdate=2018-01-23}}</ref>\n\n; December\n* '''12''' \u2013 [[Grover Washington, Jr.]], American saxophonist (born [[1999 in jazz|1999]]).\n* '''13''' \u2013 [[Skip Prokop]], Canadian rock and jazz fusion drummer in [[Lighthouse (band)|Lighthouse]], [[The Paupers]] (died [[2017 in jazz|2017]]).<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/music/2017/08/31/skip-prokop-lighthouse-co-founder-and-drummer-dead-at-74.html | title=Skip Prokop, Lighthouse co-founder and drummer, dead at 74 | newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] | date=2017-08-31| accessdate=2017-10-30}}</ref>\n* '''24''' \u2013 [[Volker Kriegel]], German guitarist and composer (died [[2003 in jazz|2003]]).\n\n; Unknown date\n* [[Fred Tompkins]], American flautist and composer.\n* [[Peter Boothman]], Australian guitarist, composer and educator (died [[2012 in jazz|2012]]).\n* [[Sven-\u00c5ke Johansson]], Swedish drummer and composer.\n* [[Ted Milton]], English poet and musician.\n* [[Winston Mankunku Ngozi]], South African tenor saxophonist (died [[2009 in jazz|2009]]).\n\n==See also==\n* [[1940s in jazz]]\n* [[List of years in jazz]]\n* [[1943 in music]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|title=[[Real Book#Other Real Books|The New Real Book]], Volume I|year=1988|publisher=Sher Music|isbn=0-9614701-4-3|ref=refTheNewRealBookVol1}}\n*{{cite book | title=The New Real Book, Volume II | year=1991 | publisher=Sher Music | isbn=0-9614701-7-8|ref=refTheNewRealBookVol2}}\n*{{cite book|title=The New Real Book, Volume III|year=1995|publisher=Sher Music|isbn=1-883217-30-X|ref=refTheNewRealBookVol3}}\n*{{cite book | title=[[Real Book#History of the 'new' Real Book|The Real Book]], Volume I |edition=6th | year=2004 | publisher=Hal Leonard | isbn=0-634-06038-4|ref=refTheRealBookVol1}}\n*{{cite book | title=The Real Book, Volume II |edition=2nd | year=2007 | publisher=Hal Leonard | isbn=1-4234-2452-2|ref=refTheRealBookVol2}}\n*{{cite book | title=The Real Book, Volume III |edition=2nd | year=2006 | publisher=Hal Leonard | isbn=0-634-06136-4|ref=refTheRealBookVol3}}\n*{{cite book | title=The Real Jazz Book | publisher=Warner Bros | isbn=978-91-85041-36-7|ref=refTheRealJazzBook}}\n*{{cite book | title=[[Real Book#History of the 'new' Real Book|The Real Vocal Book]], Volume I | year=2006 | publisher=Hal Leonard | isbn=0-634-06080-5|ref=refTheRealVocalBookVol1}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/timeline_year.php?pg=49 History Of Jazz Timeline: 1943] at [[All About Jazz]]\n\n{{inc-musong}}\n{{Jazz}}\n\n[[Category:1943 in music|Jazz]]\n[[Category:Jazz by year]]\n", "text_old": "{{Year in music|1943}}\n{{Year in jazz\n |image      = Duke Ellington - Hurricane Ballroom - trio.jpg\n |caption    = A trio of musicians from Duke Ellington's orchestra during the early morning broadcast\n |prioryear  = 1942\n |afteryear  = 1944\n}}\n{{Year nav topic5|1943|jazz}}\n{{Dynamic list}}\nThis is a timeline documenting events of '''[[Jazz]] in the year 1943'''.\n\n==Events==\n* The [[American Federation of Musicians]] recording ban, called by [[James Petrillo]], continued through 1943. [[Django Reinhardt]] records \"[[Cavalerie]]\" on the 17 February 1943 in [[Paris]] after an aborted attempt at recording it in 1937.<ref name=\"Williams1998\">{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Patrick|title=Django Reinhardt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0qkgkaD1T4gC&pg=PA182|accessdate=11 February 2012|year=1998|publisher=Editions Parenth\u00e8ses|isbn=978-2-86364-612-0|page=182}}</ref>\n\n==Album releases==\n* [[Duke Ellington]]: ''[[Black, Brown and Beige]]'' (1943)\n\n==Standards==\n{{See also|List of 1940s jazz standards}}\n\n==Deaths==\n[[File:Fats Waller edit.jpg|thumb|[