{"title_page": "Tukums", "text_new": "{{for|the 1984 Danish film|Tukuma (film)}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Tukums\n| other_name = \n| settlement_type = Town\n| image_shield =Coat_of_Arms_of_Tukums.svg\n| shield_size = \n| image_flag =Flag_of_Tukums.svg\n| flag_size = \n| image_skyline = Tukums, luter\u00e1nsk\u00fd kostel.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| image_caption = Lutheran church in Tukums\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name = {{flag|Latvia}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Districts of Latvia|District]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Tukums Municipality]]\n| established_title = [[Town rights]]\n| established_date  = 1795\n| pushpin_map            = Latvia\n| pushpin_label_position = above\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Latvia\n| coordinates     = {{coord|56|58|N|23|09|E|region:LV_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| nickname = \n| leader_title = \n| leader_name = \n| blank_name_sec1 = \n| blank_info_sec1 = \n| area_total_km2  = \n| area_water_km2  = \n| area_land_km2   = \n| area_metro_km2  = \n| elevation_m     = \n| population_total = 19722\n| population_metro = \n| population_density_km2 = \n| population_density_metro_km2 = \n| postal_code_type = [[Postal code]]\n| postal_code = LV310(1\u20132); LV-3104\n| area_code_type = [[Telephone numbering plan|Calling code]]\n| area_code = +371 631\n| timezone1 = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| utc_offset1 = +2\n| timezone1_DST = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST = +3\n| webpage = http://www.tukums.lv/\n}}\n'''Tukums''' ({{audio|Lv-Tukums.ogg|pronunciation}}; {{lang-de|Tuckum}}; {{lang-liv|Tuk\u0101m\u014d}}) is a [[town]] in [[Latvia]]. Three regions of Latvia meet in the vicinity of Tukums \u2013 [[Vidzeme]], [[Zemgale]] and [[Courland]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe historical center of Tukums developed between trade routes leading from the mouth of the [[Daugava River]] to [[Prussia]]. The oldest part is today's Talsi Street that originated at the river named Zvirgzdupite where there used to be a castle mound with a wooden castle. Since 1253 Tukums was ruled by the [[Livonian Order]]. A masonry castle was built on the bank of the [[Slocene]] river in the end of the 13th century. The castle was surrounded by settlements of [[Germans|German]] tradesmen and craftsmen. A marketplace was formed in front of the castle and some new streets appeared later running in various directions from the market place.\n\nWith the development of trade in the 16th century a new straighter trade route to Prussia was built along a new street that is called Liela (large) Street today. This street had an important role in the life of the settlement. Public buildings, major business, workshops and shops were concentrated in it.\n\nAfter the disintegration of the Livonian Order a new state, the [[Duchy of Courland and Semigallia]] was established. Like many other settlements Tukums had suffered greatly the numerous feudal wars. Under the rule of [[Jacob Kettler|Duke Jacob]] (1642\u20131682) Tukums experienced a rapid economic boom. At the time a new trade route from Tukums to [[Jelgava]], the capital of Duchy of Courland and Semigallia, was opened along today's Jelgavas Street, and another route was made along today's Raudas Street towards it. A dam was built and a lake made near the road to Jelgava. A flour mill and a cooper furnace started functioning there, and cooper was exported to foreign countries. The town, inhabited by only 800 people was quite small. The new adornment of Tukums was the lake. The church spire was another landmark added to the skyline in 1687.\n\nAfter 1795 Courland was incorporated into the  [[Russian Empire]]. In November of the same year the [[Catherine II of Russia|Russian Tsaritsa Katherine]] signed a document to divide Courland into regions and to grant regional center rights to several urban settlements, Tukums being one of them.\n\nThe town borders were marked in 1800 and the first urban map was made only two years later. The town continued growing. It included 131 private houses, mostly wooden, and 6 pubs. There were 690 male and 832 female inhabitants. The first school was opened in 1806. Street pavement was introduced in 1860 and street lighting started in 1875. A more rapid development of the town was observed after the opening of the Riga-Tukums railway line in 1877 and of another line connecting Tukums with [[Ventspils]] a little later. 24 enterprises were functioning in Tukums in 1897: tanneries, wood carding-mills, a glue plant and also pottery and food production facilities. The two windmills brought out the uniqueness of the townscape.\n\nThe town grew with the development of industry. Two new districts appeared. The rich built their houses in the eastern part around Elizabetes, Pils and Baznicas Streets, but the workers settled more to the west, forming an area of small houses surrounded by gardens. This part of Tukums was further developed during the year in 1935. In the beginning of the 1930s there were 8000 inhabitants and 73 functioning industrial enterprises in Tukums.\n\n== Places near Tukums ==\n\nThe [[Engure parish]] by the city was host to the [[Soviet Navy]] [[Tukums air base]]. It was converted into a civilian airport.\n\n[[Jaunpils Castle]] is the only fortified castle of the [[Order of Livonia]] that remains in Latvia. It was built in 1301. An exhibition hall and museum are located there on the history of the district. Jaunpils Lutheran Church which was built in 1592 is located near the castle.\n\n[[Jaunmoka Castle|Jaunmoku Palace]] (1901), {{convert|5|km|0|abbr=on}} from Tukums, surrounded by the Courlands hills, hosts an exhibition on forestry. Jaunmoku Palace is a combination of [[Art Nouveau]] elements and [[Neo-Gothic]] forms and was built as the country residence of [[George Armitstead, 1st Baron Armitstead|George Armitstead]], mayor of Riga (1901\u201312).\n\n[[Durbe Manor|Durbe manor house]], ({{lang-lv|Durbes pils}}) rebuilt in 1820, is a classical style palace, surrounded by a landscaped park. A stone bridge across the ravine and a [[Rotunda (architecture)|rotunda]] are located near the manor house.\n\nThe Schlokenbeck estate ensemble in Milzkalne, dating from the 15th century, is the only fortified [[manor house]] in Latvia. A museum on the history of broad building techniques and an exposition of horse gear is set up there.\n\nIn Zante region there is the highest peak of Tukums district \u2013 Smiltinkalns (153m), in the center of Zante there is a Red Army tank, evidence of the battles in \"[[Courland Pocket]]\" in 1944\u20131945.\n\nThe country of Zentene and Seme has the northern landscape of Courland \u2013 hills, curved roads, objects of nature and places of culture history.\n\nThe seashore of Tukums district has a length of {{convert|50|km|0|abbr=on}}, where old fishermen's huts alternate with modern villas, and sandy beaches interchange with rocky shores and meadows.\n\n[[Kandava]] was the capital of the ancient Couronian state of Vanema. In the beginning of the 13th century, German knights built their castle there, though not much has been preserved from that time. In the Middle Ages, Kandava underwent numerous wars, fires and plague epidemics. \n\nThe Kandava hills are covered with dense forests and the [[Abava Rapids]] of the [[Abava River]]. Kandava marks the beginning of the run of the [[Abava Valley]], which is often locally referred to as \"Switzerland of Courland\" in as early as the 19th century. Since January 2011, the valley has been on Latvia's Tentative World Heritage List, according to World Monuments Fund. <ref name=\"mb.com.ph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wmf.org/project/abava-valley-cultural-landscape|title=Abava Valley has been on Latvia's Tentative World Heritage List, January 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=WMF.org|url-status=live|archiveurl=|archivedate=|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Places in Tukums ==\n\n=== Museums ===\n[[File:Durbes pils 19.gs.jpg|thumb|Durbe manor house in the 19th century.]]\n* Castle Tower of Tukums \u2013 Brivibas square 19a\n* Durbe Manor house \u2013 M.Parka street 7\n* Jaunmokas Palace Museum \u2013 Jaunmokas\n* Jaunpils Museum \u2013 Jaunpils\n* Pastari\u0146\u0161 Museum \u2013 Bisnieki, Zentene\n* [[\u0160lokenbeka Castle|\u0160lokenbeka Manor]] \u2013 Milzkalne\n* Tukums Museum \u2013 Harmonijas street 7\n\n==Notable people==\n[[File:Joe Magidsohn.jpg|thumb|right|170px|[[Joe Magidsohn]]]]\n*[[Ronalds Ar\u0101js]], Latvian athlete\n*[[Kristaps Blanks]], [[football (soccer)|football]] [[Striker (association football)|striker]], [[Skonto FC]] and Latvian national football team player\n*[[\u0100dolfs B\u013codnieks]], [[Prime Minister of Latvia]] from 1933 \u2013 1934\n*[[L\u012bga K\u013cavi\u0146a]], Latvian heptathlete\n*[[Dainis K\u016bla]], [[javelin throw]]er and [[1980 Summer Olympics|1980 Olympic]] champion\n*[[Jevg\u0113\u0146ijs Kosma\u010dovs]], [[FK Ventspils]] and Latvian national football team midfielder\n*[[Joe Magidsohn]], Latvian-born football player\n*[[Janis Roze]], Latvian biologist and philosopher\n*[[James Richman]], Latvian-born investor and financier known for his investments in [[Facebook]], [[Uber]], and [[Tesla]]\n*[[Samanta T\u012bna]], Latvian singer of [[Russian]] descent \n* [https://lv.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C4%81rti%C5%86%C5%A1_Sta%C4%B7is M\u0101rti\u0146\u0161 Sta\u0137is], [[Parliamentary Secretary]] of the [[Ministry of Defense]]\n*[[Viktor Tsoi]], [[Soviet Rock]] band [[Kino (band)|Kino]] leader died near Tukums.\n*[[Bertram Zarins]], Latvian-born orthopedic surgeon at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] and [[Harvard University]]\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Latvia}}\n\nTukums is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Starptautisk\u0101 sadarb\u012bba|url=https://www.tukums.lv/lv/tukuma-novada-pasvaldiba-1/starptautiska-sadarbiba|website=tukums.lv|publisher=Tukums|language=lv|accessdate=2019-08-31}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Andrych\u00f3w]], Poland\n*{{flagicon|ISR}} [[Bnei Ayish]], Israel\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Chennevi\u00e8res-sur-Marne]], France\n*{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Izium]], Ukraine\n*{{flagicon|BLR}} [[Karelichy]], Belarus\n*{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Krasnogorsk, Moscow Oblast|Krasnogorsk]], Russia\n*{{flagicon|LTU}} [[Plung\u0117]], Lithuania\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Schee\u00dfel]], Germany\n*{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Tidaholm]], Sweden\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Newspapers ==\n* ''[[Neatkar\u012bg\u0101s Tukuma Zi\u0146as]]''\n* ''[[Tukuma Zi\u0146ot\u0101js]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://www.tukums.lv/lv/tukuma-novads/par-novadu Tukums City Official Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090729084138/http://www.turisms.tukums.lv/index/vietas?lang=3 Tukums Tourist Information Center]\n*[https://www.wmf.org/project/abava-valley-cultural-landscape World Monuments Fund]\n\n{{Cities and parishes of Tukums District}}\n{{Latvian regional cities}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tukums|*]]\n[[Category:Towns in Latvia]]\n[[Category:1795 establishments in Europe]]\n[[Category:Castles of the Teutonic Knights]]\n[[Category:Tuckum County]]\n[[Category:18th-century establishments in Latvia]]\n[[Category:Tukums Municipality]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the 1984 Danish film|Tukuma (film)}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Tukums\n| other_name = \n| settlement_type = Town\n| image_shield =Coat_of_Arms_of_Tukums.svg\n| shield_size = \n| image_flag =Flag_of_Tukums.svg\n| flag_size = \n| image_skyline = Tukums, luter\u00e1nsk\u00fd kostel.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| image_caption = Lutheran church in Tukums\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name = {{flag|Latvia}}\n| subdivision_type1 = [[Districts of Latvia|District]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Tukums Municipality]]\n| established_title = [[Town rights]]\n| established_date  = 1795\n| pushpin_map            = Latvia\n| pushpin_label_position = above\n| pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Latvia\n| coordinates     = {{coord|56|58|N|23|09|E|region:LV_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n| nickname = \n| leader_title = \n| leader_name = \n| blank_name_sec1 = \n| blank_info_sec1 = \n| area_total_km2  = \n| area_water_km2  = \n| area_land_km2   = \n| area_metro_km2  = \n| elevation_m     = \n| population_total = 19722\n| population_metro = \n| population_density_km2 = \n| population_density_metro_km2 = \n| postal_code_type = [[Postal code]]\n| postal_code = LV310(1\u20132); LV-3104\n| area_code_type = [[Telephone numbering plan|Calling code]]\n| area_code = +371 631\n| timezone1 = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| utc_offset1 = +2\n| timezone1_DST = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n| utc_offset1_DST = +3\n| webpage = http://www.tukums.lv/\n}}\n'''Tukums''' ({{audio|Lv-Tukums.ogg|pronunciation}}; {{lang-de|Tuckum}}; {{lang-liv|Tuk\u0101m\u014d}}) is a [[town]] in [[Latvia]]. Three regions of Latvia meet in the vicinity of Tukums \u2013 [[Vidzeme]], [[Zemgale]] and [[Courland]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe historical center of Tukums developed between trade routes leading from the mouth of the [[Daugava River]] to [[Prussia]]. The oldest part is today's Talsi Street that originated at the river named Zvirgzdupite where there used to be a castle mound with a wooden castle. Since 1253 Tukums was ruled by the [[Livonian Order]]. A masonry castle was built on the bank of the [[Slocene]] river in the end of the 13th century. The castle was surrounded by settlements of [[Germans|German]] tradesmen and craftsmen. A marketplace was formed in front of the castle and some new streets appeared later running in various directions from the market place.\n\nWith the development of trade in the 16th century a new straighter trade route to Prussia was built along a new street that is called Liela (large) Street today. This street had an important role in the life of the settlement. Public buildings, major business, workshops and shops were concentrated in it.\n\nAfter the disintegration of the Livonian Order a new state, the [[Duchy of Courland and Semigallia]] was established. Like many other settlements Tukums had suffered greatly the numerous feudal wars. Under the rule of [[Jacob Kettler|Duke Jacob]] (1642\u20131682) Tukums experienced a rapid economic boom. At the time a new trade route from Tukums to [[Jelgava]], the capital of Duchy of Courland and Semigallia, was opened along today's Jelgavas Street, and another route was made along today's Raudas Street towards it. A dam was built and a lake made near the road to Jelgava. A flour mill and a cooper furnace started functioning there, and cooper was exported to foreign countries. The town, inhabited by only 800 people was quite small. The new adornment of Tukums was the lake. The church spire was another landmark added to the skyline in 1687.\n\nAfter 1795 Courland was incorporated into the  [[Russian Empire]]. In November of the same year the [[Catherine II of Russia|Russian Tsaritsa Katherine]] signed a document to divide Courland into regions and to grant regional center rights to several urban settlements, Tukums being one of them.\n\nThe town borders were marked in 1800 and the first urban map was made only two years later. The town continued growing. It included 131 private houses, mostly wooden, and 6 pubs. There were 690 male and 832 female inhabitants. The first school was opened in 1806. Street pavement was introduced in 1860 and street lighting started in 1875. A more rapid development of the town was observed after the opening of the Riga-Tukums railway line in 1877 and of another line connecting Tukums with [[Ventspils]] a little later. 24 enterprises were functioning in Tukums in 1897: tanneries, wood carding-mills, a glue plant and also pottery and food production facilities. The two windmills brought out the uniqueness of the townscape.\n\nThe town grew with the development of industry. Two new districts appeared. The rich built their houses in the eastern part around Elizabetes, Pils and Baznicas Streets, but the workers settled more to the west, forming an area of small houses surrounded by gardens. This part of Tukums was further developed during the year in 1935. In the beginning of the 1930s there were 8000 inhabitants and 73 functioning industrial enterprises in Tukums.\n\n== Places near Tukums ==\n\nThe [[Engure parish]] by the city was host to the [[Soviet Navy]] [[Tukums air base]]. It was converted into a civilian airport.\n\n[[Jaunpils Castle]] is the only fortified castle of the [[Order of Livonia]] that remains in Latvia. It was built in 1301. An exhibition hall and museum are located there on the history of the district. Jaunpils Lutheran Church which was built in 1592 is located near the castle.\n\n[[Jaunmoka Castle|Jaunmoku Palace]] (1901), {{convert|5|km|0|abbr=on}} from Tukums, surrounded by the Courlands hills, hosts an exhibition on forestry. Jaunmoku Palace is a combination of [[Art Nouveau]] elements and [[Neo-Gothic]] forms and was built as the country residence of [[George Armitstead, 1st Baron Armitstead|George Armitstead]], mayor of Riga (1901\u201312).\n\n[[Durbe Manor|Durbe manor house]], ({{lang-lv|Durbes pils}}) rebuilt in 1820, is a classical style palace, surrounded by a landscaped park. A stone bridge across the ravine and a [[Rotunda (architecture)|rotunda]] are located near the manor house.\n\nThe Schlokenbeck estate ensemble in Milzkalne, dating from the 15th century, is the only fortified [[manor house]] in Latvia. A museum on the history of broad building techniques and an exposition of horse gear is set up there.\n\nIn Zante region there is the highest peak of Tukums district \u2013 Smiltinkalns (153m), in the center of Zante there is a Red Army tank, evidence of the battles in \"[[Courland Pocket]]\" in 1944\u20131945.\n\nThe country of Zentene and Seme has the northern landscape of Courland \u2013 hills, curved roads, objects of nature and places of culture history.\n\nThe seashore of Tukums district has a length of {{convert|50|km|0|abbr=on}}, where old fishermen's huts alternate with modern villas, and sandy beaches interchange with rocky shores and meadows.\n\n[[Kandava]] was the capital of the ancient Couronian state of Vanema. In the beginning of the 13th century, German knights built their castle there, though not much has been preserved from that time. In the Middle Ages, Kandava underwent numerous wars, fires and plague epidemics. \n\nThe Kandava hills are covered with dense forests and the [[Abava Rapids]] of the [[Abava River]]. Kandava marks the beginning of the run of the [[Abava Valley]], which is often locally referred to as \"Switzerland of Courland\" in as early as the 19th century. Since January 2011, the valley has been on Latvia's Tentative World Heritage List, according to World Monuments Fund. <ref name=\"mb.com.ph\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wmf.org/project/abava-valley-cultural-landscape|title=Abava Valley has been on Latvia's Tentative World Heritage List, January 2011|last=|first=|date=|website=WMF.org|url-status=live|archiveurl=|archivedate=|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Places in Tukums ==\n\n=== Museums ===\n[[File:Durbes pils 19.gs.jpg|thumb|Durbe manor house in the 19th century.]]\n* Castle Tower of Tukums \u2013 Brivibas square 19a\n* Durbe Manor house \u2013 M.Parka street 7\n* Jaunmokas Palace Museum \u2013 Jaunmokas\n* Jaunpils Museum \u2013 Jaunpils\n* Pastari\u0146\u0161 Museum \u2013 Bisnieki, Zentene\n* [[\u0160lokenbeka Castle|\u0160lokenbeka Manor]] \u2013 Milzkalne\n* Tukums Museum \u2013 Harmonijas street 7\n\n==Notable people==\n[[File:Joe Magidsohn.jpg|thumb|right|170px|[[Joe Magidsohn]]]]\n*[[Ronalds Ar\u0101js]], Latvian athlete\n*[[Kristaps Blanks]], [[football (soccer)|football]] [[Striker (association football)|striker]], [[Skonto FC]] and Latvian national football team player\n*[[\u0100dolfs B\u013codnieks]], [[Prime Minister of Latvia]] from 1933 \u2013 1934\n*[[L\u012bga K\u013cavi\u0146a]], Latvian heptathlete\n*[[Dainis K\u016bla]], [[javelin throw]]er and [[1980 Summer Olympics|1980 Olympic]] champion\n*[[Jevg\u0113\u0146ijs Kosma\u010dovs]], [[FK Ventspils]] and Latvian national football team midfielder\n*[[Joe Magidsohn]], Latvian-born football player\n*[[Janis Roze]], Latvian biologist and philosopher\n*[[James Richman]], investor and financier known for his investments in [[Facebook]], [[Uber]], and [[Tesla]]\n*[[Samanta T\u012bna]], Latvian singer of [[Russian]] descent \n* [https://lv.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C4%81rti%C5%86%C5%A1_Sta%C4%B7is M\u0101rti\u0146\u0161 Sta\u0137is], [[Parliamentary Secretary]] of the [[Ministry of Defense]]\n*[[Viktor Tsoi]], [[Soviet Rock]] band [[Kino (band)|Kino]] leader died near Tukums.\n*[[Bertram Zarins]], Latvian-born orthopedic surgeon at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] and [[Harvard University]]\n\n==Twin towns \u2014 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Latvia}}\n\nTukums is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=Starptautisk\u0101 sadarb\u012bba|url=https://www.tukums.lv/lv/tukuma-novada-pasvaldiba-1/starptautiska-sadarbiba|website=tukums.lv|publisher=Tukums|language=lv|accessdate=2019-08-31}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Andrych\u00f3w]], Poland\n*{{flagicon|ISR}} [[Bnei Ayish]], Israel\n*{{flagicon|FRA}} [[Chennevi\u00e8res-sur-Marne]], France\n*{{flagicon|UKR}} [[Izium]], Ukraine\n*{{flagicon|BLR}} [[Karelichy]], Belarus\n*{{flagicon|RUS}} [[Krasnogorsk, Moscow Oblast|Krasnogorsk]], Russia\n*{{flagicon|LTU}} [[Plung\u0117]], Lithuania\n*{{flagicon|GER}} [[Schee\u00dfel]], Germany\n*{{flagicon|SWE}} [[Tidaholm]], Sweden\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Newspapers ==\n* ''[[Neatkar\u012bg\u0101s Tukuma Zi\u0146as]]''\n* ''[[Tukuma Zi\u0146ot\u0101js]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[https://www.tukums.lv/lv/tukuma-novads/par-novadu Tukums City Official Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090729084138/http://www.turisms.tukums.lv/index/vietas?lang=3 Tukums Tourist Information Center]\n*[https://www.wmf.org/project/abava-valley-cultural-landscape World Monuments Fund]\n\n{{Cities and parishes of Tukums District}}\n{{Latvian regional cities}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Tukums|*]]\n[[Category:Towns in Latvia]]\n[[Category:1795 establishments in Europe]]\n[[Category:Castles of the Teutonic Knights]]\n[[Category:Tuckum County]]\n[[Category:18th-century establishments in Latvia]]\n[[Category:Tukums Municipality]]\n", "name_user": "Infogapp1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable people", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tukums"}
{"title_page": "Gracen Hirschy", "text_new": "{{short description|American ice hockey forward}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1995|4|4|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Fort Wayne, Indiana]], [[United States of America]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_cm = 175\n| weight_lb = \n| position = Defence \n| shoots = Left\n| team = [[Modo Hockey]]\n| league = [[SDHL]]\n| played_for = [[Leksands IF]]<br>[[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]]<br>[[University of North Dakota]]\n| sex = f\n| ntl_team = United States\n| draft = \n| draft_year = \n| draft_team = \n| career_start = 2017\n| career_end = \n}}\n\n'''Gracen Hirschy''' is an American [[ice hockey]] defender, currently playing for [[Modo Hockey]] of the SDHL.\n\n== Career == \n\nHirschy scored 66 points in 145 NCAA games for the University of North Dakota, being named an alternate captain in her final year.<ref>https://www.uscho.com/2013/11/21/krzyzaniak-and-hirschy-help-transform-north-dakota-blue-line-from-weakness-to-strength/</ref> She was named to the WHCA All-Rookie Team in her first year.<ref>https://athletics.aurora.edu/news/2018/3/2/womens-hockey-assistant-signs-pro-contract.aspx</ref>\n\nAfter graduating, Hirschy signed with [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]] in Sweden, getting 3 points in 5 games. The next year, she decided to stay in Sweden, and signed for [[Leksands IF]]<ref>https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/2/17/18227899/q-a-with-leksands-ifs-gracen-hirschy-sdhl-womens-hockey-indiana-native</ref> She put up 19 points in 34 games for Leksands, before leaving for Modo for the 2019-20 season.<ref>https://hockeysverige.se/2019/06/07/annu-en-tung-pjas-lamnar-leksand-konkurrent</ref> For Modo, she scored another 19 points in 35 games, as the team finished last in the SDHL. She was suspended for one game following a collision with a referee.<ref>https://www.svt.se/sport/ishockey/modospelaren-stangs-av-korde-pa-domaren</ref>\n\n=== International ===   \n\nIn 2013, Hirschy played in the U18 Women\u2019s World Championship for the American national team, winning a silver medal.<ref>https://news.culver.org/cga-grad-hirschy-selected-for-u-s-hockey-festival/</ref><ref>https://teamusa.usahockey.com/page/show/2875753-gracen-hirschy</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\n\nHirschy has a degree in political science.<ref>https://www.journalgazette.net/sports/rec/-The-NHL-for-women--8955218</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* Biographical information and career statistics from [https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/366324/gracen-hirschy Elite Prospects]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Modo Hockey players]]\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Wayne, Indiana]]\n[[Category:American ice hockey players]]\n\n{{US-icehockey-player-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American ice hockey forward}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| image = \n| caption = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1995|4|4|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Fort Wayne, Indianna]], [[United States of America]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| height_cm = 175\n| weight_lb = \n| position = Defence \n| shoots = Left\n| team = [[Modo Hockey]]\n| league = [[SDHL]]\n| played_for = [[Leksands IF]]<br>[[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]]<br>[[University of North Dakota]]\n| sex = f\n| ntl_team = United States\n| draft = \n| draft_year = \n| draft_team = \n| career_start = 2017\n| career_end = \n}}\n\n'''Gracen Hirschy''' is an American [[ice hockey]] defender, currently playing for [[Modo Hockey]] of the SDHL.\n\n== Career == \n\nHirschy scored 66 points in 145 NCAA games for the University of North Dakota, being named an alternate captain in her final year.<ref>https://www.uscho.com/2013/11/21/krzyzaniak-and-hirschy-help-transform-north-dakota-blue-line-from-weakness-to-strength/</ref> She was named to the WHCA All-Rookie Team in her first year.<ref>https://athletics.aurora.edu/news/2018/3/2/womens-hockey-assistant-signs-pro-contract.aspx</ref>\n\nAfter graduating, Hirschy signed with [[Djurg\u00e5rdens IF]] in Sweden, getting 3 points in 5 games. The next year, she decided to stay in Sweden, and signed for [[Leksands IF]]<ref>https://www.theicegarden.com/2019/2/17/18227899/q-a-with-leksands-ifs-gracen-hirschy-sdhl-womens-hockey-indiana-native</ref> She put up 19 points in 34 games for Leksands, before leaving for Modo for the 2019-20 season.<ref>https://hockeysverige.se/2019/06/07/annu-en-tung-pjas-lamnar-leksand-konkurrent</ref> For Modo, she scored another 19 points in 35 games, as the team finished last in the SDHL. She was suspended for one game following a collision with a referee.<ref>https://www.svt.se/sport/ishockey/modospelaren-stangs-av-korde-pa-domaren</ref>\n\n=== International ===   \n\nIn 2013, Hirschy played in the U18 Women\u2019s World Championship for the American national team, winning a silver medal.<ref>https://news.culver.org/cga-grad-hirschy-selected-for-u-s-hockey-festival/</ref><ref>https://teamusa.usahockey.com/page/show/2875753-gracen-hirschy</ref>\n\n== Personal Life ==\n\nHirschy has a degree in political science.<ref>https://www.journalgazette.net/sports/rec/-The-NHL-for-women--8955218</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* Biographical information and career statistics from [https://www.eliteprospects.com/player/366324/gracen-hirschy Elite Prospects]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Modo Hockey players]]\n[[Category:1995 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Fort Wayne, Indianna]]\n[[Category:American ice hockey players]]\n\n{{US-icehockey-player-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Shirt58", "label": "safe", "comment": "\"Fort Wayne, Indianna\" -> \"Fort Wayne, Indiana\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gracen_Hirschy"}
{"title_page": "YES Snowboards", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:YES. Snowboards}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = YES. Snowboards Inc.\n| logo = YES-Snowboards-logo.jpg\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| foundation = 2009\n| location = [[Switzerland]]\n| key_people = Romain De Marchi, JP Solberg, DCP\n| num_employees = 20\n| industry = [[Sporting goods]]\n| products = Snowboard equipment, apparel, accessories\n| revenue = \n| homepage = http://www.yesnowboard.com/\n}}\n\n'''YES. Snowboards''' is manufacturer of [[snowboard]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://whitelines.com/brands/yes-snowboards#l1Ctji8Rac5VXcmp.97 |title=Yes Snowboards |website=whitelines.com}}</ref><ref>http://www.kink.se/2008/12/18/new-snowboard-company-yes-we-can/</ref> It was founded in 2009 and is based in [[Europe]].<ref name=BT>http://www.grindtv.com/transworld-business/news/yes-snowboards-launches-at-sia/ Archive link [https://web.archive.org/web/20120312080805/http://business.transworld.net/12759/features/yes-snowboards-launches-at-sia/]</ref><ref name=\"Nidecker\" />\n\n==History==\nThe company was founded by Un...Inc riders DCP ([[David Carrier Porcheron|David Carrier-Porcheron]]), Romain De Marchi, JP Solberg and Tadashi Fuse who were fired from [[Burton Snowboards]] and created their own brand in collaboration with [[Nidecker]].<ref name=\"Nidecker\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nidecker.com/history/ |title=Nidecker History |website=Nidecker.com}}</ref><ref name=BT/> The new company established its name in the industry in a relatively short period of time.\n\n==Models==\nAll YES. models were manufactured in the GST factory in [[Austria]] before gradually moving production to the SWS factory in [[Dubai]] starting in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.yesnowboard.com/why-wouldnt-you-make-snowboards-in-dubai/ |title=Why wouldn\u2019t you make snowboards in Dubai? |website=Yes Snowboards |publication-date=12 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331162012/http://www.yesnowboard.com/why-wouldnt-you-make-snowboards-in-dubai/ |archive-date=31 March 2015}}</ref> The GST factory closed in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mtnweekly.com/sports/snowboarding/gst-is-closing-their-factory-does-it-matter-to-snowboarding |title=GST Snowboard Manufacturing is Closing, Does it Matter? |date=19 March 2015 |website=[[Mountain Weekly News]]}}</ref> The YES. designers receive R&D input of some top-level freestyle snowboarders. The 2016-17 catalog consists of fourteen models<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://whitelines.com/snowboard-gear/news-previews/yes-snowboards-2016-2017-preview-ispo-2016.html#q9ZQBrqiKUqxzfTO.97 |title=YES Snowboards 2016-2017 Preview \u2013 ISPO 2016 |website=Whitelines.com |publication-date=27 January 2016}}</ref>, which grew to twenty for 2019-20<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yesnowboard.com/|title=Yes. Snowboards|last=Snowboards|first=Yes|website=Yes. Snowboards|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>. Current (2019/20) collaborations exist with Now Snowboarding on bindings, and [[Globe International]] on shoes. \n\n==Awards==\n*EUROSima's Breakthrough Brand of the Year 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://snowboarding.transworld.net/news/yes-is-awarded-eurosimas-breakthrough-brand-of-the-year/ |title=YES is awarded EUROSima\u2019s Breakthrough Brand of the Year |website=Snowboarding.transworld.net |publication-date=24 June 2010}}</ref>\n*ISPO Award \"Gold Award\" for the 20/20 Powderhull, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ispo.com/en/products/id_76469282/yes-20-20-snowboard-simply-unbeatable-for-tricks-on-powder-.html|title=ISPO Award 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=Ispo.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.yesnowboard.com/\n\n[[Category:Snowboarding companies]]\n\n\n{{snowboarding-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = YES. Snowboards Inc.\n| logo = YES-Snowboards-logo.jpg\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| foundation = 2009\n| location = [[Switzerland]]\n| key_people = Romain De Marchi, JP Solberg, DCP\n| num_employees = 20\n| industry = [[Sporting goods]]\n| products = Snowboard equipment, apparel, accessories\n| revenue = \n| homepage = http://www.yesnowboard.com/\n}}\n\n'''YES. Snowboards''' is manufacturer of [[snowboard]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://whitelines.com/brands/yes-snowboards#l1Ctji8Rac5VXcmp.97 |title=Yes Snowboards |website=whitelines.com}}</ref><ref>http://www.kink.se/2008/12/18/new-snowboard-company-yes-we-can/</ref> It was founded in 2009 and is based in [[Europe]].<ref name=BT>http://www.grindtv.com/transworld-business/news/yes-snowboards-launches-at-sia/ Archive link [https://web.archive.org/web/20120312080805/http://business.transworld.net/12759/features/yes-snowboards-launches-at-sia/]</ref><ref name=\"Nidecker\" />\n\n==History==\nThe company was founded by Un...Inc riders DCP ([[David Carrier Porcheron|David Carrier-Porcheron]]), Romain De Marchi, JP Solberg and Tadashi Fuse who were fired from [[Burton Snowboards]] and created their own brand in collaboration with [[Nidecker]].<ref name=\"Nidecker\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nidecker.com/history/ |title=Nidecker History |website=Nidecker.com}}</ref><ref name=BT/> The new company established its name in the industry in a relatively short period of time.\n\n==Models==\nAll YES. models were manufactured in the GST factory in [[Austria]] before gradually moving production to the SWS factory in [[Dubai]] starting in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.yesnowboard.com/why-wouldnt-you-make-snowboards-in-dubai/ |title=Why wouldn\u2019t you make snowboards in Dubai? |website=Yes Snowboards |publication-date=12 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150331162012/http://www.yesnowboard.com/why-wouldnt-you-make-snowboards-in-dubai/ |archive-date=31 March 2015}}</ref> The GST factory closed in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mtnweekly.com/sports/snowboarding/gst-is-closing-their-factory-does-it-matter-to-snowboarding |title=GST Snowboard Manufacturing is Closing, Does it Matter? |date=19 March 2015 |website=[[Mountain Weekly News]]}}</ref> The YES. designers receive R&D input of some top-level freestyle snowboarders. The 2016-17 catalog consists of fourteen models<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://whitelines.com/snowboard-gear/news-previews/yes-snowboards-2016-2017-preview-ispo-2016.html#q9ZQBrqiKUqxzfTO.97 |title=YES Snowboards 2016-2017 Preview \u2013 ISPO 2016 |website=Whitelines.com |publication-date=27 January 2016}}</ref>, which grew to twenty for 2019-20<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yesnowboard.com/|title=Yes. Snowboards|last=Snowboards|first=Yes|website=Yes. Snowboards|language=en|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>. Current (2019/20) collaborations exist with Now Snowboarding on bindings, and [[Globe International]] on shoes. \n\n==Awards==\n*EUROSima's Breakthrough Brand of the Year 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://snowboarding.transworld.net/news/yes-is-awarded-eurosimas-breakthrough-brand-of-the-year/ |title=YES is awarded EUROSima\u2019s Breakthrough Brand of the Year |website=Snowboarding.transworld.net |publication-date=24 June 2010}}</ref>\n*ISPO Award \"Gold Award\" for the 20/20 Powderhull, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ispo.com/en/products/id_76469282/yes-20-20-snowboard-simply-unbeatable-for-tricks-on-powder-.html|title=ISPO Award 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=Ispo.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-11}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.yesnowboard.com/\n\n[[Category:Snowboarding companies]]\n\n\n{{snowboarding-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tomw n", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added dot to title.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YES_Snowboards"}
{"title_page": "Appomattox, Virginia", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name      = Appomattox, Virginia\n|official_name      = Town of Appomattox\n|settlement_type     = [[Town]]\n|nickname         = \n|motto          = \n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline      = Appomattox Court House, VA, Theater IMG_4179.JPG\n|imagesize        = \n|image_caption      = The Appomattox Theater in July 2011.\n|image_flag        = \n|image_seal        = \n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map        = \n|mapsize         = 250px\n|map_caption       = Location in Virginia\n| pushpin_map             = Virginia#USA\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location of Appomattox\n| pushpin_label = Appomattox\n| pushpin_label_position  = bottom\n\n<!-- Location -->\n| subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name     = {{nowrap|{{USA}}}}\n|subdivision_type1    = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1    = {{flag|Virginia|size=23px}}\n|subdivision_type2    = [[List of counties in Virginia|County]]\n|subdivision_name2    = {{flagicon image|Flag of Appomattox County, Virginia.png|size=23px}} [[Appomattox County, Virginia|Appomattox]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes   = \n|government_type     = \n|leader_title       = \n|leader_name       = \n|leader_title1      = \n|leader_name1       = \n|established_title    = \n|established_date     = \n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n|area_footnotes      = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2018 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_51.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Feb 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude      = \n|area_total_sq_mi     = 2.31\n|area_land_sq_mi     = 2.31\n|area_water_sq_mi     = 0.01\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of     = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes   = \n|population_total     = 1733\n|population_density_sq_mi = 777.44\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone         = [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n| utc_offset = &minus;5\n|timezone_DST       = EDT\n| utc_offset_DST = &minus;4\n|elevation_footnotes   = \n|elevation_m       = 259\n|elevation_ft       = 850\n|coordinates       = {{coord|37|21|32|N|78|49|35|W|region:US-VA_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type     = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code       = 24522\n|area_code        = [[Area code 434|434]]\n|blank_name        = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info        = 51-02072<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 12, 2020 |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=January 31, 2008 |title=American FactFinder |df=mdy }}</ref>\n|blank1_name       = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info       = 1498448<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=January 31, 2008|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=October 25, 2007}}</ref>\n|website         = {{URL|https://townofappomattox.com/}}\n|footnotes        = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n|population_est = 1792\n|area_total_km2 = 5.99\n|area_land_km2 = 5.97\n|area_water_km2 = 0.02\n|population_density_km2 = 300.14\n}}\n'''Appomattox''' is a town in [[Appomattox County, Virginia|Appomattox County]], [[Virginia]], [[United States]]. The population was 1,733 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. It is the [[county seat]] of [[Appomattox County, Virginia|Appomattox County]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=May 31, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n\nAppomattox is part of the [[Lynchburg, Virginia|Lynchburg]] [[Lynchburg metropolitan area|Metropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Appomattox, VA, Visitor Center IMG_4184.JPG|left|thumb|upright|The Appomattox Visitor Center in July 2011]]\nThe town was named for the [[Appomattox River]]. The river was named after the [[Appomattoc]] Native American tribe, one of the [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]]-speaking [[Powhatan Confederacy]], historically based in the coastal area and encountered by the English before the tribes of the [[Piedmont (United States)|Piedmont]]. The Appamatuck historically lived somewhat to the east of the present town, around the area of present-day Petersburg. At the time of European encounter, the area of Appomattox County above the [[Atlantic Seaboard fall line|Fall Line]] was part of the territory of the [[Manahoac]] tribe, who spoke a [[Siouan]] language.\nThe town is located three miles west of the restored historic [[village]] of [[Appomattox Court House National Historical Park|Appomattox Court House]], the site of [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] General [[Robert E. Lee]]'s surrender to Union General [[Ulysses S. Grant]] on April 9, 1865, essentially [[Conclusion of the American Civil War|ending the American Civil War]]. The area is preserved as [[Appomattox Court House National Historical Park]] and is administered by the [[National Park Service]].\n\nAt the time of the Civil War, the present community of Appomattox was the site of a railroad [[railroad station|depot]] on the line between [[Petersburg, Virginia|Petersburg]] and [[Lynchburg, Virginia|Lynchburg]], a stop on the [[Southside Railroad (Virginia)|Southside Railroad]].<ref Name=Bright2015>{{cite web |url=http://www.csa-railroads.com/South_Side.htm |title=Confederate Railroads - South Side|last=Bright |first=David L. |date=2015 |website=Confederate Railroads |publisher= |access-date=2018-01-25 |quote=}}</ref>  The town was first named \"Nebraska\" in 1855. In 1895 it was renamed \"West Appomattox\". The first postmaster of \"Nebraska, Virginia\", was [[Samuel D. McDearmon]].<ref name=\"appomattox1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.appomattoxhistory.org/clover-hill.htm |title=Appomattox town history |accessdate=January 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503195436/http://www.appomattoxhistory.org/clover-hill.htm |archivedate=May 3, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nNear the end of the Civil War, [[Robert E. Lee]] made a last attempt to reach the depot, hoping to transport the [[Army of Northern Virginia]] south by railroad to meet [[Joseph E. Johnston]]'s larger [[Confederate Army of Tennessee|Army of Tennessee]], then located in Greensboro, North Carolina. The arrival of Federal troops and their blocking Lee's army from the depot led to Lee's surrender in the home of [[Wilmer McLean]], on April 9. Johnston later surrendered 98,270 Confederate troops (the largest surrender of the war), marking the end of the conflict on April 26, 1865. Small bands of soldiers continued fighting until June 1865.\n\nThough President Lincoln had issued the Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, slaves in the southern states were not freed until the surrender at Appomattox Court House on April 9.  Though the last of the slaves weren't freed until June 19, the surrender at Appomattox is the event that would hammer the final nail in slavery's coffin.  Today, each April, the Appomattox Court House National Historical Park commemorates this event with a luminary ceremony, wherein a lantern is lit for each of the 4,600 slaves freed in Appomattox County alone.\n\nThe railroad became the [[Atlantic, Mississippi and Ohio Railroad]] in 1870. The inconvenience of the railroad's location to the original Appomattox Court House in the village of Clover Hill led to the decline of the courthouse community. After [[fire]] destroyed the courthouse building in 1892, the county relocated the court to the depot area, which formally became the [[county seat]] in 1894. The railroad became a line in the [[Norfolk and Western Railway]] and then the [[Norfolk Southern Railway]].\n\nIn 1990, there were 11,971 residents reported for Appomattox County; the Town of Appomattox had 1703 residents.\n\nIn addition to Appomattox Court House National Historical Park, the [[Appomattox River Bridge]], [[Appomattox Historic District]], [[Holiday Lake 4-H Educational Center]], and [[Holliday Lake State Park]] are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n\nThe [[2010 Appomattox shootings]] occurred from January 17 to 20 and left eight people dead.\n\n==Geography==\nAppomattox is located at {{coord|37|21|32|N|78|49|35|W|type:city}} (37.358973, &minus;78.826438).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=April 23, 2011|date=February 12, 2011|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of 2.2&nbsp;square miles (5.6&nbsp;km\u00b2).\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1930= 704\n|1940= 992\n|1950= 1094\n|1960= 1184\n|1970= 1400\n|1980= 1345\n|1990= 1707\n|2000= 1761\n|2010= 1733\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=1792\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015|df=mdy }}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 1,761 people, 716 households, and 469 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was 808.7 people per square mile (311.9/km\u00b2). There were 767 housing units at an average density of 352.2/sq&nbsp;mi (135.8/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the town was 66.89% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 32.14% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.28% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.11% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.57% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.23% of the population.\n\nThere were 716 households out of which 29.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 42.7% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 20.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.4% were non-families. 30.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 17.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.35 and the average family size was 2.92.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 23.9% under the age of 18, 8.6% from 18 to 24, 27.4% from 25 to 44, 20.8% from 45 to 64, and 19.2% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 39 years. For every 100 females, there were 82.3 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 75.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $24,167, and the median income for a family was $29,188. Males had a median income of $26,515 versus $20,732 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $14,355. About 20.9% of families and 18.4% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 26.4% of those under age 18 and 22.9% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Watkins Abbitt Jr.]], member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/5120/watkins-abbitt-jr#.UJa7WsU5Y1M|title= Abbitt, Watkins Moorman (1908-1998) |publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate =November 4, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Larry Robinson (American football)|Larry Robinson]], former [[NFL]] player<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/5120/watkins-abbitt-jr#.UJa7WsU5Y1M|title= Larry Robinson |publisher=pro-football-reference.com |accessdate=October 10, 2015}}</ref>\n*Adam Dillon, a popular creator on TikTok<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.tiktok.com/h5/share/usr/6545496062702141445.html?language=en&sec_uid=MS4wLjABAAAAx_2wCzU9ybe54VVziIydrMcJUx3nB1d27ugSg5pJr-8d43dSUyu6yryTfYu4pZdC&u_code=d973lgi42ahe6h&timestamp=1586347946&user_id=6756537411977839621&utm_source=copy&utm_campaign=client_share&utm_medium=android&share_app_name=musically&share_iid=6813233532246394630|title=Adam on TikTok|website=TikTok|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nThe climate in this area is characterized by hot, humid summers and generally mild to cool winters. According to the [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] system, Appomattox has a [[humid subtropical climate]], abbreviated \"Cfa\" on climate maps.<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=342044&cityname=Appomattox%2C+Virginia%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Appomattox, Virginia]</ref>\n\n<section begin=\"weather box\" />{{Weather box |location = Appomattox, Virginia (1981\u20132010 normals),{{efn|Mean monthly maxima and minima (i.e. the expected highest and lowest temperature readings at any point during the year or given month) calculated based on data at said location from 1981 to 2010.}} |single line = Y\n|collapsed = Y\n|Jan high F = 45.7\n|Feb high F = 50.2\n|Mar high F = 57.7\n|Apr high F = 68.3\n|May high F = 75.5\n|Jun high F = 83.4\n|Jul high F = 86.8\n|Aug high F = 85.5\n|Sep high F = 78.7\n|Oct high F = 69.3\n|Nov high F = 58.9\n|Dec high F = 4