/apco Appomattox Court House National Historical Park website]\n\n{{Appomattox County, Virginia}}\n{{Virginia towns}}\n{{Virginia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Towns in Appomattox County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:County seats in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Towns in Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "HWL12345", "label": "safe", "comment": "I added a notable person, Adam Dillon who had over 2.5 million followers on social media site Tiktok and is a social media personality. A page is currently being made about him.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Appomattox,_Virginia"}
{"title_page": "Rust (video game)", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}\n{{short description|Survival video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Rust\n| image = File:Rust vector logo.svg\n| developer = [[Facepunch Studios]]\n| publisher = Facepunch Studios\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = [[macOS]], [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| released = 8 February 2018\n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]], [[Survival game|survival]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n| director = \n| producer = \n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| composer = \n}}\n\n'''''Rust''''' is a [[multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]-only [[Survival game|survival]] [[video game]] developed by [[Facepunch Studios]]. Rust was first released in early access in December 2013 and received its full release in February 2018. ''Rust'' is available on [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[macOS]]. Console versions for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] have been announced for release in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/11/14/20965525/rust-ps4-xbox-one-release-dates-2020|title=Rust comes to PS4 and Xbox One next year|last=Good|first=Owen S.|date=14 November 2019|work=Polygon|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref> ''Rust'' was initially created as a [[Video game clone|clone]] of ''[[DayZ (mod)|DayZ]]'', a popular [[Mod (video gaming)|mod]] for ''[[ARMA 2]]'', with [[Glossary of video game terms#Crafting|crafting]] elements akin to those in ''[[Minecraft]]''.\n\nThe objective of ''Rust'' is to survive in the wilderness using gathered or stolen materials. Players must successfully manage their hunger, thirst, and health, or risk dying. Despite the looming threat of [[American black bears|bears]] and [[wolf|wolves]], the primary menace is other players due to the game being solely multiplayer. Combat is accomplished through [[firearm]]s and primitive weapons, such as [[Bow and arrow|bow]]s. In addition, vehicles controlled by [[non-player character]]s will occasionally roam, attacking heavily-armed players. These can be defeated with persistence. ''Rust'' features crafting, though initially limited until the discovery of specific items in the game's [[open world]]. To stay protected, players must build [[Military base|base]]s or join [[Clan (computer gaming)|clan]]s to improve their chance of survival. [[Raid (gaming)|Raiding]] is a major aspect of ''Rust'' and is done more frequently by large clans.\n\n''Rust'' was first released in December 2013 to the [[Steam Early Access]] program; this early access state is now known as Rust Legacy. Further into its development, the gameplay was changed significantly. Dangerous wildlife replaced zombies as the primary environmental threat and several fundamental revisions to the crafting system were released. 2014 saw the game ported to the [[Unity 5]] [[game engine]], providing substantial graphical changes. Around this time, ''Rust'' introduced immutable, predetermined [[Race (human categorization)|skin colour]] and [[biological sex]] tied to players' [[Steam (website)|Steam]] account details. Despite being fully released, the game continues to receive updates.\n\nThroughout ''Rust''{{'}}s alpha release, critical reviews were mixed, with many comparisons made to other survival games. ''Rust'' was commonly explained as being a mixture of ''[[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]]'' and ''[[Minecraft]]''. During this period, reviewers frequently noted the game's unfinished nature. During its pre-release phase, critics praised the concept and gameplay and by March 2017, ''Rust'' had sold over five million copies. After leaving Early Access, it received mixed reviews from critics. The [[player vs player]] combat and survival aspects were highlighted by those who enjoyed the game, though reviewers were critical of the constant need to [[Grinding (gaming)|grind]] for materials, along with the harsh beginner experience.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Collecting wood in Rust.jpeg|right|thumb|280px|A player using the starting rock to gather wood]]\nAs a [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]-only video game,<ref name=\"5MC\">{{cite web|title = 5 Video Games to Play if You Like \u2018Minecraft\u2019|url = http://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/5-video-games-to-play-if-you-like-minecraft.html/4/|accessdate = 1 July 2015|website = CheatSheet|first = Chris|date = 30 June 2015|last = Reed|page = 4|url-status = live|archivedate = 21 September 2016|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921085950/http://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/5-video-games-to-play-if-you-like-minecraft.html/4/|df = dmy-all}}</ref> ''Rust'' puts players against each other in a harsh, [[open world]] environment with the sole goal of survival. Animals, such as wolves and bears, act as a looming threat, but the primary danger comes from other players.<ref name=\"5MC\"/> Most maps are [[procedurally generated]],<ref name=\"rpsnov2014\"/> with the exception of Hapis Island, a pre-built map.<ref name=\"pcgamertrad\"/> [[Player versus player|Player vs player]] (PvP) combat is accomplished with [[Bow and arrow|bow]]s, melee weapons and craftable guns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/03/28/rust-diary/|title=To Hell With Other People: Nine Lives in Rust|access-date=22 October 2016|archivedate=22 October 2016|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=28 March 2014 |first=Brendan |last=Caldwell |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022050252/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/03/28/rust-diary/ |url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bullets and other projectiles travel in a [[Ballistics|ballistic]] trajectory, rather than being [[hitscan]].<ref name=\"pcgamertrad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/a-new-rust-update-promises-to-make-the-gunplay-feel-more-like-a-traditional-fps/|title=A new Rust update promises to make the gunplay feel more like a 'traditional' FPS|accessdate=June 16, 2017|date=June 5, 2017|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first=Andy|last=Chalk|url-status=live|archivedate=16 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616112622/http://www.pcgamer.com/a-new-rust-update-promises-to-make-the-gunplay-feel-more-like-a-traditional-fps/|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"devblog163\">{{cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-163/|title=Devblog 163|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=1 September 2018|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|url-status=live|archivedate=1 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901005606/https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-163/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are a number of different types of bullet for each gun, including high [[velocity]] and explosive,<ref name=\"devblog63\">{{cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-63/|archivedate=29 August 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/7221paz6G?url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-63/|title=Devblog 63|publisher=[[Facepunch]]|date=4 June 2015| first1=Garry| last1=Newman| first2=Maurino| last2=Berry| first3=Andr\u00e9| last3=Straubmeier| first4=Petur| last4=Agust| first5=Thomas| last5=Butters| first6=Vincent| last6=Mayeur| first7=Paul| last7=Bradley| first8=Diogo| last8=Teixeira| first9=Alex| last9=Rehberg| accessdate=29 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> thus allowing for more diverse strategy.<ref name=\"rpspremature\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/03/07/rust-review-early-access/|title=Premature Evaluation: Rust|last=Zacny|first=Rob|date=7 March 2016|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092550/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/03/07/rust-review-early-access/|archivedate=21 September 2016|url-status=live|access-date=28 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Hit tracking calculates damage;<ref name=\"pcgamertrad\"/> shots to the head are more damaging than shots to other parts of the body.<ref name=\"creaky\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/08/17/rust-tweaks-gunplay/|archivedate=31 August 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831035154/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/08/17/rust-tweaks-gunplay/|url-status=live|title=Lubed: Rust Tackles Its Creaky Gunplay|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|accessdate=31 August 2018|date=17 August 2015|first=Alice|last=O'Connor|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"rps20140107\"/> The use of weapon attachments, such as 8x scopes, provide an advantage over opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/streaming-rust-just-got-safer-with-new-streamer-mode/|title=Streaming Rust just got safer with new Streamer Mode|access-date=22 October 2016|archivedate=22 October 2016|url-status=live|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|date=21 September 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022052949/http://www.pcgamer.com/streaming-rust-just-got-safer-with-new-streamer-mode/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> To survive, the player must craft tools, build bases, and team with other players.<ref name=\"playreview\">{{cite web|url=https://xtrafreak.com/getting-started-in-rust-2020.php|title=How to get started in Rust 2020|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020|website=Xtrafreak.LIVE|publisher=Xtrafreak.LIVE|first=Jay|last=Oak|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"2Diary\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-diary-part-2-its-hard-to-kill-a-half-naked-jumping-man/|title=Rust diary, part 2: \"It's hard to kill a naked jumping man\"|first1=Christopher|last1=Livingston|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=26 March 2014|access-date=1 July 2015|archivedate=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090301/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-diary-part-2-its-hard-to-kill-a-half-naked-jumping-man/|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are reports that Rust will become available to play on console (PlayStation) in the year 2020.<ref name=\"playstationblog\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.us.playstation.com/2019/11/14/harsh-survival-rpg-rust-hits-playstation-4-in-2020/|title=Harsh Survival RPG Hits Playstation 4 in 2020|date=14 November 2019|accessdate=23 March 2020|website=[[PlayStation]]|publisher=[[PlayStation]]|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen beginning, a player only has a rock and a torch.<ref name=\"facepunchblog\">{{cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/|title=Rust|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020|website=[[Facepunch]]|publisher=[[Facepunch]]|url-status=live}}</ref> The rock can cut down trees and break apart stones. Cloth and food can be gathered by killing animals; mining provides stone, metal ore, and sulfur ore; and chopping down trees provides wood.<ref name=\"Tips2\">{{cite web|url = http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-guide-survival/|title = Rust guide: Surviving your first day|date = 23 January 2014|accessdate = 1 July 2015|archivedate = 21 September 2016|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921085959/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-guide-survival/|url-status = live|website = [[PC Gamer]]|publisher = [[Future plc]]|last = Chalk|first = Andy|df = dmy-all}}</ref> To survive in the world, the player must gather resources and use them to craft tools, weapons, and other gear.<ref name=\"RockBF\">{{cite web|url-status = live|archive-date = 21 September 2016|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921085957/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/01/08/in-rust-your-best-friend-is-a-rock|url = http://au.ign.com/articles/2014/01/08/in-rust-your-best-friend-is-a-rock|title = In Rust, Your Best Friend is a Rock|date = 8 January 2014|accessdate = 1 July 2015|website = IGN|last = MacDonald|first = Keza|df = dmy-all}}</ref> To [[Glossary of video game terms#Crafting|craft]] items, the player must have a sufficient amount of all required materials,<ref name=\"IGN-review\"/> with advanced items needing more obscure components scattered around the map.<ref name=\"pcgamercomponents\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/latest-rust-update-removes-xp-and-levelling/|title=Latest Rust update removes XP and levelling|first=Mat|last=Paget|date=7 November 2016|access-date=7 November 2016|url-status=live|archivedate=7 November 2016|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107055932/http://www.pcgamer.com/latest-rust-update-removes-xp-and-levelling/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are limitations imposed on the amount of craftable items, with blueprints allowing the creation of more advanced items.<ref name=\"IGN-review\"/> A possibly important element in ''Rust'' is the [[airdrop]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2014-01-17-the-mod-squad-facepunchs-garry-newman-on-rust|title=\"Rust has made about 40% of what GMod made in 9 years\"|website=[[GamesIndustry]]|publisher=[[Gamer Network]]|accessdate=December 30, 2017|archivedate=29 December 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229134209/http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2014-01-17-the-mod-squad-facepunchs-garry-newman-on-rust|first=Dan|last=Pearson|date=January 20, 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These are parachute-equipped pallets of supplies delivered by a [[Turboprop|prop plane]]. They can be seen over extremely long distances, sometimes resulting in players running towards the airdrop.<ref name=\"rps20140107\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/01/07/impressions-rust/|title=Impressions: Rust|first=Rich|last=Stanton|date=7 January 2014|access-date=22 October 2016|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|archive-date=22 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022045920/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/01/07/impressions-rust/|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are also other entities that drop advanced loot, including an [[attack helicopter]]<ref name=\"rpspremature\"/> and the [[CH-47 Chinook]]. Both of these travel randomly around the map and attempt to kill players. The Chinook additionally travels to a randomly picked monument found in the game world and drops a locked supply crate that opens after a length of time, inviting PvP interactions.<ref name=\"rpsapril\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/04/06/rust-adds-boasts/|title=Rust adds boats, improves forests, deploys choppers|first=Alice|last=O'Connor|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=25 June 2018|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615005552/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/04/06/rust-adds-boasts/|archivedate=15 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are player-operable vehicles in ''Rust''. Boats are used to traverse long distances across water and reach valuable loot.<ref name=\"rpsboat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rusts-first-player-controlled-vehicle-has-arrived-and-its-a-boat/|title=Rust's first player-controlled vehicle has arrived, and it's a boat|date=7 April 2018|accessdate=25 June 2018|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first=Christopher|last=Livingston|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408120110/https://www.pcgamer.com/rusts-first-player-controlled-vehicle-has-arrived-and-its-a-boat/|archivedate=8 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Some airborne vehicles, such as [[hot air balloon]]s, can also be used to explore the map quickly. Spawning randomly, they can be used once fueled. These player-controlled vehicles, and unlike the offensive AI entities, can be destroyed by [[surface-to-air missile]]s that players can position outside bases.<ref name=\"balloonspcg\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-now-has-hot-air-balloons-and-missiles-that-can-shoot-them-down/|title=Rust now has hot air balloons and missiles that can shoot them down|first=Christopher|last=Livingston|accessdate=8 November 2018|date=3 November 2018|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]}}</ref><ref name=\"febupdate\">{{Cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/february-update|title=The Air Power Update|date=7 February 2019|website=[[Facepunch]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe player must stay well fed or they will die of [[starvation]]. There are other challenges the player must overcome during gameplay, such as drowning, hypothermia, and wildlife attacks\u2014primarily bears and wolves.<ref name=\"Tips1\" /> Specific locales around the map are radioactive. There are four levels of radiation: minor, low, medium, and high. The correct armour or clothing must be worn to enter these areas; failure to do so can result in death.<ref name=\"devblog134\"/> Upon death, a screen with an option to respawn at a random location or at a sleeping bag placed prior appears. Respawning resets the player's inventory to the basic rock and torch. Clans usually create housing for their members, give items and supplies to each other and partake in organised [[Raid (gaming)|raiding]] and [[Looting (gaming)|looting]].<ref name=\"PCG-review\"/><ref name=\"letters\">{{cite web|url-status=live|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2014/02/19/rust-letters-on-deception-destruction-grief-and-griefing|title=Rust Letters: On Deception, Destruction, Grief, and Griefing|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831040229/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/02/19/rust-letters-on-deception-destruction-grief-and-griefing|archivedate=31 August 2018|accessdate=31 August 2018|date=19 February 2014|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|first1=Mitch|last1=Dyer|first2=Shawn|last2=Elliott|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"gibizinterview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2014-01-17-the-mod-squad-facepunchs-garry-newman-on-rust|website=[[Gamesindustry.biz]]|publisher=Gamer Network|title=\"Rust has made about 40% of what GMod made in 9 years\"|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831040219/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2014-01-17-the-mod-squad-facepunchs-garry-newman-on-rust|archivedate=31 August 2018|accessdate=31 August 2018|date=20 January 2014|first=Dan|last=Pearson|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Safe zones, called Compounds, provide players with a place to trade resources, overlooked by automated high-damage [[sentry gun|auto turrets]] that fire on anyone who draws a weapon, discouraging betrayal. Additionally, these treacherous players will be marked as hostile for a predetermined amount of time.<ref name=\"pcgamermay\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-gets-a-safe-zone-in-the-new-compound-update/|title=Rust gets a safe zone in the new Compound Update|date=4 May 2018|accessdate=25 June 2018|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first=Andy|last=Chalk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180506225405/https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-gets-a-safe-zone-in-the-new-compound-update/|archivedate=6 May 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Rust version comparison.jpg|thumb|right|A comparison of two different updates of ''Rust'', the top (2014) one is the earlier of the two. The bottom (2016) used an updated game engine]]\n''Rust''{{'}}s development began as a clone of ''[[DayZ (mod)|DayZ]]'',<ref name=\"clone\"/> a popular mod for ''[[ARMA 2]]'', featuring elements derived from ''[[Minecraft]]''.<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|url=http://playrust.com/about/|title=About Rust|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|accessdate=30 June 2015|archivedate=27 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627160841/http://playrust.com/about/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Garry Newman, the CEO of Facepunch Studios, said \"''Rust'' started off as a ''DayZ'' clone. But then we decided that we are sick of fighting zombies. And can't compete with the ''[[ARMA (series)|Arma]]'' island in terms of landmarks and towns.\"<ref name=\"clone\">{{cite web|url=http://garry.tv/2013/06/21/the-story-of-rust/|title=The Story of Rust|date=21 June 2013|first1=Garry|last1=Newman|accessdate=30 June 2015|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios|garry.tv]]|archive-date=21 September 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921083229/https://garry.tv/2013/06/21/the-story-of-rust/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Consequently, Newman described the game as being more along the lines of entries in the ''[[S.T.A.L.K.E.R]]'' series.<ref name=\"clone\"/> Facepunch released the game onto the Steam [[Early Access#Steam Early Access|Early Access]] program on 11 December 2013.<ref name=\"1million\"/> Following its alpha launch, Facepunch actively released updates for ''Rust'' adding mechanics like animals, [[hunting]], armour and weapons. In February 2014, the developers removed zombies, a temporary enemy, from ''Rust'', replacing them with red mutant bears and wolves.<ref name=\"RemoveZombies\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/there-are-no-more-zombies-in-rust/1100-6417584/|title=There are no more zombies in Rust|accessdate=18 May 2014|first1=Martin|last1=Gaston|date=7 February 2014|website=[[GameSpot]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090304/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/there-are-no-more-zombies-in-rust/1100-6417584/|archivedate=21 September 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Early on developers made the choice not to try to populate the world with interesting locations to explore, but rather provide the ability to create them. Newman described it as \"we give them the tools, they make the world\".<ref name=\"rust-interview\">{{cite web|last1=Kelly|first1=Andy|title=Garry Newman interview: on Rust and player freedom \"we give them the tools, they make the world\"|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-interview/|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=13 February 2016|archive-date=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090313/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-interview/|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> One of the developers' aims was to create a world which does not encourage any particular kind of behaviour from players. They considered implementing a system like ''DayZ''{{'}}s where those who kill other players get unique outfits which identify them as 'bandits', or possibly a rating or color-coded system. However, the developers ultimately rejected these ideas, believing they would detract from player freedom.<ref name=\"clone\" /> Instead, they found to their surprise that the implementation of voice chat had a noticeable effect on player behavior. With the ability to communicate, many players would no longer kill each other on sight out of fear.<ref name=\"rust-interview\" />\n\nIn late 2014, developers released an experimental mode of ''Rust'' and [[Porting#Porting of video games|ported]] it to a then-unreleased [[game engine]], [[Unity (game engine)#Unity 5|Unity 5]], enhancing the graphics, and in turn, improving the [[shader]] mechanics and texture realism,<ref name=\"unity5blog\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.unity3d.com/2014/11/19/porting-to-unity-5-the-untold-rust-journey/|title=Porting to Unity 5 \u2013 The Untold Rust Journey|publisher=[[Unity (engine)|Unity Blog]]|accessdate=31 August 2018|first=Christopher|last=Pope|date=19 November 2014|archivedate=31 August 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831024215/https://blogs.unity3d.com/2014/11/19/porting-to-unity-5-the-untold-rust-journey/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> as well as allowed for larger [[procedurally generated]] worlds.<ref name=\"rpsnov2014\"/> The experimental mode featured a new [[anti-cheat]] system called CheatPunch, which banned thousands of players within a few days.<ref>{{cite web|url-status=live|url=http://www.develop-online.net/news/facepunch-bans-more-than-4-500-rust-players/0189163|title=Facepunch bans more than 4,500 Rust players|archivedate=21 September 2016|date=12 February 2014|accessdate=21 September 2016|website=[[Develop (magazine)|Develop]]|publisher=[[NewBay Media]]|first=Craig|last=Chapple|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921093821/http://www.develop-online.net/news/facepunch-bans-more-than-4-500-rust-players/0189163|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October 2014, the experimental mode became the default launch option.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://playrust.com/experimental-launches-by-default/|url-status=live|archive-date=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090947/https://playrust.com/experimental-launches-by-default/|first1=Garry|last1=Newman|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|date=1 October 2014|title=Experimental Launches By Default|accessdate=9 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Shortly after, in December, [[EasyAntiCheat]], a third-party anti-cheat system, replaced CheatPunch.<ref name=\"eacupdate\">{{cite web|url=http://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-40/#more-2280|title=Devblog 40|publisher=[[Facepunch]]|date=December 28, 2014|accessdate=June 26, 2017|archivedate=26 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626125217/http://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-40/#more-2280|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In early 2015, ''Rust'' added a feature that decided each player's [[Race (human categorization)|skin colour]] tied to their [[Steam (software)|Steam]] ID.<ref name=\"kotakumessy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2015/03/rust-chooses-players-race-for-them-things-get-messy/|title=Rust Chooses Players' Race For Them, Things Get Messy|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gizmodo Media Group]]|accessdate=27 June 2018|date=26 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627173133/https://www.kotaku.com.au/2015/03/rust-chooses-players-race-for-them-things-get-messy/|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the original game, the [[HUD (video gaming)|heads-up display]] featured statistics like as [[Health (video game)|health]], hunger and [[radiation]] level.<ref name=\"Tips1\">{{cite web|url = http://www.usgamer.net/articles/rust-a-beginners-survival-guide|title = Rust Guide: How to Get Started, Beginners Hints and Tips|date = 24 January 2014|accessdate = 1 July 2015|publisher = [[Eurogamer]]|last = Williams|first = Mike|website = [[USgamer]]|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090017/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/rust-a-beginners-survival-guide|archivedate = 21 September 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref> These were later modified and hidden statistics such as [[hypothermia]] were added.<ref name=\"Racism1\">{{cite web|url = http://america.aljazeera.com/opinions/2015/5/the-online-game-that-proves-the-web-is-not-a-post-racial-utopia.html|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090953/http://america.aljazeera.com/opinions/2015/5/the-online-game-that-proves-the-web-is-not-a-post-racial-utopia.html|archivedate = 21 September 2016|title = The Web is not a post-racial utopia|date = 24 May 2015|accessdate = 1 July 2015|website = [[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]|publisher = [[Al Jazeera Media Network]]|last = Condis|first = Megan|df = dmy-all}}</ref> Monuments went through a phase where developers removed the radiation hazards because of the annoyance it was causing.<ref name=\"monuments1\">{{cite web|url=http://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-71/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090957/https://playrust.com/devblog-71/|archivedate=21 September 2016|title=Devblog 71|access-date=16 January 2016|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|date=30 July 2015|first=Craig|last=Pearson|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"monuments2\">{{cite web|url=http://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-77/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921091001/https://playrust.com/devblog-77/|archivedate=21 September 2016|title=Devblog 77|access-date=16 January 2016|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|date=10 September 2015|first=Craig|last=Pearson|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Female models, added to the game shortly afterward, were initially only available for [[server (computing)|server]] [[Server administrator|administrators]] to test. Upon rollout, akin to skin colour, players were automatically assigned a [[biological sex]] permanently linked to their Steam account.<ref name=\"womanmodel1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/female-models-come-to-rust-but-only-for-admins/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728064842/http://www.pcgamer.com/female-models-come-to-rust-but-only-for-admins/|title=Female models come to Rust, but only for admins|first1=Andy|last1=Chalk|date=16 July 2015|access-date=28 July 2015|archive-date=28 July 2015|publisher=[[Future plc]]|website=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref> Later in 2015, [[virtual goods]] stores selling guns, clothing and other objects were added to the game. When [[Valve Corporation|Valve]] introduced its Item Store, ''Rust'' was the first game on Steam to use the feature.<ref name=\"itemstoresteamed\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921091004/http://steamed.kotaku.com/steam-has-added-new-item-store-functionality-now-in-1740586891|url-status=live|archivedate=21 September 2016|url=http://steamed.kotaku.com/steam-has-added-new-item-store-functionality-now-in-1740586891|title=Steam has added a new \u2018item store\u2019 feature|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|date=4 November 2015|access-date=6 February 2016|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Steam (software)#Storefront features|Steam Community Market]] was also allowed to sell similar items.<ref name=\"itemstorepcgamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/steam-item-stores-roll-out-with-new-update-debut-in-rust/|title=Steam 'Item Stores' roll out with new update, debut in Rust|website=[[PC Gamer]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921091009/http://www.pcgamer.com/steam-item-stores-roll-out-with-new-update-debut-in-rust/|archive-date=21 September 2016|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first=Andy|last=Chalk|date=4 November 2015|access-date=6 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"itemstorerps\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/11/05/rust-item-store/|title=Rust Adds Item Store For Modders To Sell Cosmetics|publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|first=Graham|last=Smith|date=5 November 2015|access-date=14 February 2016|archive-date=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921091019/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/11/05/rust-item-store/|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDevelopers removed [[blueprint]]s, one of the core gameplay concepts of ''Rust'', in July 2016. They replaced them with an [[experience point|experience]] system where players could level up after completing tasks, such as gathering wood.<ref name=\"pcgamerxp1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-introduces-xp-system/|title=Rust introduces XP system|first=Angus|last=Morrison|date=8 July 2016|access-date=9 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709114026/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-introduces-xp-system/|url-status=live|archive-date=9 July 2016|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]}}</ref><ref name=\"devblog100\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-07-09-big-rust-update-ditches-blueprints-introduces-xp-and-levelling|title=Big Rust update ditches blueprints, introduces XP and levelling|access-date=11 July 2016|first=Robert|last=Purchese|date=9 July 2016|website=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|url-status=live|archive-date=11 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711133700/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-07-09-big-rust-update-ditches-blueprints-introduces-xp-and-levelling}}</ref> In September, lead developer Maurino Berry mentioned in a [[Reddit]] post that there was a chance the experience system would no longer exist in the future. Before saying this, Berry wrote in one of the devblogs \"the XP system had huge praise until it was released, and then lots of people hated it\".<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917095123/http://www.pcgamer.com/rusts-xp-system-isnt-working-very-well-will-likely-be-removed/|url-status=live|archive-date=17 September 2016|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rusts-xp-system-isnt-working-very-well-will-likely-be-removed/|date=12 September 2016|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|access-date=17 September 2016|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|title=Rust's XP system isn't working very well, will likely be removed|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In early November 2016, components replaced the experience system.<ref name=\"pcgamercomponents\"/> Originally, players had an initial list of items they could craft. This was changed to having a complete list with the required components from the outset.<ref name=\"pcgamercomponents\"/> Radiation, removed in 2015, was reintroduced in November 2016 after being \"reprogrammed from the ground up\".<ref name=\"devblog134\">{{cite web|url=http://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-134/|title=Devblog 134|first=Craig|last=Pearson|access-date=7 November 2016|date=3 November 2016|archivedate=7 November 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107060602/https://playrust.com/devblog-134/|url-status=live|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Instead of each location having the same level of radiation, developers added different levels ranging from low, to medium, and high.<ref name=\"devblog134\"/>\n\nIn early 2017, Garry Newman said that had Steam Early Access not existed, ''Rust'' would have been fully released as a game by then. The development team would have continued to release updates.<ref name=\"rpstrad\"/> In June 2017, developers altered the game's gun mechanics to be more like \"traditional first-person shooters\".<ref name=\"rpstrad\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2017/06/05/rust-recoil-changed/|title=Gleaming! Rust overhauls recoil and inaccuracy|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|accessdate=December 31, 2017|archivedate=31 December 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231013618/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2017/06/05/rust-recoil-changed/|first=Alice|last=O'Connor|date=June 5, 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This was achieved by reducing recoil, material costs, and improving overall accuracy.<ref name=\"pcgamertrad\"/> This update also saw the beginnings of an overhaul of Hapis Island, the game's only non-[[procedurally generated]] map.<ref name=\"pcgamertrad\"/> The game left Early Access and was officially released on 8 February 2018,<ref name=\"leave1\"/> along with graphical and gun changes.<ref name=\"overhaul1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-marks-end-of-four-year-long-early-access-with-a-visual-overhaul/|title=Rust marks end of four-year Early Access with a visual overhaul|first=Samuel |last=Horti|date=11 February 2018|accessdate=13 February 2018|url-status=live|archivedate=13 February 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213105702/https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-marks-end-of-four-year-long-early-access-with-a-visual-overhaul/|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]}}</ref> By this time, blueprints had been reinstated.<ref name=\"IGN-review\"/> Newman mentioned that despite the official release, regular updates would continue. He noted the update cycle would change from weekly to monthly so as not to \"rush in features and fixes that end up breaking something else\".<ref name=\"leave1\">{{cite web|last1=Chalk|first1=Andy|title=Rust will leave Early Access in February, but it's not finished yet|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-will-leave-early-access-in-february-but-its-not-finished-yet/|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=23 January 2018|url-status=live|date=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123034606/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-will-leave-early-access-in-february-but-its-not-finished-yet/|archivedate=23 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPost release, Facepunch have continued to support the game with updates that added new features, including graphical overhauls<ref name=\"overhaul1\"/> and new guns.<ref name=\"dev198\">{{Cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-198/|title=Devblog 198|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|accessdate=25 June 2018|date=1 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625121419/https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-198/|archivedate=25 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> April 2018 was the first big update post-Early Access. This update added the first player-operable vehicle, a boat, and a new hostile entity, a CH-47 Chinook.<ref name=\"rpsapril\"/> One month later ''Rust'' saw the addition of Compounds, safe areas guarded by scientists, [[non-player characters]] Facepunch had hinted at before<ref name=\"scientisttease\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-could-get-creepy-npc-scientists-that-ignore-your-naked-caveman-murders/|title=Rust could get creepy NPC scientists that ignore your naked caveman murders|first=Tom|last=Sykes|date=28 November 2015|accessdate=27 June 2018|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627144422/https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-could-get-creepy-npc-scientists-that-ignore-your-naked-caveman-murders/|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and high-damage turrets. The update also added [[scuba diving]] equipment to allow for the ocean to be explored easier.<ref name=\"pcgamermay\"/> The ocean-related gameplay was addressed again in October, when ''Rust'' saw the addition of a [[cargo ship]] that allowed for visitation, the \"CCSC Lazarus\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/10/05/rust-has-added-a-big-radioactive-boat-for-you-to-squabble-over/|title=Rust has added a big radioactive boat for you to squabble over|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=5 October 2018|first=Matt|last=Cox|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005143450/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/10/05/rust-has-added-a-big-radioactive-boat-for-you-to-squabble-over/|archive-date=5 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Similar in nature to the addition of player-operable boats, early November saw the addition of the first flying vehicle: hot air balloons. Additional weapons were also added at the same time.<ref name=\"balloonspcg\"/> In December, ''Rust'' saw the addition of electricity, and with it, new components and weapons.<ref name=\"electricitypcgamer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-finally-gives-its-naked-citizens-underwear-electricity/|title=Rust finally gives its naked citizens underwear, electricity|date=7 December 2018|accessdate=19 July 2019|archivedate=19 July 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719121231/https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-finally-gives-its-naked-citizens-underwear-electricity/|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|url-status=live|first=Christopher|last=Livingston}}</ref>\n\n''Rust'' continues to see updates into 2019, with gradual graphical and stability improvements, as well as major feature additions. February's update was dubbed the \"Air Power Update\" and saw the minicopter, a new player controllable vehicle.<ref name=\"febupdate\"/> In the June and July updates, horses, another player controllable entity, were added and further developed, seeing improvements and the introduction of new [[List of horse breeds|breeds]].<ref name=\"junupdate\">{{cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/june-update|title=Giddy Up!|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|access-date=19 July 2019|url-status=live|date=7 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"julupdate\">{{cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/july-update|title=July Update|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|access-date=19 July 2019|url-status=live|date=4 July 2019}}</ref> Also in June was the addition of a playable [[arcade cabinet]] to commemorate the release of Facepunch's ''[[Chippy (2019 video game)|Chippy]]'', a new [[bullet hell]]-style game.<ref name=\"junupdate\"/><ref name=\"pcgamerchippy\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719122801/https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-and-garrys-mod-devs-release-chippy-a-bullet-hell-shooter/|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-and-garrys-mod-devs-release-chippy-a-bullet-hell-shooter/|work=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|archivedate=19 July 2019|accessdate=19 July 2019|first=Samuel|last=Horti|date=15 June 2019|title=Rust and Garry's Mod devs release Chippy, a bullet hell shooter}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===In Early Access===\n''Rust'' received mixed reviews following its alpha release, with many denoting the unfinished nature and lack of polish.<ref name=\"1yearonreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamesn.com/rust-early-access-review|title=Rust Early Access review: one year on|last1=Purslow|first1=Matt|date=16 January 2015|website=[[PCGamesN]]|publisher=Network N|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702104456/http://www.pcgamesn.com/rust-early-access-review|archive-date=2 July 2015|url-status=live|access-date=2 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"gamespotea\"/> ''[[PC Gamer]]''{{'}}s Andy Chalk said ''Rust'' was a great use of Early Access and even though \"it's far from finished\", it's ready to be played.<ref name=\"PCGReview1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-alpha-review/|first1=Andy|last1=Chalk|title=Rust alpha review|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702102330/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-alpha-review/|archive-date=2 July 2015|date=10 January 2014|access-date=2 July 2015|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]}}</ref> ''[[GameSpot]]''{{'}}s Shaun McInnis said the early 2014 version was \"rough around the edges\" and \"littered with bugs\", but it entertained and had potential.<ref name=\"gamespotea\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rust-early-access-review/1100-6417381/|title=Rust Early Access Review|access-date=28 June 2016|website=[[GameSpot]]|first=Shaun|last=McInnis|date=28 January 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202546/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rust-early-access-review/1100-6417381/|archivedate=3 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Matthew Cox of ''[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]'' said it was smart of the developers to switch to the [[Unity engine]] in late 2014 due to the game's instability. In Cox's review, he noted many glitches in the late 2014 version, including unresponsive animals, [[framerate]] issues and unstable servers.<ref name=\"rpsnov2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/11/26/rust-new-version-review/|title=Impressions: Rust\u2019s New Version|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|first=Matthew|last=Cox|date=26 November 2014|access-date=28 June 2016|url-status=live|archivedate=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090319/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/11/26/rust-new-version-review/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''IGN''{{'}}s Mitch Dyer did not enjoy the combat, calling ''Rust'' a \"semi-broken\" game he felt unable to recommend.<ref name=\"igndayzmc\"/>\n\nOther games like ''[[The Forest (video game)|The Forest]]'', ''[[Just Survive]]'', ''[[Ark: Survival Evolved]]''<ref name=\"ArkRelation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/ark-survival-evolved-sells-one-million-copies-in-less-than-a-month/|title=Ark: Survival Evolved sells one million copies in less than a month|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first1=Andy|last1=Chalk|date=2 July 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706100932/http://www.pcgamer.com/ark-survival-evolved-sells-one-million-copies-in-less-than-a-month/|archive-date=6 July 2015|access-date=6 July 2015}}</ref> and ''[[7 Days to Die]]'' were compared to ''Rust'' because of their open world survival aspects, as well as having crafting mechanics similar to ''Rust''.<ref name=\"H1Z1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/05/08/rust-h1z1-and-the-emerging-survival-mmo-genre/|title=Rust, H1Z1, and the emerging 'survival MMO' genre|url-status=live|first1=Andrew|last1=Ross|date=8 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630050059/http://www.engadget.com/2014/05/08/rust-h1z1-and-the-emerging-survival-mmo-genre/|archive-date=30 June 2015|website=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> ''Kotaku''{{'}}s Luke Plunkett noted the similarities, saying it felt as though someone had thought of a game whereby ''Dayz'' and ''Minecraft'' could be played simultaneously.<ref name=\"kotakudayzvsmc\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/rust-is-dayz-vs-minecraft-and-it-will-kick-your-ass-1497654260|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092707/http://kotaku.com/rust-is-dayz-vs-minecraft-and-it-will-kick-your-ass-1497654260|archivedate=21 September 2016|url-status=live|title=Rust Is DayZ vs Minecraft, And It Will Kick Your Ass|first=Luke|last=Plunkett|date=9 January 2014|access-date=28 June 2016|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dyer, while criticising ''Rust'' due to its bugs, called parts of the experience \"utterly unforgettable\" and often unpredictable.<ref name=\"igndayzmc\">{{cite web|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2013/12/20/rust-the-terrifying-minecraft-dayz-open-world-survival-sim|title=Rust: The Terrifying Minecraft + DayZ Open World Survival Sim|access-date=28 June 2016|first=Mitch|last=Dyer|website=[[IGN]]|date=20 December 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092624/http://au.ign.com/articles/2013/12/20/rust-the-terrifying-minecraft-dayz-open-world-survival-sim|archive-date=21 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe inability to choose and design a player's character was both commended and criticised. The [[YouTube]] channel ''[[Extra Credits]]'' commended ''Rust'' for promoting diversity by randomly selecting a player's in-game race. Tying race to their Steam ID forced players to experience the game in a different way than they might normally experience it, perhaps promoting [[empathy]] for someone of a different ethnicity.<ref name=\"ExtraCreditCharSelect\">{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eh1zfdUTqBY | title=Rust - Representing Race in Games - Extra Credits | publisher=[[YouTube]] | date=27 May 2015 | accessdate=31 August 2015 | author=Extra Credits | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120090719/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eh1zfdUTqBY | archivedate=20 November 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> David Craddock of ''[[Shacknews]]'' criticised the lack of communication between Facepunch and the community when they added female models.<ref name=\"communicationcraddock\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/94189/opinion-how-facepunch-failed-to-communicate-gender-assignment-in-rust|title=Opinion: How Facepunch failed to communicate gender assignment in Rust|date=18 April 2016|access-date=14 June 2016|first=David|last=Craddock|url-status=live|publisher=[[Shacknews]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614112541/http://www.shacknews.com/article/94189/opinion-how-facepunch-failed-to-communicate-gender-assignment-in-rust|archive-date=14 June 2016}}</ref> In response to this criticism, Garry Newman commented he felt some trepidation about adding the racial feature, fearing it might be seen as the original character model \"[[Blackface|blacked up]]\". He stressed the chosen ethnicity was permanent\u2014\"just like in real life, you are who you are\".<ref name=\"racialempathy\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rust-experiments-with-racial-empathy-randomly-assi/1100-6426197/ | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092554/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rust-experiments-with-racial-empathy-randomly-assi/1100-6426197/ | archive-date=21 September 2016 | title=Rust Experiments With Racial Empathy, Randomly Assigns Skin Color | website=[[GameSpot]] | date=26 March 2015 | accessdate=2 November 2015 | last=Starkey | first=Daniel | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Newman discussed the reasoning behind not providing the option to choose their character's gender and race in an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'', saying ''Rust'' is about survival, not characterization and identity. \"We wanted the appearance of the players to be consistent over time. They should be recognisable consistently and long-term.\"<ref name=\"garrytheguardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/apr/13/videogame-chooses-character-race-gender-rust|title=Why my videogame chooses your character\u2019s race and gender for you|first=Garry|url-status=live|last=Newman|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=14 April 2016|access-date=14 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614113408/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/apr/13/videogame-chooses-character-race-gender-rust|archive-date=14 June 2016}}</ref> Sales reportedly increased by 74% shortly after the addition of female models.<ref name=\"skyrocketsales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/04/23/rust-female-character-models-sales-jump-bullet-with-butterfly-wings/|title=Sales skyrocketed after 'Rust' added female character models|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092625/https://www.engadget.com/2016/04/23/rust-female-character-models-sales-jump-bullet-with-butterfly-wings/|archivedate=21 September 2016|first=Timothy|last=Seppala|website=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|access-date=28 June 2016|date=23 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"skyrocketsales2\">{{cite web|url=http://steamed.kotaku.com/rusts-controversial-random-gender-update-has-led-to-mor-1772390030|title=Rust's Controversial Random Gender Update Has Led To More Players|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|date=22 April 2016|access-date=28 June 2016|url-status=live|archive-date=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921092223/http://steamed.kotaku.com/rusts-controversial-random-gender-update-has-led-to-mor-1772390030|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Sales====\nWithin the first two weeks of ''Rust''{{'}}s alpha release it sold over 150,000 copies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/207990/Garrys_Mod_creator_finds_unexpected_success_with_new_game_Rust.php|title=Garry's Mod creator finds unexpected success with new game Rust|url-status=live|archivedate=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092701/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/207990/Garrys_Mod_creator_finds_unexpected_success_with_new_game_Rust.php|last=Wawro|first=Alex|date=3 January 2014|work=[[Gamasutra]]|publisher=[[UBM TechWeb]]|accessdate=5 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> compared to the 34,000 copies of ''[[Garry's Mod]]'' sold in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.facepunchstudios.com/2014/01/03/gmod-vs-rust-launch/|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921092234/http://www.facepunchstudios.com/2014/01/03/gmod-vs-rust-launch/|archivedate = 21 September 2016|title = GMod vs Rust Launch|date = 3 January 2014|access-date = 12 February 2016|publisher = [[Facepunch]]|last = Newman|first = Garry|df = dmy-all}}</ref> ''Rust''{{'}}s sales had reached one million copies after being an Early Access title for only two months,<ref name=\"1million\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2014/02/11/rust-hits-1-million-sales-after-two-months/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092531/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-hits-1-million-sales-after-two-months/|archive-date=21 September 2016|title=Rust hits 1 million sales after two months|last=Petitte|first=Omri|date=11 February 2014|work=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=11 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and during February 2014, it overtook ''[[Garry's Mod]]'' in terms of sales, making over {{US$|30&nbsp;million|link=yes}}.<ref name=\"30million\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/2/21/5433886/garrys-mod-sales-30m-rust|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092308/http://www.polygon.com/2014/2/21/5433886/garrys-mod-sales-30m-rust|archivedate=21 September 2016|title=Garry's Mod sales hit $30M, Rust eclipses it|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|first1=Samit|last1=Sarkar|date=21 February 2014|access-date=2 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> By the end of 2015, three million copies had been sold.<ref name=\"3mil\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-sales-pass-the-three-million-mark/|title=Rust sales pass the three million mark|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092642/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-sales-pass-the-three-million-mark/|archivedate=21 September 2016|first1=Tom|last1=Sykes|website=[[PC Gamer]]|date=24 December 2015|access-date=3 January 2015|publisher=[[Future plc]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> By March 2017, the game had sold more than 5.2 million units, with more than 1.2 million in-game skins sold.<ref>{{cite web|title=Community Update 127|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/community-update-127/|accessdate=3 July 2017|date=14 March 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704013413/https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/community-update-127/|archivedate=4 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In December 2019, Facepunch announced that ''Rust'' had sold 9 million copies, making $142 million, overtaking ''Garry's Mod'' in terms of [[Gross (economics)|gross]], though still behind in total sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-has-made-more-money-than-garrys-mod/|title=Rust has made more money than Garry\u2019s Mod|date=21 December 2019|accessdate=23 December 2019|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first= Jonathan |last=Bolding|url-status=live|archivedate=23 December 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222141629/https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-has-made-more-money-than-garrys-mod/}}</ref>\n\n===Full release===\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = 69/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/rust |title=Rust for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=17 June 2018|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617094907/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/rust|archivedate=17 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| Destruct = 8/10<ref name=\"Destructoid-review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-rust-490145.phtml|first=Ray|last=Porreca|accessdate=17 June 2018|website=[[Destructoid]]|title=Review: Rust|date=19 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625121417/https://www.destructoid.com/review-rust-490145.phtml|archivedate=25 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| GI = 6.5/10<ref name=\"GI-review\">{{cite magazine |last=Gwaltney |first=Javy |date=February 13, 2018 |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/games/rust/b/pc/archive/2018/02/13/more-rough-than-diamond.aspx |title=More Rough Than Diamond - Rust - PC |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=February 19, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221213403/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/rust/b/pc/archive/2018/02/13/more-rough-than-diamond.aspx |archivedate=21 February 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| GSpot = 3/10<ref name=\"GS-review\">{{cite web |last=Barbosa |first=Alessandro |date=February 17, 2018 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rust-review-life-is-fleeting/1900-6416858/ |title=Rust Review: Life Is Fleeting |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=February 19, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033111/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rust-review-life-is-fleeting/1900-6416858/ |archivedate=20 February 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| IGN = 7/10<ref name=\"IGN-review\">{{cite web|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2018/02/24/rust-review|title=Rust Review|accessdate=10 March 2018|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|author=GB Burford|date=February 28, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310110314/http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/24/rust-review|archivedate=10 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 80/100<ref name=\"PCG-review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-review/|title=Rust Review|first=Luke|last=Winkie|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=27 June 2018|date=19 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627115724/https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-review/|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[GameStar]]''\n| rev1Score= 69/100<ref name=\"GameStar-review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamestar.de/artikel/rust-zwischen-steinzeit-und-menschlichen-abgruenden,3326749.html|title=Rust im Test - Zwischen Steinzeit und menschlichen Abgr\u00fcnden|language=German|first=Gloria|last=Maderfeld|accessdate=27 June 2018|date=1 March 2018|website=[[GameStar]]|publisher=[[Webedia]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330225844/https://www.gamestar.de/artikel/rust-zwischen-steinzeit-und-menschlichen-abgruenden,3326749.html|archive-date=30 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAfter being fully released, ''Rust'' garnered \"mixed or average\" reviews on [[review aggregator]] website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC\" /> Critics praised the PvP combat, difficulty, and survival aspects, while grinding and the experience had by new players came under some criticism.<ref name=\"GameStar-review\"/><ref name=\"RPS-review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/02/12/rust-review|title=Wot I Think: Rust|first=Matt|last=Cox|date=12 February 2018|accessdate=13 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214142100/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/02/12/rust-review/|archivedate=14 February 2018|df=dmy-all|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]}}</ref><ref name=\"PCG-review\"/>\n\nMany critics held the opinion that while starting anew was frustrating, the combat was rewarding. For instance, Luke Winkie of ''[[PC Gamer]]'' summarised the game saying, \"Wake up naked, run for your life, do horrible things to one another. There is no grander narrative, or [[mythos]], or win condition.\"<ref name=\"PCG-review\"/> He described the beginner experience as \"quite prickly\" but continued on to praise the combat, joking that \"connecting [a] hatchet with an idiot's head feels great\". Gloria Manderfeld, a writer for the German magazine ''[[GameStar]]'', echoed these opinions, adding there was little end-game besides PvP. However, she opined the PvP itself was effective.<ref name=\"GameStar-review\"/> Ray Porreca of ''[[Destructoid]]'' described the combat as the \"meat\" of the game. However, he wrote that the experience would vary depending on their desire to fight. \"If you can look past a community that tends to be [[Glossary of video game terms#toxicity|toxic]], ''Rust''{{'}}s sprawling plains and toppled landmarks are an excellent backdrop for player-driven storytelling and pitched, dramatic moments.\"<ref name=\"Destructoid-review\"/> In a negative review ''[[GameSpot]]''{{'}}s Alessandro Barbosa said the whole experience felt unfulfilling. He described the game as lacking certain creative features, like the ability to easily redesign bases.<ref name=\"GS-review\"/>\n\nThe disdain towards the experience as a new player was noted in conjunction with the necessity of grinding, and how repetitive that became. ''[[IGN]]''{{'}}s review described the game as expecting the player to spend all their gaming time on it, fearing that failing to do so will result in being raided and needing to begin again.<ref name=\"IGN-review\"/> ''[[Game Informer]]''{{'}}s Javy Gwaltney reiterated this, explaining it felt demotivating when they died solely because they came in contact with someone more experienced.<ref name=\"GI-review\"/> Agreeing with Manderfeld's description,<ref name=\"GameStar-review\"/> in an updated review Cox said his patience wore thin after a while. He said that while maintaining [[health (gaming)|health bars]] may have once been enjoyable, he balked at the prospect in 2018.<ref name=\"RPS-review\"/>\n\nNonetheless, some critics praised the game's difficulty, mentioning the satisfaction they felt after managing to survive successfully. Porreca recommended the game to those willing to dedicate time, saying the game offers \"a social sandbox and a deep, functioning crafting system\".<ref name=\"Destructoid-review\"/> Winkie expressed interest in the necessity of managing hunger, thirst, and health while learning more and discovering better items. He also expressed a sense of appreciation for those dedicated to the game, mentioning the YouTube videos of large, multi-clan raids. He closed the review saying everyone should try ''Rust'' due to its difference from other games.<ref name=\"PCG-review\"/> Cox agreed noting the game's brutality only added to the gratification a player felt when they managed to eventually succeed.<ref name=\"RPS-review\"/>\n\nThe reception towards the graphics were mixed. Critics praised the environment, but denounced the animations and character models.<ref name=\"GI-review\"/> Barbosa described the animations as \"stiff and unnatural\" and the models \"ugly and dull\".<ref name=\n\"GS-review\"/> Additionally, the way ''Rust'' uses sound was commended by Gwaltney, who explained it as being compelling due to the way players must listen for others in order to survive.<ref name=\"GI-review\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{portal|Video games}}\n* {{Official website|rust.facepunch.com}}\n\n[[Category:2018 video games]]\n[[Category:Early access video games]]\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Steam Workshop games]]\n[[Category:Survival video games]]\n[[Category:Unity (game engine) games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video games that support Vulkan]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}\n{{short description|Survival video game}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Rust\n| image = File:Rust vector logo.svg\n| developer = [[Facepunch Studios]]\n| publisher = Facepunch Studios\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = [[macOS]], [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| released = 8 February 2018\n| genre = [[Action-adventure game|Action-adventure]], [[Survival game|survival]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer video game|Multiplayer]]\n| director = \n| producer = \n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| composer = \n}}\n\n'''''Rust''''' is a [[multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]-only [[Survival game|survival]] [[video game]] developed by [[Facepunch Studios|Facepunch Studios.]] Rust was first released in early access in December 2013 and received its full release in February 2018. ''Rust'' is available on [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[macOS]]. Console versions for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Xbox One]] have been announced for release in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/11/14/20965525/rust-ps4-xbox-one-release-dates-2020|title=Rust comes to PS4 and Xbox One next year|last=Good|first=Owen S.|date=14 November 2019|work=Polygon|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref> ''Rust'' was initially created as a [[Video game clone|clone]] of ''[[DayZ (mod)|DayZ]]'', a popular [[Mod (video gaming)|mod]] for ''[[ARMA 2]]'', with [[Glossary of video game terms#Crafting|crafting]] elements akin to those in ''[[Minecraft]]''. \n\nThe objective of ''Rust'' is to survive in the wilderness using gathered or stolen materials. Players must successfully manage their hunger, thirst, and health, or risk dying. Despite the looming threat of [[American black bears|bears]] and [[wolf|wolves]], the primary menace is other players due to the game being solely multiplayer. Combat is accomplished through [[firearm]]s and primitive weapons, such as [[Bow and arrow|bow]]s. In addition, vehicles controlled by [[non-player character]]s will occasionally roam, attacking heavily-armed players. These can be defeated with persistence. ''Rust'' features crafting, though initially limited until the discovery of specific items in the game's [[open world]]. To stay protected, players must build [[Military base|base]]s or join [[Clan (computer gaming)|clan]]s to improve their chance of survival. [[Raid (gaming)|Raiding]] is a major aspect of ''Rust'' and is done more frequently by large clans. \n\n''Rust'' was first released in December 2013 to the [[Steam Early Access]] program; this early access state is now known as Rust Legacy. Further into its development, the gameplay was changed significantly. Dangerous wildlife replaced zombies as the primary environmental threat and several fundamental revisions to the crafting system were released. 2014 saw the game ported to the [[Unity 5]] [[game engine]], providing substantial graphical changes. Around this time, ''Rust'' introduced immutable, predetermined [[Race (human categorization)|skin colour]] and [[biological sex]] tied to players' [[Steam (website)|Steam]] account details. Despite being fully released, the game continues to receive updates.\n\nThroughout ''Rust''{{'}}s alpha release, critical reviews were mixed, with many comparisons made to other survival games. ''Rust'' was commonly explained as being a mixture of ''[[DayZ (video game)|DayZ]]'' and ''[[Minecraft]]''. During this period, reviewers frequently noted the game's unfinished nature. During its pre-release phase, critics praised the concept and gameplay and by March 2017, ''Rust'' had sold over five million copies. After leaving Early Access, it received mixed reviews from critics. The [[player vs player]] combat and survival aspects were highlighted by those who enjoyed the game, though reviewers were critical of the constant need to [[Grinding (gaming)|grind]] for materials, along with the harsh beginner experience.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Collecting wood in Rust.jpeg|right|thumb|280px|A player using the starting rock to gather wood]]\nAs a [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]]-only video game,<ref name=\"5MC\">{{cite web|title = 5 Video Games to Play if You Like \u2018Minecraft\u2019|url = http://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/5-video-games-to-play-if-you-like-minecraft.html/4/|accessdate = 1 July 2015|website = CheatSheet|first = Chris|date = 30 June 2015|last = Reed|page = 4|url-status = live|archivedate = 21 September 2016|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921085950/http://www.cheatsheet.com/entertainment/5-video-games-to-play-if-you-like-minecraft.html/4/|df = dmy-all}}</ref> ''Rust'' puts players against each other in a harsh, [[open world]] environment with the sole goal of survival. Animals, such as wolves and bears, act as a looming threat, but the primary danger comes from other players.<ref name=\"5MC\"/> Most maps are [[procedurally generated]],<ref name=\"rpsnov2014\"/> with the exception of Hapis Island, a pre-built map.<ref name=\"pcgamertrad\"/> [[Player versus player|Player vs player]] (PvP) combat is accomplished with [[Bow and arrow|bow]]s, melee weapons and craftable guns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/03/28/rust-diary/|title=To Hell With Other People: Nine Lives in Rust|access-date=22 October 2016|archivedate=22 October 2016|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=28 March 2014 |first=Brendan |last=Caldwell |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022050252/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/03/28/rust-diary/ |url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Bullets and other projectiles travel in a [[Ballistics|ballistic]] trajectory, rather than being [[hitscan]].<ref name=\"pcgamertrad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/a-new-rust-update-promises-to-make-the-gunplay-feel-more-like-a-traditional-fps/|title=A new Rust update promises to make the gunplay feel more like a 'traditional' FPS|accessdate=June 16, 2017|date=June 5, 2017|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first=Andy|last=Chalk|url-status=live|archivedate=16 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616112622/http://www.pcgamer.com/a-new-rust-update-promises-to-make-the-gunplay-feel-more-like-a-traditional-fps/|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"devblog163\">{{cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-163/|title=Devblog 163|date=7 June 2017|accessdate=1 September 2018|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|url-status=live|archivedate=1 September 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180901005606/https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-163/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are a number of different types of bullet for each gun, including high [[velocity]] and explosive,<ref name=\"devblog63\">{{cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-63/|archivedate=29 August 2018|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/7221paz6G?url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-63/|title=Devblog 63|publisher=[[Facepunch]]|date=4 June 2015| first1=Garry| last1=Newman| first2=Maurino| last2=Berry| first3=Andr\u00e9| last3=Straubmeier| first4=Petur| last4=Agust| first5=Thomas| last5=Butters| first6=Vincent| last6=Mayeur| first7=Paul| last7=Bradley| first8=Diogo| last8=Teixeira| first9=Alex| last9=Rehberg| accessdate=29 August 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> thus allowing for more diverse strategy.<ref name=\"rpspremature\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/03/07/rust-review-early-access/|title=Premature Evaluation: Rust|last=Zacny|first=Rob|date=7 March 2016|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092550/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2016/03/07/rust-review-early-access/|archivedate=21 September 2016|url-status=live|access-date=28 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Hit tracking calculates damage;<ref name=\"pcgamertrad\"/> shots to the head are more damaging than shots to other parts of the body.<ref name=\"creaky\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/08/17/rust-tweaks-gunplay/|archivedate=31 August 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831035154/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/08/17/rust-tweaks-gunplay/|url-status=live|title=Lubed: Rust Tackles Its Creaky Gunplay|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|accessdate=31 August 2018|date=17 August 2015|first=Alice|last=O'Connor|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"rps20140107\"/> The use of weapon attachments, such as 8x scopes, provide an advantage over opponents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/streaming-rust-just-got-safer-with-new-streamer-mode/|title=Streaming Rust just got safer with new Streamer Mode|access-date=22 October 2016|archivedate=22 October 2016|url-status=live|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|date=21 September 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022052949/http://www.pcgamer.com/streaming-rust-just-got-safer-with-new-streamer-mode/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> To survive, the player must craft tools, build bases, and team with other players.<ref name=\"playreview\">{{cite web|url=https://xtrafreak.com/getting-started-in-rust-2020.php|title=How to get started in Rust 2020|date=20 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020|website=Xtrafreak.LIVE|publisher=Xtrafreak.LIVE|first=Jay|last=Oak|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"2Diary\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-diary-part-2-its-hard-to-kill-a-half-naked-jumping-man/|title=Rust diary, part 2: \"It's hard to kill a naked jumping man\"|first1=Christopher|last1=Livingston|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=26 March 2014|access-date=1 July 2015|archivedate=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090301/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-diary-part-2-its-hard-to-kill-a-half-naked-jumping-man/|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are reports that Rust will become available to play on console (Playstation) in the year 2020. <ref name=\"playstationblog\">{{cite web|url=https://blog.us.playstation.com/2019/11/14/harsh-survival-rpg-rust-hits-playstation-4-in-2020/|title=Harsh Survival RPG Hits Playstation 4 in 2020|date=14 November 2019|accessdate=23 March 2020|website=[[PlayStation]]|publisher=[[PlayStation]]|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen beginning, a player only has a rock and a torch. <ref name=\"facepunchblog\">{{cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/|title=Rust|date=23 March 2020|accessdate=23 March 2020|website=[[Facepunch]]|publisher=[[Facepunch]]|url-status=live}}</ref> The rock can cut down trees and break apart stones. Cloth and food can be gathered by killing animals; mining provides stone, metal ore, and sulfur ore; and chopping down trees provides wood.<ref name=\"Tips2\">{{cite web|url = http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-guide-survival/|title = Rust guide: Surviving your first day|date = 23 January 2014|accessdate = 1 July 2015|archivedate = 21 September 2016|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921085959/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-guide-survival/|url-status = live|website = [[PC Gamer]]|publisher = [[Future plc]]|last = Chalk|first = Andy|df = dmy-all}}</ref> To survive in the world, the player must gather resources and use them to craft tools, weapons, and other gear.<ref name=\"RockBF\">{{cite web|url-status = live|archive-date = 21 September 2016|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921085957/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/01/08/in-rust-your-best-friend-is-a-rock|url = http://au.ign.com/articles/2014/01/08/in-rust-your-best-friend-is-a-rock|title = In Rust, Your Best Friend is a Rock|date = 8 January 2014|accessdate = 1 July 2015|website = IGN|last = MacDonald|first = Keza|df = dmy-all}}</ref> To [[Glossary of video game terms#Crafting|craft]] items, the player must have a sufficient amount of all required materials,<ref name=\"IGN-review\"/> with advanced items needing more obscure components scattered around the map.<ref name=\"pcgamercomponents\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/latest-rust-update-removes-xp-and-levelling/|title=Latest Rust update removes XP and levelling|first=Mat|last=Paget|date=7 November 2016|access-date=7 November 2016|url-status=live|archivedate=7 November 2016|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107055932/http://www.pcgamer.com/latest-rust-update-removes-xp-and-levelling/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are limitations imposed on the amount of craftable items, with blueprints allowing the creation of more advanced items.<ref name=\"IGN-review\"/> A possibly important element in ''Rust'' is the [[airdrop]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2014-01-17-the-mod-squad-facepunchs-garry-newman-on-rust|title=\"Rust has made about 40% of what GMod made in 9 years\"|website=[[GamesIndustry]]|publisher=[[Gamer Network]]|accessdate=December 30, 2017|archivedate=29 December 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229134209/http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2014-01-17-the-mod-squad-facepunchs-garry-newman-on-rust|first=Dan|last=Pearson|date=January 20, 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> These are parachute-equipped pallets of supplies delivered by a [[Turboprop|prop plane]]. They can be seen over extremely long distances, sometimes resulting in players running towards the airdrop.<ref name=\"rps20140107\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/01/07/impressions-rust/|title=Impressions: Rust|first=Rich|last=Stanton|date=7 January 2014|access-date=22 October 2016|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|archive-date=22 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022045920/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/01/07/impressions-rust/|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are also other entities that drop advanced loot, including an [[attack helicopter]]<ref name=\"rpspremature\"/> and the [[CH-47 Chinook]]. Both of these travel randomly around the map and attempt to kill players. The Chinook additionally travels to a randomly picked monument found in the game world and drops a locked supply crate that opens after a length of time, inviting PvP interactions.<ref name=\"rpsapril\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/04/06/rust-adds-boasts/|title=Rust adds boats, improves forests, deploys choppers|first=Alice|last=O'Connor|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=25 June 2018|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615005552/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/04/06/rust-adds-boasts/|archivedate=15 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There are player-operable vehicles in ''Rust''. Boats are used to traverse long distances across water and reach valuable loot.<ref name=\"rpsboat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rusts-first-player-controlled-vehicle-has-arrived-and-its-a-boat/|title=Rust's first player-controlled vehicle has arrived, and it's a boat|date=7 April 2018|accessdate=25 June 2018|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first=Christopher|last=Livingston|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180408120110/https://www.pcgamer.com/rusts-first-player-controlled-vehicle-has-arrived-and-its-a-boat/|archivedate=8 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Some airborne vehicles, such as [[hot air balloon]]s, can also be used to explore the map quickly. Spawning randomly, they can be used once fueled. These player-controlled vehicles, and unlike the offensive AI entities, can be destroyed by [[surface-to-air missile]]s that players can position outside bases.<ref name=\"balloonspcg\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-now-has-hot-air-balloons-and-missiles-that-can-shoot-them-down/|title=Rust now has hot air balloons and missiles that can shoot them down|first=Christopher|last=Livingston|accessdate=8 November 2018|date=3 November 2018|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]}}</ref><ref name=\"febupdate\">{{Cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/february-update|title=The Air Power Update|date=7 February 2019|website=[[Facepunch]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe player must stay well fed or they will die of [[starvation]]. There are other challenges the player must overcome during gameplay, such as drowning, hypothermia, and wildlife attacks\u2014primarily bears and wolves.<ref name=\"Tips1\" /> Specific locales around the map are radioactive. There are four levels of radiation: minor, low, medium, and high. The correct armour or clothing must be worn to enter these areas; failure to do so can result in death.<ref name=\"devblog134\"/> Upon death, a screen with an option to respawn at a random location or at a sleeping bag placed prior appears. Respawning resets the player's inventory to the basic rock and torch. Clans usually create housing for their members, give items and supplies to each other and partake in organised [[Raid (gaming)|raiding]] and [[Looting (gaming)|looting]].<ref name=\"PCG-review\"/><ref name=\"letters\">{{cite web|url-status=live|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2014/02/19/rust-letters-on-deception-destruction-grief-and-griefing|title=Rust Letters: On Deception, Destruction, Grief, and Griefing|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831040229/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/02/19/rust-letters-on-deception-destruction-grief-and-griefing|archivedate=31 August 2018|accessdate=31 August 2018|date=19 February 2014|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|first1=Mitch|last1=Dyer|first2=Shawn|last2=Elliott|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"gibizinterview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2014-01-17-the-mod-squad-facepunchs-garry-newman-on-rust|website=[[Gamesindustry.biz]]|publisher=Gamer Network|title=\"Rust has made about 40% of what GMod made in 9 years\"|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831040219/https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2014-01-17-the-mod-squad-facepunchs-garry-newman-on-rust|archivedate=31 August 2018|accessdate=31 August 2018|date=20 January 2014|first=Dan|last=Pearson|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Safe zones, called Compounds, provide players with a place to trade resources, overlooked by automated high-damage [[sentry gun| auto turrets]] that fire on anyone who draws a weapon, discouraging betrayal. Additionally, these treacherous players will be marked as hostile for a predetermined amount of time.<ref name=\"pcgamermay\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-gets-a-safe-zone-in-the-new-compound-update/|title=Rust gets a safe zone in the new Compound Update|date=4 May 2018|accessdate=25 June 2018|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first=Andy|last=Chalk|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180506225405/https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-gets-a-safe-zone-in-the-new-compound-update/|archivedate=6 May 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\n[[File:Rust version comparison.jpg|thumb|right|A comparison of two different updates of ''Rust'', the top (2014) one is the earlier of the two. The bottom (2016) used an updated game engine]]\n''Rust''{{'}}s development began as a clone of ''[[DayZ (mod)|DayZ]]'',<ref name=\"clone\"/> a popular mod for ''[[ARMA 2]]'', featuring elements derived from ''[[Minecraft]]''.<ref name=\"About\">{{cite web|url=http://playrust.com/about/|title=About Rust|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|accessdate=30 June 2015|archivedate=27 June 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170627160841/http://playrust.com/about/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Garry Newman, the CEO of Facepunch Studios, said \"''Rust'' started off as a ''DayZ'' clone. But then we decided that we are sick of fighting zombies. And can't compete with the ''[[ARMA (series)|Arma]]'' island in terms of landmarks and towns.\"<ref name=\"clone\">{{cite web|url=http://garry.tv/2013/06/21/the-story-of-rust/|title=The Story of Rust|date=21 June 2013|first1=Garry|last1=Newman|accessdate=30 June 2015|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios|garry.tv]]|archive-date=21 September 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921083229/https://garry.tv/2013/06/21/the-story-of-rust/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Consequently, Newman described the game as being more along the lines of entries in the ''[[S.T.A.L.K.E.R]]'' series.<ref name=\"clone\"/> Facepunch released the game onto the Steam [[Early Access#Steam Early Access|Early Access]] program on 11 December 2013.<ref name=\"1million\"/> Following its alpha launch, Facepunch actively released updates for ''Rust'' adding mechanics like animals, [[hunting]], armour and weapons. In February 2014, the developers removed zombies, a temporary enemy, from ''Rust'', replacing them with red mutant bears and wolves.<ref name=\"RemoveZombies\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/there-are-no-more-zombies-in-rust/1100-6417584/|title=There are no more zombies in Rust|accessdate=18 May 2014|first1=Martin|last1=Gaston|date=7 February 2014|website=[[GameSpot]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090304/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/there-are-no-more-zombies-in-rust/1100-6417584/|archivedate=21 September 2016|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Early on developers made the choice not to try to populate the world with interesting locations to explore, but rather provide the ability to create them. Newman described it as \"we give them the tools, they make the world\".<ref name=\"rust-interview\">{{cite web|last1=Kelly|first1=Andy|title=Garry Newman interview: on Rust and player freedom \"we give them the tools, they make the world\"|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-interview/|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=13 February 2016|archive-date=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090313/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-interview/|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> One of the developers' aims was to create a world which does not encourage any particular kind of behaviour from players. They considered implementing a system like ''DayZ''{{'}}s where those who kill other players get unique outfits which identify them as 'bandits', or possibly a rating or color-coded system. However, the developers ultimately rejected these ideas, believing they would detract from player freedom.<ref name=\"clone\" /> Instead, they found to their surprise that the implementation of voice chat had a noticeable effect on player behavior. With the ability to communicate, many players would no longer kill each other on sight out of fear.<ref name=\"rust-interview\" />\n\nIn late 2014, developers released an experimental mode of ''Rust'' and [[Porting#Porting of video games|ported]] it to a then-unreleased [[game engine]], [[Unity (game engine)#Unity 5|Unity 5]], enhancing the graphics, and in turn, improving the [[shader]] mechanics and texture realism,<ref name=\"unity5blog\">{{cite web|url=https://blogs.unity3d.com/2014/11/19/porting-to-unity-5-the-untold-rust-journey/|title=Porting to Unity 5 \u2013 The Untold Rust Journey|publisher=[[Unity (engine)|Unity Blog]]|accessdate=31 August 2018|first=Christopher|last=Pope|date=19 November 2014|archivedate=31 August 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180831024215/https://blogs.unity3d.com/2014/11/19/porting-to-unity-5-the-untold-rust-journey/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> as well as allowed for larger [[procedurally generated]] worlds.<ref name=\"rpsnov2014\"/> The experimental mode featured a new [[anti-cheat]] system called CheatPunch, which banned thousands of players within a few days.<ref>{{cite web|url-status=live|url=http://www.develop-online.net/news/facepunch-bans-more-than-4-500-rust-players/0189163|title=Facepunch bans more than 4,500 Rust players|archivedate=21 September 2016|date=12 February 2014|accessdate=21 September 2016|website=[[Develop (magazine)|Develop]]|publisher=[[NewBay Media]]|first=Craig|last=Chapple|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921093821/http://www.develop-online.net/news/facepunch-bans-more-than-4-500-rust-players/0189163|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In October 2014, the experimental mode became the default launch option.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://playrust.com/experimental-launches-by-default/|url-status=live|archive-date=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090947/https://playrust.com/experimental-launches-by-default/|first1=Garry|last1=Newman|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|date=1 October 2014|title=Experimental Launches By Default|accessdate=9 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Shortly after, in December, [[EasyAntiCheat]], a third-party anti-cheat system, replaced CheatPunch.<ref name=\"eacupdate\">{{cite web|url=http://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-40/#more-2280|title=Devblog 40|publisher=[[Facepunch]]|date=December 28, 2014|accessdate=June 26, 2017|archivedate=26 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170626125217/http://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-40/#more-2280|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In early 2015, ''Rust'' added a feature that decided each player's [[Race (human categorization)|skin colour]] tied to their [[Steam (software)|Steam]] ID.<ref name=\"kotakumessy\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kotaku.com.au/2015/03/rust-chooses-players-race-for-them-things-get-messy/|title=Rust Chooses Players' Race For Them, Things Get Messy|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gizmodo Media Group]]|accessdate=27 June 2018|date=26 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627173133/https://www.kotaku.com.au/2015/03/rust-chooses-players-race-for-them-things-get-messy/|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn the original game, the [[HUD (video gaming)|heads-up display]] featured statistics like as [[Health (video game)|health]], hunger and [[radiation]] level.<ref name=\"Tips1\">{{cite web|url = http://www.usgamer.net/articles/rust-a-beginners-survival-guide|title = Rust Guide: How to Get Started, Beginners Hints and Tips|date = 24 January 2014|accessdate = 1 July 2015|publisher = [[Eurogamer]]|last = Williams|first = Mike|website = [[USgamer]]|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090017/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/rust-a-beginners-survival-guide|archivedate = 21 September 2016|df = dmy-all}}</ref> These were later modified and hidden statistics such as [[hypothermia]] were added.<ref name=\"Racism1\">{{cite web|url = http://america.aljazeera.com/opinions/2015/5/the-online-game-that-proves-the-web-is-not-a-post-racial-utopia.html|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090953/http://america.aljazeera.com/opinions/2015/5/the-online-game-that-proves-the-web-is-not-a-post-racial-utopia.html|archivedate = 21 September 2016|title = The Web is not a post-racial utopia|date = 24 May 2015|accessdate = 1 July 2015|website = [[Al Jazeera English|Al Jazeera]]|publisher = [[Al Jazeera Media Network]]|last = Condis|first = Megan|df = dmy-all}}</ref> Monuments went through a phase where developers removed the radiation hazards because of the annoyance it was causing.<ref name=\"monuments1\">{{cite web|url=http://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-71/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090957/https://playrust.com/devblog-71/|archivedate=21 September 2016|title=Devblog 71|access-date=16 January 2016|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|date=30 July 2015|first=Craig|last=Pearson|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"monuments2\">{{cite web|url=http://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-77/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921091001/https://playrust.com/devblog-77/|archivedate=21 September 2016|title=Devblog 77|access-date=16 January 2016|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|date=10 September 2015|first=Craig|last=Pearson|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Female models, added to the game shortly afterward, were initially only available for [[server (computing)|server]] [[Server administrator|administrators]] to test. Upon rollout, akin to skin colour, players were automatically assigned a [[biological sex]] permanently linked to their Steam account.<ref name=\"womanmodel1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/female-models-come-to-rust-but-only-for-admins/|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150728064842/http://www.pcgamer.com/female-models-come-to-rust-but-only-for-admins/|title=Female models come to Rust, but only for admins|first1=Andy|last1=Chalk|date=16 July 2015|access-date=28 July 2015|archive-date=28 July 2015|publisher=[[Future plc]]|website=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref> Later in 2015, [[virtual goods]] stores selling guns, clothing and other objects were added to the game. When [[Valve Corporation|Valve]] introduced its Item Store, ''Rust'' was the first game on Steam to use the feature.<ref name=\"itemstoresteamed\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921091004/http://steamed.kotaku.com/steam-has-added-new-item-store-functionality-now-in-1740586891|url-status=live|archivedate=21 September 2016|url=http://steamed.kotaku.com/steam-has-added-new-item-store-functionality-now-in-1740586891|title=Steam has added a new \u2018item store\u2019 feature|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|date=4 November 2015|access-date=6 February 2016|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Steam (software)#Storefront features|Steam Community Market]] was also allowed to sell similar items.<ref name=\"itemstorepcgamer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/steam-item-stores-roll-out-with-new-update-debut-in-rust/|title=Steam 'Item Stores' roll out with new update, debut in Rust|website=[[PC Gamer]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921091009/http://www.pcgamer.com/steam-item-stores-roll-out-with-new-update-debut-in-rust/|archive-date=21 September 2016|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first=Andy|last=Chalk|date=4 November 2015|access-date=6 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"itemstorerps\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/11/05/rust-item-store/|title=Rust Adds Item Store For Modders To Sell Cosmetics|publisher=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|first=Graham|last=Smith|date=5 November 2015|access-date=14 February 2016|archive-date=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921091019/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/11/05/rust-item-store/|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDevelopers removed [[blueprint]]s, one of the core gameplay concepts of ''Rust'', in July 2016. They replaced them with an [[experience point|experience]] system where players could level up after completing tasks, such as gathering wood.<ref name=\"pcgamerxp1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-introduces-xp-system/|title=Rust introduces XP system|first=Angus|last=Morrison|date=8 July 2016|access-date=9 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160709114026/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-introduces-xp-system/|url-status=live|archive-date=9 July 2016|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]}}</ref><ref name=\"devblog100\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-07-09-big-rust-update-ditches-blueprints-introduces-xp-and-levelling|title=Big Rust update ditches blueprints, introduces XP and levelling|access-date=11 July 2016|first=Robert|last=Purchese|date=9 July 2016|website=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|url-status=live|archive-date=11 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160711133700/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-07-09-big-rust-update-ditches-blueprints-introduces-xp-and-levelling}}</ref> In September, lead developer Maurino Berry mentioned in a [[Reddit]] post that there was a chance the experience system would no longer exist in the future. Before saying this, Berry wrote in one of the devblogs \"the XP system had huge praise until it was released, and then lots of people hated it\".<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917095123/http://www.pcgamer.com/rusts-xp-system-isnt-working-very-well-will-likely-be-removed/|url-status=live|archive-date=17 September 2016|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rusts-xp-system-isnt-working-very-well-will-likely-be-removed/|date=12 September 2016|first=Shaun|last=Prescott|access-date=17 September 2016|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|title=Rust's XP system isn't working very well, will likely be removed|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In early November 2016, components replaced the experience system.<ref name=\"pcgamercomponents\"/> Originally, players had an initial list of items they could craft. This was changed to having a complete list with the required components from the outset.<ref name=\"pcgamercomponents\"/> Radiation, removed in 2015, was reintroduced in November 2016 after being \"reprogrammed from the ground up\".<ref name=\"devblog134\">{{cite web|url=http://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-134/|title=Devblog 134|first=Craig|last=Pearson|access-date=7 November 2016|date=3 November 2016|archivedate=7 November 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161107060602/https://playrust.com/devblog-134/|url-status=live|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Instead of each location having the same level of radiation, developers added different levels ranging from low, to medium, and high.<ref name=\"devblog134\"/>\n\nIn early 2017, Garry Newman said that had Steam Early Access not existed, ''Rust'' would have been fully released as a game by then. The development team would have continued to release updates.<ref name=\"rpstrad\"/> In June 2017, developers altered the game's gun mechanics to be more like \"traditional first-person shooters\".<ref name=\"rpstrad\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2017/06/05/rust-recoil-changed/|title=Gleaming! Rust overhauls recoil and inaccuracy|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|accessdate=December 31, 2017|archivedate=31 December 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171231013618/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2017/06/05/rust-recoil-changed/|first=Alice|last=O'Connor|date=June 5, 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This was achieved by reducing recoil, material costs, and improving overall accuracy.<ref name=\"pcgamertrad\"/> This update also saw the beginnings of an overhaul of Hapis Island, the game's only non-[[procedurally generated]] map.<ref name=\"pcgamertrad\"/> The game left Early Access and was officially released on 8 February 2018,<ref name=\"leave1\"/> along with graphical and gun changes.<ref name=\"overhaul1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-marks-end-of-four-year-long-early-access-with-a-visual-overhaul/|title=Rust marks end of four-year Early Access with a visual overhaul|first=Samuel |last=Horti|date=11 February 2018|accessdate=13 February 2018|url-status=live|archivedate=13 February 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213105702/https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-marks-end-of-four-year-long-early-access-with-a-visual-overhaul/|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]}}</ref> By this time, blueprints had been reinstated.<ref name=\"IGN-review\"/> Newman mentioned that despite the official release, regular updates would continue. He noted the update cycle would change from weekly to monthly so as not to \"rush in features and fixes that end up breaking something else\".<ref name=\"leave1\">{{cite web|last1=Chalk|first1=Andy|title=Rust will leave Early Access in February, but it's not finished yet|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-will-leave-early-access-in-february-but-its-not-finished-yet/|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=23 January 2018|url-status=live|date=22 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123034606/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-will-leave-early-access-in-february-but-its-not-finished-yet/|archivedate=23 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nPost release, Facepunch have continued to support the game with updates that added new features, including graphical overhauls<ref name=\"overhaul1\"/> and new guns.<ref name=\"dev198\">{{Cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-198/|title=Devblog 198|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|accessdate=25 June 2018|date=1 March 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625121419/https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/devblog-198/|archivedate=25 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> April 2018 was the first big update post-Early Access. This update added the first player-operable vehicle, a boat, and a new hostile entity, a CH-47 Chinook.<ref name=\"rpsapril\"/> One month later ''Rust'' saw the addition of Compounds, safe areas guarded by scientists, [[non-player characters]] Facepunch had hinted at before<ref name=\"scientisttease\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-could-get-creepy-npc-scientists-that-ignore-your-naked-caveman-murders/|title=Rust could get creepy NPC scientists that ignore your naked caveman murders|first=Tom|last=Sykes|date=28 November 2015|accessdate=27 June 2018|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627144422/https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-could-get-creepy-npc-scientists-that-ignore-your-naked-caveman-murders/|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and high-damage turrets. The update also added [[scuba diving]] equipment to allow for the ocean to be explored easier.<ref name=\"pcgamermay\"/> The ocean-related gameplay was addressed again in October, when ''Rust'' saw the addition of a [[cargo ship]] that allowed for visitation, the \"CCSC Lazarus\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/10/05/rust-has-added-a-big-radioactive-boat-for-you-to-squabble-over/|title=Rust has added a big radioactive boat for you to squabble over|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|date=5 October 2018|first=Matt|last=Cox|accessdate=20 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005143450/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/10/05/rust-has-added-a-big-radioactive-boat-for-you-to-squabble-over/|archive-date=5 October 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Similar in nature to the addition of player-operable boats, early November saw the addition of the first flying vehicle: hot air balloons. Additional weapons were also added at the same time.<ref name=\"balloonspcg\"/> In December, ''Rust'' saw the addition of electricity, and with it, new components and weapons.<ref name=\"electricitypcgamer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-finally-gives-its-naked-citizens-underwear-electricity/|title=Rust finally gives its naked citizens underwear, electricity|date=7 December 2018|accessdate=19 July 2019|archivedate=19 July 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719121231/https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-finally-gives-its-naked-citizens-underwear-electricity/|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|url-status=live|first=Christopher|last=Livingston}}</ref>\n\n''Rust'' continues to see updates into 2019, with gradual graphical and stability improvements, as well as major feature additions. February's update was dubbed the \"Air Power Update\" and saw the minicopter, a new player controllable vehicle.<ref name=\"febupdate\"/> In the June and July updates, horses, another player controllable entity, were added and further developed, seeing improvements and the introduction of new [[List of horse breeds|breeds]].<ref name=\"junupdate\">{{cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/june-update|title=Giddy Up!|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|access-date=19 July 2019|url-status=live|date=7 June 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"julupdate\">{{cite web|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/july-update|title=July Update|publisher=[[Facepunch Studios]]|access-date=19 July 2019|url-status=live|date=4 July 2019}}</ref> Also in June was the addition of a playable [[arcade cabinet]] to commemorate the release of Facepunch's ''[[Chippy (2019 video game)|Chippy]]'', a new [[bullet hell]]-style game.<ref name=\"junupdate\"/><ref name=\"pcgamerchippy\">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719122801/https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-and-garrys-mod-devs-release-chippy-a-bullet-hell-shooter/|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-and-garrys-mod-devs-release-chippy-a-bullet-hell-shooter/|work=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|archivedate=19 July 2019|accessdate=19 July 2019|first=Samuel|last=Horti|date=15 June 2019|title=Rust and Garry's Mod devs release Chippy, a bullet hell shooter}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===In Early Access===\n''Rust'' received mixed reviews following its alpha release, with many denoting the unfinished nature and lack of polish.<ref name=\"1yearonreview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamesn.com/rust-early-access-review|title=Rust Early Access review: one year on|last1=Purslow|first1=Matt|date=16 January 2015|website=[[PCGamesN]]|publisher=Network N|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702104456/http://www.pcgamesn.com/rust-early-access-review|archive-date=2 July 2015|url-status=live|access-date=2 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"gamespotea\"/> ''[[PC Gamer]]''{{'}}s Andy Chalk said ''Rust'' was a great use of Early Access and even though \"it's far from finished\", it's ready to be played.<ref name=\"PCGReview1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-alpha-review/|first1=Andy|last1=Chalk|title=Rust alpha review|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702102330/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-alpha-review/|archive-date=2 July 2015|date=10 January 2014|access-date=2 July 2015|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]}}</ref> ''[[GameSpot]]''{{'}}s Shaun McInnis said the early 2014 version was \"rough around the edges\" and \"littered with bugs\", but it entertained and had potential.<ref name=\"gamespotea\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rust-early-access-review/1100-6417381/|title=Rust Early Access Review|access-date=28 June 2016|website=[[GameSpot]]|first=Shaun|last=McInnis|date=28 January 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303202546/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rust-early-access-review/1100-6417381/|archivedate=3 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Matthew Cox of ''[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]'' said it was smart of the developers to switch to the [[Unity engine]] in late 2014 due to the game's instability. In Cox's review, he noted many glitches in the late 2014 version, including unresponsive animals, [[framerate]] issues and unstable servers.<ref name=\"rpsnov2014\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/11/26/rust-new-version-review/|title=Impressions: Rust\u2019s New Version|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]|first=Matthew|last=Cox|date=26 November 2014|access-date=28 June 2016|url-status=live|archivedate=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921090319/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2014/11/26/rust-new-version-review/|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''IGN''{{'}}s Mitch Dyer did not enjoy the combat, calling ''Rust'' a \"semi-broken\" game he felt unable to recommend.<ref name=\"igndayzmc\"/>\n\nOther games like ''[[The Forest (video game)|The Forest]]'', ''[[Just Survive]]'', ''[[Ark: Survival Evolved]]''<ref name=\"ArkRelation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/ark-survival-evolved-sells-one-million-copies-in-less-than-a-month/|title=Ark: Survival Evolved sells one million copies in less than a month|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first1=Andy|last1=Chalk|date=2 July 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706100932/http://www.pcgamer.com/ark-survival-evolved-sells-one-million-copies-in-less-than-a-month/|archive-date=6 July 2015|access-date=6 July 2015}}</ref> and ''[[7 Days to Die]]'' were compared to ''Rust'' because of their open world survival aspects, as well as having crafting mechanics similar to ''Rust''.<ref name=\"H1Z1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/05/08/rust-h1z1-and-the-emerging-survival-mmo-genre/|title=Rust, H1Z1, and the emerging 'survival MMO' genre|url-status=live|first1=Andrew|last1=Ross|date=8 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630050059/http://www.engadget.com/2014/05/08/rust-h1z1-and-the-emerging-survival-mmo-genre/|archive-date=30 June 2015|website=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> ''Kotaku''{{'}}s Luke Plunkett noted the similarities, saying it felt as though someone had thought of a game whereby ''Dayz'' and ''Minecraft'' could be played simultaneously.<ref name=\"kotakudayzvsmc\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/rust-is-dayz-vs-minecraft-and-it-will-kick-your-ass-1497654260|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092707/http://kotaku.com/rust-is-dayz-vs-minecraft-and-it-will-kick-your-ass-1497654260|archivedate=21 September 2016|url-status=live|title=Rust Is DayZ vs Minecraft, And It Will Kick Your Ass|first=Luke|last=Plunkett|date=9 January 2014|access-date=28 June 2016|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Dyer, while criticising ''Rust'' due to its bugs, called parts of the experience \"utterly unforgettable\" and often unpredictable.<ref name=\"igndayzmc\">{{cite web|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2013/12/20/rust-the-terrifying-minecraft-dayz-open-world-survival-sim|title=Rust: The Terrifying Minecraft + DayZ Open World Survival Sim|access-date=28 June 2016|first=Mitch|last=Dyer|website=[[IGN]]|date=20 December 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092624/http://au.ign.com/articles/2013/12/20/rust-the-terrifying-minecraft-dayz-open-world-survival-sim|archive-date=21 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe inability to choose and design a player's character was both commended and criticised. The [[YouTube]] channel ''[[Extra Credits]]'' commended ''Rust'' for promoting diversity by randomly selecting a player's in-game race. Tying race to their Steam ID forced players to experience the game in a different way than they might normally experience it, perhaps promoting [[empathy]] for someone of a different ethnicity.<ref name=\"ExtraCreditCharSelect\">{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eh1zfdUTqBY | title=Rust - Representing Race in Games - Extra Credits | publisher=[[YouTube]] | date=27 May 2015 | accessdate=31 August 2015 | author=Extra Credits | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120090719/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eh1zfdUTqBY | archivedate=20 November 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> David Craddock of ''[[Shacknews]]'' criticised the lack of communication between Facepunch and the community when they added female models.<ref name=\"communicationcraddock\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shacknews.com/article/94189/opinion-how-facepunch-failed-to-communicate-gender-assignment-in-rust|title=Opinion: How Facepunch failed to communicate gender assignment in Rust|date=18 April 2016|access-date=14 June 2016|first=David|last=Craddock|url-status=live|publisher=[[Shacknews]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614112541/http://www.shacknews.com/article/94189/opinion-how-facepunch-failed-to-communicate-gender-assignment-in-rust|archive-date=14 June 2016}}</ref> In response to this criticism, Garry Newman commented he felt some trepidation about adding the racial feature, fearing it might be seen as the original character model \"[[Blackface|blacked up]]\". He stressed the chosen ethnicity was permanent\u2014\"just like in real life, you are who you are\".<ref name=\"racialempathy\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rust-experiments-with-racial-empathy-randomly-assi/1100-6426197/ | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092554/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/rust-experiments-with-racial-empathy-randomly-assi/1100-6426197/ | archive-date=21 September 2016 | title=Rust Experiments With Racial Empathy, Randomly Assigns Skin Color | website=[[GameSpot]] | date=26 March 2015 | accessdate=2 November 2015 | last=Starkey | first=Daniel | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Newman discussed the reasoning behind not providing the option to choose their character's gender and race in an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'', saying ''Rust'' is about survival, not characterization and identity. \"We wanted the appearance of the players to be consistent over time. They should be recognisable consistently and long-term.\"<ref name=\"garrytheguardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/apr/13/videogame-chooses-character-race-gender-rust|title=Why my videogame chooses your character\u2019s race and gender for you|first=Garry|url-status=live|last=Newman|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=14 April 2016|access-date=14 June 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614113408/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/apr/13/videogame-chooses-character-race-gender-rust|archive-date=14 June 2016}}</ref> Sales reportedly increased by 74% shortly after the addition of female models.<ref name=\"skyrocketsales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2016/04/23/rust-female-character-models-sales-jump-bullet-with-butterfly-wings/|title=Sales skyrocketed after 'Rust' added female character models|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092625/https://www.engadget.com/2016/04/23/rust-female-character-models-sales-jump-bullet-with-butterfly-wings/|archivedate=21 September 2016|first=Timothy|last=Seppala|website=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[AOL]]|access-date=28 June 2016|date=23 April 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"skyrocketsales2\">{{cite web|url=http://steamed.kotaku.com/rusts-controversial-random-gender-update-has-led-to-mor-1772390030|title=Rust's Controversial Random Gender Update Has Led To More Players|website=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|first=Nathan|last=Grayson|date=22 April 2016|access-date=28 June 2016|url-status=live|archive-date=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921092223/http://steamed.kotaku.com/rusts-controversial-random-gender-update-has-led-to-mor-1772390030|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Sales====\nWithin the first two weeks of ''Rust''{{'}}s alpha release it sold over 150,000 copies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/207990/Garrys_Mod_creator_finds_unexpected_success_with_new_game_Rust.php|title=Garry's Mod creator finds unexpected success with new game Rust|url-status=live|archivedate=21 September 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092701/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/207990/Garrys_Mod_creator_finds_unexpected_success_with_new_game_Rust.php|last=Wawro|first=Alex|date=3 January 2014|work=[[Gamasutra]]|publisher=[[UBM TechWeb]]|accessdate=5 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> compared to the 34,000 copies of ''[[Garry's Mod]]'' sold in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.facepunchstudios.com/2014/01/03/gmod-vs-rust-launch/|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160921092234/http://www.facepunchstudios.com/2014/01/03/gmod-vs-rust-launch/|archivedate = 21 September 2016|title = GMod vs Rust Launch|date = 3 January 2014|access-date = 12 February 2016|publisher = [[Facepunch]]|last = Newman|first = Garry|df = dmy-all}}</ref> ''Rust''{{'}}s sales had reached one million copies after being an Early Access title for only two months,<ref name=\"1million\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/2014/02/11/rust-hits-1-million-sales-after-two-months/|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092531/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-hits-1-million-sales-after-two-months/|archive-date=21 September 2016|title=Rust hits 1 million sales after two months|last=Petitte|first=Omri|date=11 February 2014|work=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=11 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and during February 2014, it overtook ''[[Garry's Mod]]'' in terms of sales, making over {{US$|30&nbsp;million|link=yes}}.<ref name=\"30million\">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/2/21/5433886/garrys-mod-sales-30m-rust|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092308/http://www.polygon.com/2014/2/21/5433886/garrys-mod-sales-30m-rust|archivedate=21 September 2016|title=Garry's Mod sales hit $30M, Rust eclipses it|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|first1=Samit|last1=Sarkar|date=21 February 2014|access-date=2 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> By the end of 2015, three million copies had been sold.<ref name=\"3mil\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-sales-pass-the-three-million-mark/|title=Rust sales pass the three million mark|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160921092642/http://www.pcgamer.com/rust-sales-pass-the-three-million-mark/|archivedate=21 September 2016|first1=Tom|last1=Sykes|website=[[PC Gamer]]|date=24 December 2015|access-date=3 January 2015|publisher=[[Future plc]]|df=dmy-all}}</ref> By March 2017, the game had sold more than 5.2 million units, with more than 1.2 million in-game skins sold.<ref>{{cite web|title=Community Update 127|url=https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/community-update-127/|accessdate=3 July 2017|date=14 March 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704013413/https://rust.facepunch.com/blog/community-update-127/|archivedate=4 July 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In December 2019, Facepunch announced that ''Rust'' had sold 9 million copies, making $142 million, overtaking ''Garry's Mod'' in terms of [[Gross (economics)|gross]], though still behind in total sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-has-made-more-money-than-garrys-mod/|title=Rust has made more money than Garry\u2019s Mod|date=21 December 2019|accessdate=23 December 2019|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|first= Jonathan |last=Bolding|url-status=live|archivedate=23 December 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191222141629/https://www.pcgamer.com/au/rust-has-made-more-money-than-garrys-mod/}}</ref>\n\n===Full release===\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = 69/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/rust |title=Rust for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=17 June 2018|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617094907/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/rust|archivedate=17 June 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| Destruct = 8/10<ref name=\"Destructoid-review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-rust-490145.phtml|first=Ray|last=Porreca|accessdate=17 June 2018|website=[[Destructoid]]|title=Review: Rust|date=19 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180625121417/https://www.destructoid.com/review-rust-490145.phtml|archivedate=25 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| GI = 6.5/10<ref name=\"GI-review\">{{cite magazine |last=Gwaltney |first=Javy |date=February 13, 2018 |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/games/rust/b/pc/archive/2018/02/13/more-rough-than-diamond.aspx |title=More Rough Than Diamond - Rust - PC |magazine=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=February 19, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221213403/http://www.gameinformer.com/games/rust/b/pc/archive/2018/02/13/more-rough-than-diamond.aspx |archivedate=21 February 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| GSpot = 3/10<ref name=\"GS-review\">{{cite web |last=Barbosa |first=Alessandro |date=February 17, 2018 |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rust-review-life-is-fleeting/1900-6416858/ |title=Rust Review: Life Is Fleeting |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=February 19, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033111/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/rust-review-life-is-fleeting/1900-6416858/ |archivedate=20 February 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| IGN = 7/10<ref name=\"IGN-review\">{{cite web|url=http://au.ign.com/articles/2018/02/24/rust-review|title=Rust Review|accessdate=10 March 2018|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|author=GB Burford|date=February 28, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180310110314/http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/02/24/rust-review|archivedate=10 March 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| PCGUS = 80/100<ref name=\"PCG-review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-review/|title=Rust Review|first=Luke|last=Winkie|website=[[PC Gamer]]|publisher=[[Future plc]]|accessdate=27 June 2018|date=19 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627115724/https://www.pcgamer.com/rust-review/|archive-date=27 June 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[GameStar]]''\n| rev1Score= 69/100<ref name=\"GameStar-review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamestar.de/artikel/rust-zwischen-steinzeit-und-menschlichen-abgruenden,3326749.html|title=Rust im Test - Zwischen Steinzeit und menschlichen Abgr\u00fcnden|language=German|first=Gloria|last=Maderfeld|accessdate=27 June 2018|date=1 March 2018|website=[[GameStar]]|publisher=[[Webedia]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330225844/https://www.gamestar.de/artikel/rust-zwischen-steinzeit-und-menschlichen-abgruenden,3326749.html|archive-date=30 March 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAfter being fully released, ''Rust'' garnered \"mixed or average\" reviews on [[review aggregator]] website [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC\" /> Critics praised the PvP combat, difficulty, and survival aspects, while grinding and the experience had by new players came under some criticism.<ref name=\"GameStar-review\"/><ref name=\"RPS-review\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/02/12/rust-review|title=Wot I Think: Rust|first=Matt|last=Cox|date=12 February 2018|accessdate=13 February 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214142100/https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/02/12/rust-review/|archivedate=14 February 2018|df=dmy-all|website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]}}</ref><ref name=\"PCG-review\"/>\n\nMany critics held the opinion that while starting anew was frustrating, the combat was rewarding. For instance, Luke Winkie of ''[[PC Gamer]]'' summarised the game saying, \"Wake up naked, run for your life, do horrible things to one another. There is no grander narrative, or [[mythos]], or win condition.\"<ref name=\"PCG-review\"/> He described the beginner experience as \"quite prickly\" but continued on to praise the combat, joking that \"connecting [a] hatchet with an idiot's head feels great\". Gloria Manderfeld, a writer for the German magazine ''[[GameStar]]'', echoed these opinions, adding there was little end-game besides PvP. However, she opined the PvP itself was effective.<ref name=\"GameStar-review\"/> Ray Porreca of ''[[Destructoid]]'' described the combat as the \"meat\" of the game. However, he wrote that the experience would vary depending on their desire to fight. \"If you can look past a community that tends to be [[Glossary_of_video_game_terms#toxicity|toxic]], ''Rust''{{'}}s sprawling plains and toppled landmarks are an excellent backdrop for player-driven storytelling and pitched, dramatic moments.\"<ref name=\"Destructoid-review\"/> In a negative review ''[[GameSpot]]''{{'}}s Alessandro Barbosa said the whole experience felt unfulfilling. He described the game as lacking certain creative features, like the ability to easily redesign bases.<ref name=\"GS-review\"/>\n\nThe disdain towards the experience as a new player was noted in conjunction with the necessity of grinding, and how repetitive that became. ''[[IGN]]''{{'}}s review described the game as expecting the player to spend all their gaming time on it, fearing that failing to do so will result in being raided and needing to begin again.<ref name=\"IGN-review\"/> ''[[Game Informer]]''{{'}}s Javy Gwaltney reiterated this, explaining it felt demotivating when they died solely because they came in contact with someone more experienced.<ref name=\"GI-review\"/> Agreeing with Manderfeld's description,<ref name=\"GameStar-review\"/> in an updated review Cox said his patience wore thin after a while. He said that while maintaining [[health (gaming)|health bars]] may have once been enjoyable, he balked at the prospect in 2018.<ref name=\"RPS-review\"/>\n\nNonetheless, some critics praised the game's difficulty, mentioning the satisfaction they felt after managing to survive successfully. Porreca recommended the game to those willing to dedicate time, saying the game offers \"a social sandbox and a deep, functioning crafting system\".<ref name=\"Destructoid-review\"/> Winkie expressed interest in the necessity of managing hunger, thirst, and health while learning more and discovering better items. He also expressed a sense of appreciation for those dedicated to the game, mentioning the YouTube videos of large, multi-clan raids. He closed the review saying everyone should try ''Rust'' due to its difference from other games.<ref name=\"PCG-review\"/> Cox agreed noting the game's brutality only added to the gratification a player felt when they managed to eventually succeed.<ref name=\"RPS-review\"/>\n\nThe reception towards the graphics were mixed. Critics praised the environment, but denounced the animations and character models.<ref name=\"GI-review\"/> Barbosa described the animations as \"stiff and unnatural\" and the models \"ugly and dull\".<ref name=\n\"GS-review\"/> Additionally, the way ''Rust'' uses sound was commended by Gwaltney, who explained it as being compelling due to the way players must listen for others in order to survive.<ref name=\"GI-review\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{portal|Video games}}\n* {{Official website|rust.facepunch.com}}\n\n[[Category:2018 video games]]\n[[Category:Early access video games]]\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Steam Workshop games]]\n[[Category:Survival video games]]\n[[Category:Unity (game engine) games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Video games that support Vulkan]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Xbox One games]]\n", "name_user": "Nealbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: Playstation \u2192 PlayStation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rust_(video_game)"}
{"title_page": "Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Species of coronavirus causing SARS and COVID-19}}\n{{about|a '''species''' of coronavirus comprising multiple strains|the ''strain'' that causes [[SARS]]|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|the ''strain'' that causes COVID-19|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2}}\n{{Virusbox\n| image          = SARS-CoV with corona.jpg\n| image_caption  = [[Transmission electron micrograph]] of SARS-related coronaviruses emerging from host cells cultured in the lab\n| parent         = Sarbecovirus\n| species        = Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus\n| authority      = \n| synonyms       = *''SARS coronavirus''\n*''SARS-related coronavirus''\n*''Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus''<ref name=\"TaxHist\">{{cite web |title=ICTV Taxonomy history: ''Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus'' |url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/taxonomy/p/taxonomy-history?taxnode_id=20181868 |website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) |access-date=27 January 2019 |language=en |format=html}}</ref>\n| synonyms_ref   = \n| subdivision_ranks = Strains\n| subdivision    = \n[[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS-CoV]]\n<br/> [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n<br/> [[Bat SARS-like coronavirus WIV1]] \n<br/> Numerous other bat strains\n}}\n\n'''''Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus''''' ('''''SARS-CoV''''')<ref group=note> The terms '''SARS-CoV''' and '''SARSr-CoV''' are sometimes used interchangeably, especially prior to the discovery of SARS-CoV-2.</ref> is a species of [[coronavirus]] that infects [[humans]], [[bats]] and certain other [[mammals]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Branswell |first=Helen | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.statnews.com/2015/11/09/sars-like-virus-bats-shows-potential-infect-humans-study-finds/|title=SARS-like virus in bats shows potential to infect humans, study finds|date=9 November 2015|work=Stat News|access-date=20 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wong AC, Li X, Lau SK, Woo PC | title = Global Epidemiology of Bat Coronaviruses | journal = Viruses | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 174 | date = February 2019 | pmid = 30791586 | pmc = 6409556 | doi = 10.3390/v11020174 | quote = Most notably, horseshoe bats were found to be the reservoir of SARS-like CoVs, while palm civet cats are considered to be the intermediate host for SARS-CoVs [43,44,45]. }}</ref> It is an [[Viral envelope|enveloped]] [[positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus]] that enters its host cell by binding to the [[ACE2]] receptor.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is a member of the genus ''[[Betacoronavirus]]'' and subgenus ''Sarbecoronavirus''.<ref name=\"ICTV10\">{{cite web |title=Virus Taxonomy: 2018 Release |url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/taxonomy/ |website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) |access-date=13 January 2019 |language=en |date=October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Woo PC, Huang Y, Lau SK, Yuen KY | title = Coronavirus genomics and bioinformatics analysis | journal = Viruses | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 1804\u201320 | date = August 2010 | pmid = 21994708 | pmc = 3185738 | doi = 10.3390/v2081803 | quote = Figure 2. Phylogenetic analysis of RNA-dependent RNA polymerases (Pol) of coronaviruses with complete genome sequences available. The tree was constructed by the neighbor-joining method and rooted using Breda virus polyprotein. }}</ref>\n\nTwo strains of the virus have caused outbreaks of severe [[respiratory diseases]] in humans: [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS-CoV]] (or SARS-CoV-1), which caused [[2002-2004 SARS outbreak|the 2002-2004 outbreak]] of [[severe acute respiratory syndrome]] (SARS), and [[SARS-CoV-2]], which is causing \nthe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19).<ref name=\"CVSG\">{{cite journal | title = The species Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus: classifying 2019-nCoV and naming it SARS-CoV-2 | journal = Nature Microbiology | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32123347 | doi = 10.1038/s41564-020-0695-z | author1 = Coronaviridae Study Group of the International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses | volume = 5 | issue = 4 | pages = 536\u2013544 }}</ref><ref name=\"SCI\">{{cite journal |last1=Kohen |first1=Jon |last2=Kupferschmidth |first2=Kai |title=Strategies shift as coronavirus pandemic looms |journal=Science |date=28 February 2020 |volume=367 |issue=6481 |pages=962\u2013963 |doi=10.1126/science.367.6481.962 |pmid=32108093 |bibcode=2020Sci...367..962C }}</ref> There are hundreds of other strains of SARS-CoV, all of which are only known to infect non-human species: [[Bat-borne virus|bats are a major reservoir]] of many strains of SARS-related coronaviruses, and several strains have been identified in [[palm civet]]s, which were likely ancestors of SARS-CoV.<ref name=\"CVSG\" /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lau SK, Li KS, Huang Y, Shek CT, Tse H, Wang M, Choi GK, Xu H, Lam CS, Guo R, Chan KH, Zheng BJ, Woo PC, Yuen KY | display-authors = 6 | title = Ecoepidemiology and complete genome comparison of different strains of severe acute respiratory syndrome-related Rhinolophus bat coronavirus in China reveal bats as a reservoir for acute, self-limiting infection that allows recombination events | journal = Journal of Virology | volume = 84 | issue = 6 | pages = 2808\u201319 | date = March 2010 | pmid = 20071579 | pmc = 2826035 | doi = 10.1128/JVI.02219-09 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\nThe SARS-related coronavirus was one of several viruses identified by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) in 2016 as a likely cause of a future epidemic in a new plan developed after the [[Western African Ebola virus epidemic|Ebola epidemic]] for urgent research and development before and during an epidemic towards diagnostic tests, [[vaccines]] and medicines. The prediction came to pass with the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kieny|first1=Marie-Paule | name-list-format = vanc |title=After Ebola, a Blueprint Emerges to Jump-Start R&D|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/after-ebola-a-blueprint-emerges-to-jump-start-r-d/|website=Scientific American Blog Network|access-date=13 December 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220134725/https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/after-ebola-a-blueprint-emerges-to-jump-start-r-d/|archive-date=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=LIST OF PATHOGENS|url=http://www.who.int/csr/research-and-development/list_of_pathogens/en/|website=World Health Organization|access-date=13 December 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220180509/http://www.who.int/csr/research-and-development/list_of_pathogens/en/|archive-date=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Classification ==\nSARS-related coronavirus is a member of the genus ''[[Betacoronavirus|Betacoronavirus]]'' (group 2) and subgenus ''Sarbecovirus'' (subgroup B).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wong AC, Li X, Lau SK, Woo PC | title = Global Epidemiology of Bat Coronaviruses | journal = Viruses | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 174 | date = February 2019 | pmid = 30791586 | pmc = 6409556 | doi = 10.3390/v11020174 | quote = See Figure 1. }}</ref>  Sarbecoviruses, unlike [[Embecovirus|embecoviruses]] or [[Alphacoronavirus|alphacoronaviruses]], only have one papain-like proteinase (PLpro) instead of two in the [[open reading frame]] ORF1.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Woo PC, Huang Y, Lau SK, Yuen KY | title = Coronavirus genomics and bioinformatics analysis | journal = Viruses | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 1804\u201320 | date = August 2010 | pmid = 21994708 | pmc = 3185738 | doi = 10.3390/v2081803 | quote = See Figure 1. }}</ref> SARSr-CoV was determined to be an early split-off from the betacoronaviruses based on a set of conserved domains that it shares with the group.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Woo PC, Huang Y, Lau SK, Yuen KY | title = Coronavirus genomics and bioinformatics analysis | journal = Viruses | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 1804\u201320 | date = August 2010 | pmid = 21994708 | pmc = 3185738 | doi = 10.3390/v2081803 | quote = Furthermore, subsequent phylogenetic analysis using both complete genome sequence and proteomic approaches, it was concluded that SARSr-CoV is probably an early split-off from the Betacoronavirus lineage [1]; See Figure 2. }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/ictv-reports/ictv_9th_report/positive-sense-rna-viruses-2011/w/posrna_viruses/223/coronaviridae-figures|title=Coronaviridae - Figures - Positive Sense RNA Viruses - Positive Sense RNA Viruses (2011) | work = International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)|language=en |access-date=2020-03-06|quote=See Figure 2.}}</ref>\n\nBats serve as the main host reservoir for the SARS-related coronavirus. The virus has coevolved in the [[Bat-borne virus|bat host reservoir]] over a long period of time.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gouilh MA, Puechmaille SJ, Gonzalez JP, Teeling E, Kittayapong P, Manuguerra JC | title = SARS-Coronavirus ancestor's foot-prints in South-East Asian bat colonies and the refuge theory | journal = Infection, Genetics and Evolution | volume = 11 | issue = 7 | pages = 1690\u2013702 | date = October 2011 | pmid = 21763784 | doi = 10.1016/j.meegid.2011.06.021 | quote = Betacoronaviruses-b ancestors, meaning SARSr-CoVs ancestors, could have been historically hosted by the common ancestor of the Rhinolophidae and Hipposideridae and could have later evolved independently in the lineages leading towards Rhinolophidae and Hipposideridae betacoronaviruses. }}</ref> Only recently have strains of SARS-related coronavirus evolved and made the [[Cross-species transmission|cross-species jump]] from bats to humans, as in the case of the strains [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS-CoV]] and [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]].<ref name=\"pmid18258002\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Cui J, Han N, Streicker D, Li G, Tang X, Shi Z, Hu Z, Zhao G, Fontanet A, Guan Y, Wang L, Jones G, Field HE, Daszak P, Zhang S | display-authors = 6 | title = Evolutionary relationships between bat coronaviruses and their hosts | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 13 | issue = 10 | pages = 1526\u201332 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 18258002 | pmc = 2851503 | doi = 10.3201/eid1310.070448 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid24172901\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ge XY, Li JL, Yang XL, Chmura AA, Zhu G, Epstein JH, Mazet JK, Hu B, Zhang W, Peng C, Zhang YJ, Luo CM, Tan B, Wang N, Zhu Y, Crameri G, Zhang SY, Wang LF, Daszak P, Shi ZL | display-authors = 6 | title = Isolation and characterization of a bat SARS-like coronavirus that uses the ACE2 receptor | journal = Nature | volume = 503 | issue = 7477 | pages = 535\u20138 | date = November 2013 | pmid = 24172901 | pmc = 5389864 | doi = 10.1038/nature12711 | bibcode = 2013Natur.503..535G }}</ref> Both these strains descended from a single ancestor but made the cross-species jump into humans separately. SARS-CoV-2 is not a direct descendant of SARS-CoV.<ref name=\"CVSG\" /> \n\n== Genome ==\n[[File:SARS-CoV genome organization.jpg|thumb|Genome organization of SARS-CoV]]\n\nThe SARS-related [[coronavirus]] is an enveloped, [[positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus|positive-sense, single-stranded RNA virus]]. Its genome is about 30&nbsp;[[kilobase|kb]], which is one of the largest among RNA viruses. The virus has 14 [[Open reading frame|open reading frames]] which overlap in some cases.<ref name=\"Snijder_2003\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Snijder EJ, Bredenbeek PJ, Dobbe JC, Thiel V, Ziebuhr J, Poon LL, Guan Y, Rozanov M, Spaan WJ, Gorbalenya AE | display-authors = 6 | title = Unique and conserved features of genome and proteome of SARS-coronavirus, an early split-off from the coronavirus group 2 lineage | journal = Journal of Molecular Biology | volume = 331 | issue = 5 | pages = 991\u20131004 | date = August 2003 | pmid = 12927536 | doi = 10.1016/S0022-2836(03)00865-9 | quote = The SARS-CoV genome is \u223c29.7 kb long and contains 14 open reading frames (ORFs) flanked by 5\u2032 and 3\u2032-untranslated regions of 265 and 342 nucleotides, respectively (Figure 1). }}</ref> The genome has a [[Five-prime cap|5\u2032 methylated cap]] and a [[Polyadenylation|3\u2032 polyadenylated tail]].<ref name = \"Fehr_2015\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> There are 265 [[Nucleotide|nucleotides]] in the [[Five prime untranslated region|5'UTR]] and 342 nucleotides in the [[Three prime untranslated region|3'UTR]].<ref name=\"Snijder_2003\" /> \n\nThe 5' methylated cap and 3' polyadenylated tail allows the [[Messenger RNA|positive-sense RNA genome]] to be directly [[Translation (biology)|translated]] by the host cell's [[ribosome]] on [[viral entry]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = An Overview of Their Replication and Pathogenesis; Section 2 Genomic Organization | journal = Methods in Molecular Biology | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> SARSr-CoV is similar to other coronaviruses in that its genome expression starts with translation by the host cell's ribosomes of its initial two large overlapping open reading frames (ORFs), 1a and 1b, both of which produce [[polyprotein]]s.<ref name=\"Snijder_2003\" />\n{|class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" |col2style=text-align:right| style= \"width:auto; float:right; clear:right; margin:0px 0px 0.5em 1em;\"\n!colspan=2| Function of SARS-CoV <br> genome proteins (orf1a to orf9b)\n|-\n! Protein || Function<ref name=McBride2012_Table1>{{cite journal | vauthors = McBride R, Fielding BC | title = The role of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS)-coronavirus accessory proteins in virus pathogenesis | journal = Viruses | volume = 4 | issue = 11 | pages = 2902\u201323 | date = November 2012 | pmid = 23202509 | pmc = 3509677 | doi = 10.3390/v4112902 |quote=See Table 1. }}</ref><ref name=\"Tang_2009\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tang X, Li G, Vasilakis N, Zhang Y, Shi Z, Zhong Y, Wang LF, Zhang S | title = Differential stepwise evolution of SARS coronavirus functional proteins in different host species | journal = BMC Evolutionary Biology | volume = 9 | issue = | pages = 52 | date = March 2009 | pmid = 19261195 | pmc = 2676248 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2148-9-52 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Narayanan|first=Krishna|last2=Huang|first2=Cheng|last3=Makino|first3=Shinji|date=April 2008|title=SARS coronavirus Accessory Proteins|journal=Virus Research|volume=133|issue=1|pages=113\u2013121|doi=10.1016/j.virusres.2007.10.009|issn=0168-1702|pmc=2720074|pmid=18045721|quote=See Table 1.}}</ref>\n|-\n|orf1a, <br>orf1b\n|Replicase/transcriptase polyprotein (pp1ab) <br>(''nonstructural proteins'')\n|-\n|orf2\n|Spike (S) protein, virus binding and entry <br>(''structural protein'')\n|-\n|[[orf3a]]||Interacts with S, E, M structural proteins; <br>[[Ion channel|Ion channel]] activity; <br>Upregulates [[Cytokine|cytokines]] and [[Chemokine|chemokines]] such as [[Interleukin 8|IL-8]] and [[CCL5|RANTES]]; <br>Upregulates [[NF-\u03baB]] and [[C-Jun N-terminal kinases|JNK]]; <br>Induces [[apoptosis]] and [[Induced cell cycle arrest|cell cycle arrest]], via [[Caspase 8]] and [[Caspase-9|-9]], <br>and by [[Bcl-2-associated X protein|Bax]], [[p53]], and [[P38 mitogen-activated protein kinases|p38 MAP kinase]]\n|-\n| orf3b ||Upregulates [[Cytokine|cytokines]] and [[Chemokine|chemokines]] by [[RUNX1|RUNX1b]]; <br>Inhibits [[Interferon|Type I IFN]] production and signaling; <br>Induces apoptosis and [[Induced cell cycle arrest|cell cycle arrest]]; \n|-\n|orf4\n|Envelope (E) protein, virus assembly and budding <br>(''structural protein'')\n|-\n|orf5\n|Membrane (M) protein, virus assembly and budding <br>(''structural protein'')\n|-\n| orf6 || Enhances cellular DNA synthesis; <br>Inhibits Type I IFN production and signaling\n|-\n|[[SARS coronavirus X4 like protein domain|orf7a]]|| Inhibits cellular protein synthesis; <br>Induces inflammatory response by [[NF-\u03baB|NF-kappaB]] and [[Interleukin 8|IL-8 promotor]]; <br>Upregulate chemokines such as IL-8 and RANTES; <br>Upregulates JNK, p38 MAP kinase; <br>Induces apoptosis and cell cycle arrest\n|-\n| orf7b || Unknown\n|-\n| orf8a || Induces apoptosis through [[Mitochondrion|mitochondria]] pathway\n|-\n| orf8b || Enhances cellular DNA synthesis\n|-\n|orf9a\n|Nucleocapsid (N) protein, viral RNA packaging <br>(''structural protein'')\n|-\n| orf9b || Induces apoptosis\n|-\n|}\nThe functions of several of the viral proteins are known.<ref name=McBride2012>{{cite journal | vauthors = McBride R, Fielding BC | title = The role of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS)-coronavirus accessory proteins in virus pathogenesis | journal = Viruses | volume = 4 | issue = 11 | pages = 2902\u201323 | date = November 2012 | pmid = 23202509 | pmc = 3509677 | doi = 10.3390/v4112902 }}</ref> ORFs 1a and 1b encode the replicase/transcriptase polyprotein, and later ORFs 2, 4, 5, and 9a encode, respectively, the four major structural proteins: spike, envelope, membrane, and [[Capsid|nucleocapsid]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Snijder EJ, Bredenbeek PJ, Dobbe JC, Thiel V, Ziebuhr J, Poon LL, Guan Y, Rozanov M, Spaan WJ, Gorbalenya AE | display-authors = 6 | title = Unique and conserved features of genome and proteome of SARS-coronavirus, an early split-off from the coronavirus group 2 lineage | journal = Journal of Molecular Biology | volume = 331 | issue = 5 | pages = 991\u20131004 | date = August 2003 | pmid = 12927536 | doi = 10.1016/S0022-2836(03)00865-9 | quote = See Figure 1. }}</ref> The later ORFs also encode for eight unique proteins (orf3a to orf9b), known as the accessory proteins, many with no known homologues. The different functions of the accessory proteins are not well understood.<ref name=McBride2012/>\n\n== Morphology == \n[[File:Coronavirus virion structure.svg|thumb|Illustration of SARSr-CoV virion]]\n\nThe morphology of the SARS-related coronavirus is characteristic of the coronavirus family as a whole. The viruses are large [[Pleomorphism (cytology)|pleomorphic]] spherical particles with bulbous surface projections that form a corona around the particles in electron micrographs.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Goldsmith CS, Tatti KM, Ksiazek TG, Rollin PE, Comer JA, Lee WW, Rota PA, Bankamp B, Bellini WJ, Zaki SR | display-authors = 6 | title = Ultrastructural characterization of SARS coronavirus | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 10 | issue = 2 | pages = 320\u20136 | date = February 2004 | pmid = 15030705 | pmc = 3322934 | doi = 10.3201/eid1002.030913 | quote = Virions acquired an envelope by budding into the cisternae and formed mostly spherical, sometimes pleomorphic, particles that averaged 78 nm in diameter (Figure 1A). }}</ref> The size of the virus particles is in the 80\u201390&nbsp;nm range. The envelope of the virus in electron micrographs appears as a distinct pair of electron dense shells.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Neuman BW, Adair BD, Yoshioka C, Quispe JD, Orca G, Kuhn P, Milligan RA, Yeager M, Buchmeier MJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Supramolecular architecture of severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus revealed by electron cryomicroscopy | journal = Journal of Virology | volume = 80 | issue = 16 | pages = 7918\u201328 | date = August 2006 | pmid = 16873249 | pmc = 1563832 | doi = 10.1128/JVI.00645-06 | quote = Particle diameters ranged from 50 to 150 nm, excluding the spikes, with mean particle diameters of 82 to 94 nm; Also See Figure 1 for double shell. }}</ref> \n\nThe [[viral envelope]] consists of a [[lipid bilayer]] where the membrane (M), envelope (E) and [[Peplomer|spike (S)]] proteins are anchored.<ref name=\"Lai_1997\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lai MM, Cavanagh D | title = The molecular biology of coronaviruses | journal = Advances in Virus Research | volume = 48 | issue = | pages = 1\u2013100 | date = 1997 | pmid = 9233431 | doi = 10.1016/S0065-3527(08)60286-9 | isbn = 9780120398485 }}</ref> The spike proteins provide the virus with its bulbous surface projections. The spike protein's interaction with its complement [[Viral entry|host cell receptor]] is central in determining the [[tissue tropism]], [[infectivity]], and [[Host tropism|species range]] of the virus.<ref>{{cite book | vauthors = Masters PS | title = The molecular biology of coronaviruses | volume = 66 | pages = 193\u2013292 | date = 2006-01-01 | pmid = 16877062 | doi = 10.1016/S0065-3527(06)66005-3 | publisher = Academic Press | isbn = 9780120398690 | quote = Nevertheless, the interaction between S protein and receptor remains the principal, if not sole, determinant of coronavirus host species range and tissue tropism. | series = Advances in Virus Research }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cui J, Li F, Shi ZL | title = Origin and evolution of pathogenic coronaviruses | journal = Nature Reviews. Microbiology | volume = 17 | issue = 3 | pages = 181\u2013192 | date = March 2019 | pmid = 30531947 | doi = 10.1038/s41579-018-0118-9 | pmc = 7097006 | quote = Different SARS-CoV strains isolated from several hosts vary in their binding affinities for human ACE2 and consequently in their infectivity of human cells76,78 (Fig. 6b) }}</ref> \n\nInside  the envelope, there is the [[Capsid|nucleocapsid]], which is formed from multiple copies of the nucleocapsid (N) protein, which are bound to the positive-sense single-stranded (~30 [[Base pair|kb]]) RNA genome in a continuous [[Bead|beads-on-a-string]] type conformation.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = An Overview of Their Replication and Pathogenesis; Section 2 Genomic Organization | journal = Methods in Molecular Biology | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc | quote = See section: Virion Structure. }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Chang CK, Hou MH, Chang CF, Hsiao CD, Huang TH | title = The SARS coronavirus nucleocapsid protein--forms and functions | journal = Antiviral Research | volume = 103 | pages = 39\u201350 | date = March 2014 | pmid = 24418573 | doi = 10.1016/j.antiviral.2013.12.009 | quote = See Figure 4c. }}</ref> The lipid bilayer envelope, membrane proteins, and nucleocapsid protect the virus  when it is outside the host.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Neuman BW, Kiss G, Kunding AH, Bhella D, Baksh MF, Connelly S, Droese B, Klaus JP, Makino S, Sawicki SG, Siddell SG, Stamou DG, Wilson IA, Kuhn P, Buchmeier MJ | display-authors = 6 | title = A structural analysis of M protein in coronavirus assembly and morphology | journal = Journal of Structural Biology | volume = 174 | issue = 1 | pages = 11\u201322 | date = April 2011 | pmid = 21130884 | pmc = 4486061 | doi = 10.1016/j.jsb.2010.11.021 | quote = See Figure 10. }}</ref>\n\n== Life cycle ==\n\nSARS-related coronavirus follows the replication strategy typical of all coronaviruses.<ref name = \"Fehr_2015\" /><ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Tok TT, Tatar G | title = Structures and Functions of Coronavirus Proteins: Molecular Modeling of Viral Nucleoprotein. |url = https://www.scireslit.com/Virology/IJVID-ID13.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Molecular Biology of the SARS-Coronavirus |doi=10.1007/978-3-642-03683-5|isbn=978-3-642-03682-8|year=2010|editor1-last=Lal|editor1-first=Sunil K | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref>\n\n=== Attachment and entry ===\n[[File:Coronavirus replication cycle.jpg|thumb|Coronavirus replication cycle]]\nThe attachment of the SARS-related coronavirus to the host cell is mediated by the spike protein and its receptor.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc | quote = See section: Coronavirus Life Cycle \u2013 Attachment and Entry }}</ref> The spike protein receptor binding domain (RBD) recognizes and attaches to the [[angiotensin-converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) receptor.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ge XY, Li JL, Yang XL, Chmura AA, Zhu G, Epstein JH, Mazet JK, Hu B, Zhang W, Peng C, Zhang YJ, Luo CM, Tan B, Wang N, Zhu Y, Crameri G, Zhang SY, Wang LF, Daszak P, Shi ZL | display-authors = 6 | title = Isolation and characterization of a bat SARS-like coronavirus that uses the ACE2 receptor | journal = Nature | volume = 503 | issue = 7477 | pages = 535\u20138 | date = November 2013 | pmid = 24172901 | pmc = 5389864 | doi = 10.1038/nature12711 | bibcode = 2013Natur.503..535G }}</ref> Following attachment, the virus can enter the host cell by two different paths. The path the virus takes depends on the host [[protease]] available to cleave and activate the receptor-attached spike protein.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Simmons G, Zmora P, Gierer S, Heurich A, P\u00f6hlmann S | title = Proteolytic activation of the SARS-coronavirus spike protein: cutting enzymes at the cutting edge of antiviral research | journal = Antiviral Research | volume = 100 | issue = 3 | pages = 605\u201314 | date = December 2013 | pmid = 24121034 | pmc = 3889862 | doi = 10.1016/j.antiviral.2013.09.028 | quote = See Figure 2. }}</ref>\n\nThe first path the SARS coronavirus can take to enter the host cell is by [[endocytosis]] and uptake of the virus in an [[endosome]]. The receptor-attached spike protein is then activated by the host's pH-dependent [[cysteine protease]] [[cathepsin L]]. Activation of the receptor-attached spike protein causes a [[conformational change]], and the subsequent fusion of the viral envelope with the [[Lipid bilayer|endosomal wall]].<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nAlternatively, the virus can enter the host cell directly by [[Proteolysis|proteolytic]] cleavage of the receptor-attached spike protein by the host's [[TMPRSS2]] or [[TMPRSS11D]] [[Serine protease|serine proteases]] at the cell surface.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Heurich A, Hofmann-Winkler H, Gierer S, Liepold T, Jahn O, P\u00f6hlmann S | title = TMPRSS2 and ADAM17 cleave ACE2 differentially and only proteolysis by TMPRSS2 augments entry driven by the severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus spike protein | journal = Journal of Virology | volume = 88 | issue = 2 | pages = 1293\u2013307 | date = January 2014 | pmid = 24227843 | pmc = 3911672 | doi = 10.1128/JVI.02202-13 | quote = The SARS-CoV can hijack two cellular proteolytic systems to ensure the adequate processing of its S protein. Cleavage of SARS-S can be facilitated by cathepsin L, a pH-dependent endo-/lysosomal host cell protease, upon uptake of virions into target cell endosomes (25). Alternatively, the type II transmembrane serine proteases (TTSPs) TMPRSS2 and HAT can activate SARS-S, presumably by cleavage of SARS-S at or close to the cell surface, and activation of SARS-S by TMPRSS2 allows for cathepsin L-independent cellular entry (26,\u201328). }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Zumla A, Chan JF, Azhar EI, Hui DS, Yuen KY | title = Coronaviruses - drug discovery and therapeutic options | journal = Nature Reviews. Drug Discovery | volume = 15 | issue = 5 | pages = 327\u201347 | date = May 2016 | pmid = 26868298 | doi = 10.1038/nrd.2015.37 | pmc = 7097181 | quote = S is activated and cleaved into the S1 and S2 subunits by other host proteases, such as transmembrane protease serine 2 (TMPRSS2) and TMPRSS11D, which enables cell surface non-endosomal virus entry at the plasma membrane. }}</ref> In the SARS coronavirus, the activation of the [[C-terminus|C-terminal part]] of the spike protein triggers the fusion of the viral envelope with the host cell membrane by inducing conformational changes which are not fully understood.<ref name=\"pmid316509562\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li Z, Tomlinson AC, Wong AH, Zhou D, Desforges M, Talbot PJ, Benlekbir S, Rubinstein JL, Rini JM | display-authors = 6 | title = The human coronavirus HCoV-229E S-protein structure and receptor binding | journal = eLife | volume = 8 | issue =  | date = October 2019 | pmid = 31650956 | pmc = 6970540 | doi = 10.7554/eLife.51230 }}</ref>\n\n=== Genome translation ===\n{|class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" |col2style=text-align:right| style= \"width:auto; float:right; clear:right; margin:0px 0px 0.5em 1em;\"\n!colspan=2| Function of coronavirus <br> nonstructural proteins (nsps)<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc | quote = See Table 2. }}</ref>\n|-\n! Protein || Function\n|-\n| nsp1 || Promotes host [[Messenger RNA|mRNA]] degradation, blocks host [[Translation (biology)|translation]]; <br>blocks [[Innate immune system|innate immune response]]\n|-\n| nsp2 || Binds to [[prohibitin]] proteins; <br>unknown function\n|-\n| nsp3 ||[[Protein domain|Multidoman]] [[transmembrane protein]]; interacts with [[Capsid|N protein]]; promotes [[cytokine]] expression; [[Papain|PLPro]] domain cleaves [[Proteolysis|polyprotein]] pp1ab and blocks host's innate immune response; other domains unknown functions\n|-\n| nsp4 || Transmembrane [[scaffold protein]]; <br>allows proper structure for [[Lipid bilayer|double membrane vesicles]] (DMVs)\n|-\n| nsp5 ||[[C30 Endopeptidase|3CLPro]] cleaves polyprotein pp1ab\n|-\n| nsp6 || Transmembrane scaffold protein; <br>unknown function\n|-\n| nsp7 || Forms [[Oligomer|hexadecameric]] complex with nsp8; [[Processivity|processivity clamp]] for [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase|RdRp]] (nsp12)\n|-\n| nsp8 || Forms hexadecameric complex with nsp7; processivity clamp for RdRp (nsp12); acts as a [[primase]]\n|-\n| nsp9 ||[[RNA-binding protein|RNA binding protein]] (RBP)\n|-\n| nsp10 || nsp16 and nsp14 [[Cofactor (biochemistry)|cofactor]]; forms heterodimer with both; stimulates [[2'-O-methylation|2-O-MT]] (nsp16) and [[Exoribonuclease|ExoN]] (nsp14) activity\n|-\n| nsp11 || Unknown function\n|-\n| nsp12 ||[[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase]] (RdRp)\n|-\n| nsp13 ||[[Helicase|RNA helicase]], [[Triphosphatase|5\u2032 triphosphatase]]\n|-\n| nsp14 ||[[Methyltransferase|N7 Methyltransferase]], [[Exoribonuclease|3\u2032-5\u2032 exoribonuclease]] (ExoN); N7 MTase adds [[Five-prime cap|5\u2032 cap]], ExoN [[Proofreading (biology)|proofreads genome]]\n|-\n| nsp15 ||[[Endoribonuclease]] (NendoU)\n|-\n| nsp16 ||[[2'-O-methylation|2\u2032-O-Methyltransferase]] (2-O-MT); protects viral RNA from [[MDA5]]\n|-\n|}\nAfter fusion the nucleocapsid passes into the [[cytoplasm]], where the viral genome is released.<ref name=\":2\" /> The genome [[Ribosome-binding_site|acts as a messenger RNA]], and the cell's [[ribosomes|ribosome]] [[Translation_(biology)|translates]] two-thirds of the genome, which corresponds to the open reading frame ORF1a and ORF1b, into two large overlapping polyproteins, pp1a and pp1ab. \n\nThe larger polyprotein pp1ab is a result of a [[ribosomal frameshift|-1 ribosomal frameshift]] caused by a [[slippery sequence]] (UUUAAAC) and a downstream [[Nucleic acid secondary structure|RNA pseudoknot]] at the end of open reading frame ORF1a.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Masters PS | title = The molecular biology of coronaviruses | journal = Advances in Virus Research | volume = 66 | pages = 193\u2013292 | date = 2006-01-01 | pmid = 16877062 | doi = 10.1016/S0065-3527(06)66005-3 | publisher = Academic Press | isbn = 9780120398690 | quote =See Figure 8. }}</ref> The ribosomal frameshift allows for the continuous translation of ORF1a followed by ORF1b.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nThe polyproteins contain their own [[C30_Endopeptidase|proteases]],  [[Papain|PLpro]] and [[C30 Endopeptidase|3CLpro]], which cleave the polyproteins at different specific sites. The cleavage of polyprotein pp1ab yields 16 nonstructural proteins (nsp1 to nsp16). Product proteins include various replication  proteins such as [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase]] (RdRp), [[RNA helicase]], and [[exoribonuclease]] (ExoN).<ref name=\":3\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc |quote=See section: Replicase Protein Expression }}</ref>\n\n=== Replication and transcription ===\n[[File:Replication-transcription complex for Coronaviruses.tif|thumb|Model of the replicase-transcriptase complex of a coronavirus. [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase|RdRp]] for [[DNA replication|replication]] (red), [[Exoribonuclease|ExoN]] for [[Proofreading (biology)|proofreading]] (dark blue), ExoN cofactor (yellow), [[RNA-binding protein|RBPs]] to avoid [[Nucleic acid secondary structure|secondary structure]] (light blue), [[DNA clamp|RNA sliding clamp]] for [[processivity]] and [[primase]] [[Protein domain|domain]] for [[Primer (molecular biology)|priming]] (green/orange), and a [[helicase]] to unwind RNA (downstream). ]]\n\nA number of the nonstructural replication proteins coalesce to form a [[Protein complex|multi-protein]] replicase-transcriptase complex (RTC).<ref name=\":3\" /> The main replicase-transcriptase protein is the [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase]] (RdRp). It is directly involved in the [[DNA replication|replication]] and [[Transcription (biology)|transcription]] of RNA from an RNA strand. The other nonstructural proteins in the complex assist in the replication and transcription process.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe protein nsp15 is a [[Exoribonuclease|3'-5' exoribonuclease]] which provides extra fidelity to the replication process. The exoribonuclease provides a [[Proofreading (biology)|proofreading]] function to the complex which the RNA-dependent RNA polymerase lacks. Similarly, proteins nsp7 and nsp8 form a hexadecameric sliding clamp as part of the complex which greatly increases the [[processivity]] of the RNA-dependent RNA polymerase.<ref name=\":1\" /> The coronaviruses require the increased fidelity and processivity during RNA synthesis because of the relatively large genome size in comparison to other RNA viruses.<ref name=\"SextonSmith2016\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Sexton NR, Smith EC, Blanc H, Vignuzzi M, Peersen OB, Denison MR|date=August 2016|title=Homology-Based Identification of a Mutation in the Coronavirus RNA-Dependent RNA Polymerase That Confers Resistance to Multiple Mutagens|journal=Journal of Virology|volume=90|issue=16|pages=7415\u201328|doi=10.1128/JVI.00080-16|pmc=4984655|pmid=27279608|quote=Finally, these results, combined with those from previous work (33, 44), suggest that CoVs encode at least three proteins involved in fidelity (nsp12-RdRp, nsp14-ExoN, and nsp10), supporting the assembly of a multiprotein replicase-fidelity complex, as described previously (38).}}</ref>\n\nOne of the main functions of the replicase-transcriptase complex is to transcribe the viral genome. RdRp directly mediates the [[transcription (biology)|synthesis]] of  negative-sense subgenomic RNA molecules from the positive-sense genomic RNA. This is followed by the transcription of these negative-sense subgenomic RNA molecules to their corresponding positive-sense [[Messenger RNA|mRNAs]].<ref name=\":5\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc |quote=See section: Corona Life Cycle \u2013 Replication and Transcription}}</ref>\n\nThe other important function of the replicase-transcriptase complex is to replicate the viral genome. RdRp directly mediates the [[DNA replication|synthesis]] of negative-sense genomic RNA from the positive-sense genomic RNA. This is followed by the replication of positive-sense genomic RNA from the negative-sense genomic RNA.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nThe replicated positive-sense genomic RNA becomes the genome of the [[viral shedding|progeny viruses]]. The various smaller mRNAs are transcripts from the last third of the virus genome which follows the reading frames ORF1a and ORF1b. These mRNAs are translated into the four structural proteins (S, E, M, and N) that will become part of the progeny virus particles and also eight other accessory proteins (orf3 to orf9b) which assist the virus.<ref>{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc | quote = See Figure 1. }}</ref>\n\n=== Assembly and release ===\n\n[[Translation (biology)|RNA translation]] occurs  inside the [[endoplasmic reticulum]]. The viral structural proteins S,  E and M  move along the secretory pathway into the [[Vesicular-tubular_cluster|Golgi intermediate compartment]]. There, the M proteins direct most protein-protein interactions required for assembly of viruses following its binding to the nucleocapsid.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc |quote=See section: Coronavirus Life Cycle \u2013 Assembly and Release }}</ref>\n\nProgeny viruses are released from the host cell by [[exocytosis]] through secretory vesicles.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Coronavirus disease 2019}}\n*[[Bat SARS-like coronavirus WIV1|SARS-like coronavirus WIV1]] (SL-CoV-WIV1)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Peiris JS, Lai ST, Poon LL, Guan Y, Yam LY, Lim W, Nicholls J, Yee WK, Yan WW, Cheung MT, Cheng VC, Chan KH, Tsang DN, Yung RW, Ng TK, Yuen KY | display-authors = 6 | title = Coronavirus as a possible cause of severe acute respiratory syndrome | journal = Lancet | volume = 361 | issue = 9366 | pages = 1319\u201325 | date = April 2003 | pmid = 12711465 | doi = 10.1016/s0140-6736(03)13077-2 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Rota PA, Oberste MS, Monroe SS, Nix WA, Campagnoli R, Icenogle JP, Pe\u00f1aranda S, Bankamp B, Maher K, Chen MH, Tong S, Tamin A, Lowe L, Frace M, DeRisi JL, Chen Q, Wang D, Erdman DD, Peret TC, Burns C, Ksiazek TG, Rollin PE, Sanchez A, Liffick S, Holloway B, Limor J, McCaustland K, Olsen-Rasmussen M, Fouchier R, G\u00fcnther S, Osterhaus AD, Drosten C, Pallansch MA, Anderson LJ, Bellini WJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Characterization of a novel coronavirus associated with severe acute respiratory syndrome | journal = Science | volume = 300 | issue = 5624 | pages = 1394\u20139 | date = May 2003 | pmid = 12730500 | doi = 10.1126/science.1085952 | bibcode = 2003Sci...300.1394R }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Marra MA, Jones SJ, Astell CR, Holt RA, Brooks-Wilson A, Butterfield YS, Khattra J, Asano JK, Barber SA, Chan SY, Cloutier A, Coughlin SM, Freeman D, Girn N, Griffith OL, Leach SR, Mayo M, McDonald H, Montgomery SB, Pandoh PK, Petrescu AS, Robertson AG, Schein JE, Siddiqui A, Smailus DE, Stott JM, Yang GS, Plummer F, Andonov A, Artsob H, Bastien N, Bernard K, Booth TF, Bowness D, Czub M, Drebot M, Fernando L, Flick R, Garbutt M, Gray M, Grolla A, Jones S, Feldmann H, Meyers A, Kabani A, Li Y, Normand S, Stroher U, Tipples GA, Tyler S, Vogrig R, Ward D, Watson B, Brunham RC, Krajden M, Petric M, Skowronski DM, Upton C, Roper RL | display-authors = 6 | title = The Genome sequence of the SARS-associated coronavirus | journal = Science | volume = 300 | issue = 5624 | pages = 1399\u2013404 | date = May 2003 | pmid = 12730501 | doi = 10.1126/science.1085953 | bibcode = 2003Sci...300.1399M }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Snijder EJ, Bredenbeek PJ, Dobbe JC, Thiel V, Ziebuhr J, Poon LL, Guan Y, Rozanov M, Spaan WJ, Gorbalenya AE | display-authors = 6 | title = Unique and conserved features of genome and proteome of SARS-coronavirus, an early split-off from the coronavirus group 2 lineage | journal = Journal of Molecular Biology | volume = 331 | issue = 5 | pages = 991\u20131004 | date = August 2003 | pmid = 12927536 | doi = 10.1016/S0022-2836(03)00865-9 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.319.7007 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Yount B, Roberts RS, Lindesmith L, Baric RS | title = Rewiring the severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus (SARS-CoV) transcription circuit: engineering a recombination-resistant genome | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 103 | issue = 33 | pages = 12546\u201351 | date = August 2006 | pmid = 16891412 | pmc = 1531645 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0605438103 | bibcode = 2006PNAS..10312546Y }}\n* {{cite book | veditors = Thiel V | title = Coronaviruses: Molecular and Cellular Biology | edition = 1st | publisher = Caister Academic Press | year = 2007 |  isbn =  978-1-904455-16-5 }}\n* {{cite book | vauthors = Enjuanes L, Sola I, Z\u00fa\u00f1iga S, Almaz\u00e1n F |year=2008 |chapter=Coronavirus Replication and Interaction with Host |title=Animal Viruses: Molecular Biology |publisher=Caister Academic Press |isbn= 978-1-904455-22-6 | veditors = Mettenleiter TC, Sobrino F}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikispecies}}\n\n* [http://www.who.int/mediacentre/releases/2003/pr31/en/ WHO press release identifying and naming the SARS virus]\n* [http://www.bcgsc.ca/bioinfo/SARS/ The SARS virus genetic map]\n* [http://www.sciencemag.org/site/feature/data/sars/ ''Science'' special on the SARS virus] (free content: no registration required)\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050301194019/http://www.health.library.mcgill.ca/resource/sars.htm |date=1 March 2005 |title=McGill University SARS Resources }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160412085632/http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/sars/ U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) SARS home]\n* [http://www.castanet.net/news/Canada/80872/World-Health-Organization-on-alert World Health Organization on alert]\n\n{{SARS}}\n{{Viral diseases}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q278567}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus}}\n[[Category:Sarbecovirus]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Species of coronavirus causing SARS and COVID-19}}\n{{about|a '''species''' of coronavirus comprising multiple strains|the ''strain'' that causes [[SARS]]|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|the ''strain'' that causes COVID-19|Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2}}\n{{Virusbox\n| image          = SARS-CoV with corona.jpg\n| image_caption  = [[Transmission electron micrograph]] of SARS-related coronaviruses emerging from host cells cultured in the lab\n| parent         = Sarbecovirus\n| species        = Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus\n| authority      = \n| synonyms       = *''SARS coronavirus''\n*''SARS-related coronavirus''\n*''Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus''<ref name=\"TaxHist\">{{cite web |title=ICTV Taxonomy history: ''Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus'' |url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/taxonomy/p/taxonomy-history?taxnode_id=20181868 |website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) |access-date=27 January 2019 |language=en |format=html}}</ref>\n| synonyms_ref   = \n| subdivision_ranks = Strains\n| subdivision    = \n[[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS-CoV]]\n<br/> [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n<br/> [[Bat SARS-like coronavirus WIV1]] \n<br/> Numerous other bat strains\n}}\n\n'''''Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus''''' ('''SARS-CoV''')<ref group=note> The terms '''SARS-CoV''' and '''SARSr-CoV''' are sometimes used interchangeably, especially prior to the discovery of SARS-CoV-2.</ref> is a species of [[coronavirus]] that infects [[humans]], [[bats]] and certain other [[mammals]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Branswell |first=Helen | name-list-format = vanc |url=https://www.statnews.com/2015/11/09/sars-like-virus-bats-shows-potential-infect-humans-study-finds/|title=SARS-like virus in bats shows potential to infect humans, study finds|date=9 November 2015|work=Stat News|access-date=20 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wong AC, Li X, Lau SK, Woo PC | title = Global Epidemiology of Bat Coronaviruses | journal = Viruses | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 174 | date = February 2019 | pmid = 30791586 | pmc = 6409556 | doi = 10.3390/v11020174 | quote = Most notably, horseshoe bats were found to be the reservoir of SARS-like CoVs, while palm civet cats are considered to be the intermediate host for SARS-CoVs [43,44,45]. }}</ref> It is an [[Viral envelope|enveloped]] [[positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus]] that enters its host cell by binding to the [[ACE2]] receptor.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is a member of the genus ''[[Betacoronavirus]]'' and subgenus ''Sarbecoronavirus''.<ref name=\"ICTV10\">{{cite web |title=Virus Taxonomy: 2018 Release |url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/taxonomy/ |website=International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV) |access-date=13 January 2019 |language=en |date=October 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":02\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Woo PC, Huang Y, Lau SK, Yuen KY | title = Coronavirus genomics and bioinformatics analysis | journal = Viruses | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 1804\u201320 | date = August 2010 | pmid = 21994708 | pmc = 3185738 | doi = 10.3390/v2081803 | quote = Figure 2. Phylogenetic analysis of RNA-dependent RNA polymerases (Pol) of coronaviruses with complete genome sequences available. The tree was constructed by the neighbor-joining method and rooted using Breda virus polyprotein. }}</ref>\n\nTwo strains of the virus have caused outbreaks of severe [[respiratory diseases]] in humans: [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS-CoV]] (or SARS-CoV-1), which caused [[2002-2004 SARS outbreak|the 2002-2004 outbreak]] of [[severe acute respiratory syndrome]] (SARS), and [[SARS-CoV-2]], which is causing \nthe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19).<ref name=\"CVSG\">{{cite journal | title = The species Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus: classifying 2019-nCoV and naming it SARS-CoV-2 | journal = Nature Microbiology | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32123347 | doi = 10.1038/s41564-020-0695-z | author1 = Coronaviridae Study Group of the International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses | volume = 5 | issue = 4 | pages = 536\u2013544 }}</ref><ref name=\"SCI\">{{cite journal |last1=Kohen |first1=Jon |last2=Kupferschmidth |first2=Kai |title=Strategies shift as coronavirus pandemic looms |journal=Science |date=28 February 2020 |volume=367 |issue=6481 |pages=962\u2013963 |doi=10.1126/science.367.6481.962 |pmid=32108093 |bibcode=2020Sci...367..962C }}</ref> There are hundreds of other strains of SARS-CoV, all of which are only known to infect non-human species: [[Bat-borne virus|bats are a major reservoir]] of many strains of SARS-related coronaviruses, and several strains have been identified in [[palm civet]]s, which were likely ancestors of SARS-CoV.<ref name=\"CVSG\" /><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Lau SK, Li KS, Huang Y, Shek CT, Tse H, Wang M, Choi GK, Xu H, Lam CS, Guo R, Chan KH, Zheng BJ, Woo PC, Yuen KY | display-authors = 6 | title = Ecoepidemiology and complete genome comparison of different strains of severe acute respiratory syndrome-related Rhinolophus bat coronavirus in China reveal bats as a reservoir for acute, self-limiting infection that allows recombination events | journal = Journal of Virology | volume = 84 | issue = 6 | pages = 2808\u201319 | date = March 2010 | pmid = 20071579 | pmc = 2826035 | doi = 10.1128/JVI.02219-09 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n\nThe SARS-related coronavirus was one of several viruses identified by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) in 2016 as a likely cause of a future epidemic in a new plan developed after the [[Western African Ebola virus epidemic|Ebola epidemic]] for urgent research and development before and during an epidemic towards diagnostic tests, [[vaccines]] and medicines. The prediction came to pass with the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kieny|first1=Marie-Paule | name-list-format = vanc |title=After Ebola, a Blueprint Emerges to Jump-Start R&D|url=https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/after-ebola-a-blueprint-emerges-to-jump-start-r-d/|website=Scientific American Blog Network|access-date=13 December 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220134725/https://blogs.scientificamerican.com/guest-blog/after-ebola-a-blueprint-emerges-to-jump-start-r-d/|archive-date=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=LIST OF PATHOGENS|url=http://www.who.int/csr/research-and-development/list_of_pathogens/en/|website=World Health Organization|access-date=13 December 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220180509/http://www.who.int/csr/research-and-development/list_of_pathogens/en/|archive-date=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Classification ==\nSARS-related coronavirus is a member of the genus ''[[Betacoronavirus|Betacoronavirus]]'' (group 2) and subgenus ''Sarbecovirus'' (subgroup B).<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Wong AC, Li X, Lau SK, Woo PC | title = Global Epidemiology of Bat Coronaviruses | journal = Viruses | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 174 | date = February 2019 | pmid = 30791586 | pmc = 6409556 | doi = 10.3390/v11020174 | quote = See Figure 1. }}</ref>  Sarbecoviruses, unlike [[Embecovirus|embecoviruses]] or [[Alphacoronavirus|alphacoronaviruses]], only have one papain-like proteinase (PLpro) instead of two in the [[open reading frame]] ORF1.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Woo PC, Huang Y, Lau SK, Yuen KY | title = Coronavirus genomics and bioinformatics analysis | journal = Viruses | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 1804\u201320 | date = August 2010 | pmid = 21994708 | pmc = 3185738 | doi = 10.3390/v2081803 | quote = See Figure 1. }}</ref> SARSr-CoV was determined to be an early split-off from the betacoronaviruses based on a set of conserved domains that it shares with the group.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Woo PC, Huang Y, Lau SK, Yuen KY | title = Coronavirus genomics and bioinformatics analysis | journal = Viruses | volume = 2 | issue = 8 | pages = 1804\u201320 | date = August 2010 | pmid = 21994708 | pmc = 3185738 | doi = 10.3390/v2081803 | quote = Furthermore, subsequent phylogenetic analysis using both complete genome sequence and proteomic approaches, it was concluded that SARSr-CoV is probably an early split-off from the Betacoronavirus lineage [1]; See Figure 2. }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://talk.ictvonline.org/ictv-reports/ictv_9th_report/positive-sense-rna-viruses-2011/w/posrna_viruses/223/coronaviridae-figures|title=Coronaviridae - Figures - Positive Sense RNA Viruses - Positive Sense RNA Viruses (2011) | work = International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (ICTV)|language=en |access-date=2020-03-06|quote=See Figure 2.}}</ref>\n\nBats serve as the main host reservoir for the SARS-related coronavirus. The virus has coevolved in the [[Bat-borne virus|bat host reservoir]] over a long period of time.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gouilh MA, Puechmaille SJ, Gonzalez JP, Teeling E, Kittayapong P, Manuguerra JC | title = SARS-Coronavirus ancestor's foot-prints in South-East Asian bat colonies and the refuge theory | journal = Infection, Genetics and Evolution | volume = 11 | issue = 7 | pages = 1690\u2013702 | date = October 2011 | pmid = 21763784 | doi = 10.1016/j.meegid.2011.06.021 | quote = Betacoronaviruses-b ancestors, meaning SARSr-CoVs ancestors, could have been historically hosted by the common ancestor of the Rhinolophidae and Hipposideridae and could have later evolved independently in the lineages leading towards Rhinolophidae and Hipposideridae betacoronaviruses. }}</ref> Only recently have strains of SARS-related coronavirus evolved and made the [[Cross-species transmission|cross-species jump]] from bats to humans, as in the case of the strains [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus|SARS-CoV]] and [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]].<ref name=\"pmid18258002\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Cui J, Han N, Streicker D, Li G, Tang X, Shi Z, Hu Z, Zhao G, Fontanet A, Guan Y, Wang L, Jones G, Field HE, Daszak P, Zhang S | display-authors = 6 | title = Evolutionary relationships between bat coronaviruses and their hosts | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 13 | issue = 10 | pages = 1526\u201332 | date = October 2007 | pmid = 18258002 | pmc = 2851503 | doi = 10.3201/eid1310.070448 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid24172901\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ge XY, Li JL, Yang XL, Chmura AA, Zhu G, Epstein JH, Mazet JK, Hu B, Zhang W, Peng C, Zhang YJ, Luo CM, Tan B, Wang N, Zhu Y, Crameri G, Zhang SY, Wang LF, Daszak P, Shi ZL | display-authors = 6 | title = Isolation and characterization of a bat SARS-like coronavirus that uses the ACE2 receptor | journal = Nature | volume = 503 | issue = 7477 | pages = 535\u20138 | date = November 2013 | pmid = 24172901 | pmc = 5389864 | doi = 10.1038/nature12711 | bibcode = 2013Natur.503..535G }}</ref> Both these strains descended from a single ancestor but made the cross-species jump into humans separately. SARS-CoV-2 is not a direct descendant of SARS-CoV.<ref name=\"CVSG\" /> \n\n== Genome ==\n[[File:SARS-CoV genome organization.jpg|thumb|Genome organization of SARS-CoV]]\n\nThe SARS-related [[coronavirus]] is an enveloped, [[positive-sense single-stranded RNA virus|positive-sense, single-stranded RNA virus]]. Its genome is about 30&nbsp;[[kilobase|kb]], which is one of the largest among RNA viruses. The virus has 14 [[Open reading frame|open reading frames]] which overlap in some cases.<ref name=\"Snijder_2003\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Snijder EJ, Bredenbeek PJ, Dobbe JC, Thiel V, Ziebuhr J, Poon LL, Guan Y, Rozanov M, Spaan WJ, Gorbalenya AE | display-authors = 6 | title = Unique and conserved features of genome and proteome of SARS-coronavirus, an early split-off from the coronavirus group 2 lineage | journal = Journal of Molecular Biology | volume = 331 | issue = 5 | pages = 991\u20131004 | date = August 2003 | pmid = 12927536 | doi = 10.1016/S0022-2836(03)00865-9 | quote = The SARS-CoV genome is \u223c29.7 kb long and contains 14 open reading frames (ORFs) flanked by 5\u2032 and 3\u2032-untranslated regions of 265 and 342 nucleotides, respectively (Figure 1). }}</ref> The genome has a [[Five-prime cap|5\u2032 methylated cap]] and a [[Polyadenylation|3\u2032 polyadenylated tail]].<ref name = \"Fehr_2015\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> There are 265 [[Nucleotide|nucleotides]] in the [[Five prime untranslated region|5'UTR]] and 342 nucleotides in the [[Three prime untranslated region|3'UTR]].<ref name=\"Snijder_2003\" /> \n\nThe 5' methylated cap and 3' polyadenylated tail allows the [[Messenger RNA|positive-sense RNA genome]] to be directly [[Translation (biology)|translated]] by the host cell's [[ribosome]] on [[viral entry]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = An Overview of Their Replication and Pathogenesis; Section 2 Genomic Organization | journal = Methods in Molecular Biology | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref> SARSr-CoV is similar to other coronaviruses in that its genome expression starts with translation by the host cell's ribosomes of its initial two large overlapping open reading frames (ORFs), 1a and 1b, both of which produce [[polyprotein]]s.<ref name=\"Snijder_2003\" />\n{|class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" |col2style=text-align:right| style= \"width:auto; float:right; clear:right; margin:0px 0px 0.5em 1em;\"\n!colspan=2| Function of SARS-CoV <br> genome proteins (orf1a to orf9b)\n|-\n! Protein || Function<ref name=McBride2012_Table1>{{cite journal | vauthors = McBride R, Fielding BC | title = The role of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS)-coronavirus accessory proteins in virus pathogenesis | journal = Viruses | volume = 4 | issue = 11 | pages = 2902\u201323 | date = November 2012 | pmid = 23202509 | pmc = 3509677 | doi = 10.3390/v4112902 |quote=See Table 1. }}</ref><ref name=\"Tang_2009\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Tang X, Li G, Vasilakis N, Zhang Y, Shi Z, Zhong Y, Wang LF, Zhang S | title = Differential stepwise evolution of SARS coronavirus functional proteins in different host species | journal = BMC Evolutionary Biology | volume = 9 | issue = | pages = 52 | date = March 2009 | pmid = 19261195 | pmc = 2676248 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2148-9-52 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Narayanan|first=Krishna|last2=Huang|first2=Cheng|last3=Makino|first3=Shinji|date=April 2008|title=SARS coronavirus Accessory Proteins|journal=Virus Research|volume=133|issue=1|pages=113\u2013121|doi=10.1016/j.virusres.2007.10.009|issn=0168-1702|pmc=2720074|pmid=18045721|quote=See Table 1.}}</ref>\n|-\n|orf1a, <br>orf1b\n|Replicase/transcriptase polyprotein (pp1ab) <br>(''nonstructural proteins'')\n|-\n|orf2\n|Spike (S) protein, virus binding and entry <br>(''structural protein'')\n|-\n|[[orf3a]]||Interacts with S, E, M structural proteins; <br>[[Ion channel|Ion channel]] activity; <br>Upregulates [[Cytokine|cytokines]] and [[Chemokine|chemokines]] such as [[Interleukin 8|IL-8]] and [[CCL5|RANTES]]; <br>Upregulates [[NF-\u03baB]] and [[C-Jun N-terminal kinases|JNK]]; <br>Induces [[apoptosis]] and [[Induced cell cycle arrest|cell cycle arrest]], via [[Caspase 8]] and [[Caspase-9|-9]], <br>and by [[Bcl-2-associated X protein|Bax]], [[p53]], and [[P38 mitogen-activated protein kinases|p38 MAP kinase]]\n|-\n| orf3b ||Upregulates [[Cytokine|cytokines]] and [[Chemokine|chemokines]] by [[RUNX1|RUNX1b]]; <br>Inhibits [[Interferon|Type I IFN]] production and signaling; <br>Induces apoptosis and [[Induced cell cycle arrest|cell cycle arrest]]; \n|-\n|orf4\n|Envelope (E) protein, virus assembly and budding <br>(''structural protein'')\n|-\n|orf5\n|Membrane (M) protein, virus assembly and budding <br>(''structural protein'')\n|-\n| orf6 || Enhances cellular DNA synthesis; <br>Inhibits Type I IFN production and signaling\n|-\n|[[SARS coronavirus X4 like protein domain|orf7a]]|| Inhibits cellular protein synthesis; <br>Induces inflammatory response by [[NF-\u03baB|NF-kappaB]] and [[Interleukin 8|IL-8 promotor]]; <br>Upregulate chemokines such as IL-8 and RANTES; <br>Upregulates JNK, p38 MAP kinase; <br>Induces apoptosis and cell cycle arrest\n|-\n| orf7b || Unknown\n|-\n| orf8a || Induces apoptosis through [[Mitochondrion|mitochondria]] pathway\n|-\n| orf8b || Enhances cellular DNA synthesis\n|-\n|orf9a\n|Nucleocapsid (N) protein, viral RNA packaging <br>(''structural protein'')\n|-\n| orf9b || Induces apoptosis\n|-\n|}\nThe functions of several of the viral proteins are known.<ref name=McBride2012>{{cite journal | vauthors = McBride R, Fielding BC | title = The role of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS)-coronavirus accessory proteins in virus pathogenesis | journal = Viruses | volume = 4 | issue = 11 | pages = 2902\u201323 | date = November 2012 | pmid = 23202509 | pmc = 3509677 | doi = 10.3390/v4112902 }}</ref> ORFs 1a and 1b encode the replicase/transcriptase polyprotein, and later ORFs 2, 4, 5, and 9a encode, respectively, the four major structural proteins: spike, envelope, membrane, and [[Capsid|nucleocapsid]].<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Snijder EJ, Bredenbeek PJ, Dobbe JC, Thiel V, Ziebuhr J, Poon LL, Guan Y, Rozanov M, Spaan WJ, Gorbalenya AE | display-authors = 6 | title = Unique and conserved features of genome and proteome of SARS-coronavirus, an early split-off from the coronavirus group 2 lineage | journal = Journal of Molecular Biology | volume = 331 | issue = 5 | pages = 991\u20131004 | date = August 2003 | pmid = 12927536 | doi = 10.1016/S0022-2836(03)00865-9 | quote = See Figure 1. }}</ref> The later ORFs also encode for eight unique proteins (orf3a to orf9b), known as the accessory proteins, many with no known homologues. The different functions of the accessory proteins are not well understood.<ref name=McBride2012/>\n\n== Morphology == \n[[File:Coronavirus virion structure.svg|thumb|Illustration of SARSr-CoV virion]]\n\nThe morphology of the SARS-related coronavirus is characteristic of the coronavirus family as a whole. The viruses are large [[Pleomorphism (cytology)|pleomorphic]] spherical particles with bulbous surface projections that form a corona around the particles in electron micrographs.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Goldsmith CS, Tatti KM, Ksiazek TG, Rollin PE, Comer JA, Lee WW, Rota PA, Bankamp B, Bellini WJ, Zaki SR | display-authors = 6 | title = Ultrastructural characterization of SARS coronavirus | journal = Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume = 10 | issue = 2 | pages = 320\u20136 | date = February 2004 | pmid = 15030705 | pmc = 3322934 | doi = 10.3201/eid1002.030913 | quote = Virions acquired an envelope by budding into the cisternae and formed mostly spherical, sometimes pleomorphic, particles that averaged 78 nm in diameter (Figure 1A). }}</ref> The size of the virus particles is in the 80\u201390&nbsp;nm range. The envelope of the virus in electron micrographs appears as a distinct pair of electron dense shells.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Neuman BW, Adair BD, Yoshioka C, Quispe JD, Orca G, Kuhn P, Milligan RA, Yeager M, Buchmeier MJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Supramolecular architecture of severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus revealed by electron cryomicroscopy | journal = Journal of Virology | volume = 80 | issue = 16 | pages = 7918\u201328 | date = August 2006 | pmid = 16873249 | pmc = 1563832 | doi = 10.1128/JVI.00645-06 | quote = Particle diameters ranged from 50 to 150 nm, excluding the spikes, with mean particle diameters of 82 to 94 nm; Also See Figure 1 for double shell. }}</ref> \n\nThe [[viral envelope]] consists of a [[lipid bilayer]] where the membrane (M), envelope (E) and [[Peplomer|spike (S)]] proteins are anchored.<ref name=\"Lai_1997\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Lai MM, Cavanagh D | title = The molecular biology of coronaviruses | journal = Advances in Virus Research | volume = 48 | issue = | pages = 1\u2013100 | date = 1997 | pmid = 9233431 | doi = 10.1016/S0065-3527(08)60286-9 | isbn = 9780120398485 }}</ref> The spike proteins provide the virus with its bulbous surface projections. The spike protein's interaction with its complement [[Viral entry|host cell receptor]] is central in determining the [[tissue tropism]], [[infectivity]], and [[Host tropism|species range]] of the virus.<ref>{{cite book | vauthors = Masters PS | title = The molecular biology of coronaviruses | volume = 66 | pages = 193\u2013292 | date = 2006-01-01 | pmid = 16877062 | doi = 10.1016/S0065-3527(06)66005-3 | publisher = Academic Press | isbn = 9780120398690 | quote = Nevertheless, the interaction between S protein and receptor remains the principal, if not sole, determinant of coronavirus host species range and tissue tropism. | series = Advances in Virus Research }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cui J, Li F, Shi ZL | title = Origin and evolution of pathogenic coronaviruses | journal = Nature Reviews. Microbiology | volume = 17 | issue = 3 | pages = 181\u2013192 | date = March 2019 | pmid = 30531947 | doi = 10.1038/s41579-018-0118-9 | pmc = 7097006 | quote = Different SARS-CoV strains isolated from several hosts vary in their binding affinities for human ACE2 and consequently in their infectivity of human cells76,78 (Fig. 6b) }}</ref> \n\nInside  the envelope, there is the [[Capsid|nucleocapsid]], which is formed from multiple copies of the nucleocapsid (N) protein, which are bound to the positive-sense single-stranded (~30 [[Base pair|kb]]) RNA genome in a continuous [[Bead|beads-on-a-string]] type conformation.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = An Overview of Their Replication and Pathogenesis; Section 2 Genomic Organization | journal = Methods in Molecular Biology | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc | quote = See section: Virion Structure. }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Chang CK, Hou MH, Chang CF, Hsiao CD, Huang TH | title = The SARS coronavirus nucleocapsid protein--forms and functions | journal = Antiviral Research | volume = 103 | pages = 39\u201350 | date = March 2014 | pmid = 24418573 | doi = 10.1016/j.antiviral.2013.12.009 | quote = See Figure 4c. }}</ref> The lipid bilayer envelope, membrane proteins, and nucleocapsid protect the virus  when it is outside the host.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Neuman BW, Kiss G, Kunding AH, Bhella D, Baksh MF, Connelly S, Droese B, Klaus JP, Makino S, Sawicki SG, Siddell SG, Stamou DG, Wilson IA, Kuhn P, Buchmeier MJ | display-authors = 6 | title = A structural analysis of M protein in coronavirus assembly and morphology | journal = Journal of Structural Biology | volume = 174 | issue = 1 | pages = 11\u201322 | date = April 2011 | pmid = 21130884 | pmc = 4486061 | doi = 10.1016/j.jsb.2010.11.021 | quote = See Figure 10. }}</ref>\n\n== Life cycle ==\n\nSARS-related coronavirus follows the replication strategy typical of all coronaviruses.<ref name = \"Fehr_2015\" /><ref>{{cite web | vauthors = Tok TT, Tatar G | title = Structures and Functions of Coronavirus Proteins: Molecular Modeling of Viral Nucleoprotein. |url = https://www.scireslit.com/Virology/IJVID-ID13.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Molecular Biology of the SARS-Coronavirus |doi=10.1007/978-3-642-03683-5|isbn=978-3-642-03682-8|year=2010|editor1-last=Lal|editor1-first=Sunil K | name-list-format = vanc }}</ref>\n\n=== Attachment and entry ===\n[[File:Coronavirus replication cycle.jpg|thumb|Coronavirus replication cycle]]\nThe attachment of the SARS-related coronavirus to the host cell is mediated by the spike protein and its receptor.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc | quote = See section: Coronavirus Life Cycle \u2013 Attachment and Entry }}</ref> The spike protein receptor binding domain (RBD) recognizes and attaches to the [[angiotensin-converting enzyme 2]] (ACE2) receptor.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Ge XY, Li JL, Yang XL, Chmura AA, Zhu G, Epstein JH, Mazet JK, Hu B, Zhang W, Peng C, Zhang YJ, Luo CM, Tan B, Wang N, Zhu Y, Crameri G, Zhang SY, Wang LF, Daszak P, Shi ZL | display-authors = 6 | title = Isolation and characterization of a bat SARS-like coronavirus that uses the ACE2 receptor | journal = Nature | volume = 503 | issue = 7477 | pages = 535\u20138 | date = November 2013 | pmid = 24172901 | pmc = 5389864 | doi = 10.1038/nature12711 | bibcode = 2013Natur.503..535G }}</ref> Following attachment, the virus can enter the host cell by two different paths. The path the virus takes depends on the host [[protease]] available to cleave and activate the receptor-attached spike protein.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Simmons G, Zmora P, Gierer S, Heurich A, P\u00f6hlmann S | title = Proteolytic activation of the SARS-coronavirus spike protein: cutting enzymes at the cutting edge of antiviral research | journal = Antiviral Research | volume = 100 | issue = 3 | pages = 605\u201314 | date = December 2013 | pmid = 24121034 | pmc = 3889862 | doi = 10.1016/j.antiviral.2013.09.028 | quote = See Figure 2. }}</ref>\n\nThe first path the SARS coronavirus can take to enter the host cell is by [[endocytosis]] and uptake of the virus in an [[endosome]]. The receptor-attached spike protein is then activated by the host's pH-dependent [[cysteine protease]] [[cathepsin L]]. Activation of the receptor-attached spike protein causes a [[conformational change]], and the subsequent fusion of the viral envelope with the [[Lipid bilayer|endosomal wall]].<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nAlternatively, the virus can enter the host cell directly by [[Proteolysis|proteolytic]] cleavage of the receptor-attached spike protein by the host's [[TMPRSS2]] or [[TMPRSS11D]] [[Serine protease|serine proteases]] at the cell surface.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Heurich A, Hofmann-Winkler H, Gierer S, Liepold T, Jahn O, P\u00f6hlmann S | title = TMPRSS2 and ADAM17 cleave ACE2 differentially and only proteolysis by TMPRSS2 augments entry driven by the severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus spike protein | journal = Journal of Virology | volume = 88 | issue = 2 | pages = 1293\u2013307 | date = January 2014 | pmid = 24227843 | pmc = 3911672 | doi = 10.1128/JVI.02202-13 | quote = The SARS-CoV can hijack two cellular proteolytic systems to ensure the adequate processing of its S protein. Cleavage of SARS-S can be facilitated by cathepsin L, a pH-dependent endo-/lysosomal host cell protease, upon uptake of virions into target cell endosomes (25). Alternatively, the type II transmembrane serine proteases (TTSPs) TMPRSS2 and HAT can activate SARS-S, presumably by cleavage of SARS-S at or close to the cell surface, and activation of SARS-S by TMPRSS2 allows for cathepsin L-independent cellular entry (26,\u201328). }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Zumla A, Chan JF, Azhar EI, Hui DS, Yuen KY | title = Coronaviruses - drug discovery and therapeutic options | journal = Nature Reviews. Drug Discovery | volume = 15 | issue = 5 | pages = 327\u201347 | date = May 2016 | pmid = 26868298 | doi = 10.1038/nrd.2015.37 | pmc = 7097181 | quote = S is activated and cleaved into the S1 and S2 subunits by other host proteases, such as transmembrane protease serine 2 (TMPRSS2) and TMPRSS11D, which enables cell surface non-endosomal virus entry at the plasma membrane. }}</ref> In the SARS coronavirus, the activation of the [[C-terminus|C-terminal part]] of the spike protein triggers the fusion of the viral envelope with the host cell membrane by inducing conformational changes which are not fully understood.<ref name=\"pmid316509562\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Li Z, Tomlinson AC, Wong AH, Zhou D, Desforges M, Talbot PJ, Benlekbir S, Rubinstein JL, Rini JM | display-authors = 6 | title = The human coronavirus HCoV-229E S-protein structure and receptor binding | journal = eLife | volume = 8 | issue =  | date = October 2019 | pmid = 31650956 | pmc = 6970540 | doi = 10.7554/eLife.51230 }}</ref>\n\n=== Genome translation ===\n{|class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" |col2style=text-align:right| style= \"width:auto; float:right; clear:right; margin:0px 0px 0.5em 1em;\"\n!colspan=2| Function of coronavirus <br> nonstructural proteins (nsps)<ref name=\":1\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc | quote = See Table 2. }}</ref>\n|-\n! Protein || Function\n|-\n| nsp1 || Promotes host [[Messenger RNA|mRNA]] degradation, blocks host [[Translation (biology)|translation]]; <br>blocks [[Innate immune system|innate immune response]]\n|-\n| nsp2 || Binds to [[prohibitin]] proteins; <br>unknown function\n|-\n| nsp3 ||[[Protein domain|Multidoman]] [[transmembrane protein]]; interacts with [[Capsid|N protein]]; promotes [[cytokine]] expression; [[Papain|PLPro]] domain cleaves [[Proteolysis|polyprotein]] pp1ab and blocks host's innate immune response; other domains unknown functions\n|-\n| nsp4 || Transmembrane [[scaffold protein]]; <br>allows proper structure for [[Lipid bilayer|double membrane vesicles]] (DMVs)\n|-\n| nsp5 ||[[C30 Endopeptidase|3CLPro]] cleaves polyprotein pp1ab\n|-\n| nsp6 || Transmembrane scaffold protein; <br>unknown function\n|-\n| nsp7 || Forms [[Oligomer|hexadecameric]] complex with nsp8; [[Processivity|processivity clamp]] for [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase|RdRp]] (nsp12)\n|-\n| nsp8 || Forms hexadecameric complex with nsp7; processivity clamp for RdRp (nsp12); acts as a [[primase]]\n|-\n| nsp9 ||[[RNA-binding protein|RNA binding protein]] (RBP)\n|-\n| nsp10 || nsp16 and nsp14 [[Cofactor (biochemistry)|cofactor]]; forms heterodimer with both; stimulates [[2'-O-methylation|2-O-MT]] (nsp16) and [[Exoribonuclease|ExoN]] (nsp14) activity\n|-\n| nsp11 || Unknown function\n|-\n| nsp12 ||[[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase]] (RdRp)\n|-\n| nsp13 ||[[Helicase|RNA helicase]], [[Triphosphatase|5\u2032 triphosphatase]]\n|-\n| nsp14 ||[[Methyltransferase|N7 Methyltransferase]], [[Exoribonuclease|3\u2032-5\u2032 exoribonuclease]] (ExoN); N7 MTase adds [[Five-prime cap|5\u2032 cap]], ExoN [[Proofreading (biology)|proofreads genome]]\n|-\n| nsp15 ||[[Endoribonuclease]] (NendoU)\n|-\n| nsp16 ||[[2'-O-methylation|2\u2032-O-Methyltransferase]] (2-O-MT); protects viral RNA from [[MDA5]]\n|-\n|}\nAfter fusion the nucleocapsid passes into the [[cytoplasm]], where the viral genome is released.<ref name=\":2\" /> The genome [[Ribosome-binding_site|acts as a messenger RNA]], and the cell's [[ribosomes|ribosome]] [[Translation_(biology)|translates]] two-thirds of the genome, which corresponds to the open reading frame ORF1a and ORF1b, into two large overlapping polyproteins, pp1a and pp1ab. \n\nThe larger polyprotein pp1ab is a result of a [[ribosomal frameshift|-1 ribosomal frameshift]] caused by a [[slippery sequence]] (UUUAAAC) and a downstream [[Nucleic acid secondary structure|RNA pseudoknot]] at the end of open reading frame ORF1a.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Masters PS | title = The molecular biology of coronaviruses | journal = Advances in Virus Research | volume = 66 | pages = 193\u2013292 | date = 2006-01-01 | pmid = 16877062 | doi = 10.1016/S0065-3527(06)66005-3 | publisher = Academic Press | isbn = 9780120398690 | quote =See Figure 8. }}</ref> The ribosomal frameshift allows for the continuous translation of ORF1a followed by ORF1b.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nThe polyproteins contain their own [[C30_Endopeptidase|proteases]],  [[Papain|PLpro]] and [[C30 Endopeptidase|3CLpro]], which cleave the polyproteins at different specific sites. The cleavage of polyprotein pp1ab yields 16 nonstructural proteins (nsp1 to nsp16). Product proteins include various replication  proteins such as [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase]] (RdRp), [[RNA helicase]], and [[exoribonuclease]] (ExoN).<ref name=\":3\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc |quote=See section: Replicase Protein Expression }}</ref>\n\n=== Replication and transcription ===\n[[File:Replication-transcription complex for Coronaviruses.tif|thumb|Model of the replicase-transcriptase complex of a coronavirus. [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase|RdRp]] for [[DNA replication|replication]] (red), [[Exoribonuclease|ExoN]] for [[Proofreading (biology)|proofreading]] (dark blue), ExoN cofactor (yellow), [[RNA-binding protein|RBPs]] to avoid [[Nucleic acid secondary structure|secondary structure]] (light blue), [[DNA clamp|RNA sliding clamp]] for [[processivity]] and [[primase]] [[Protein domain|domain]] for [[Primer (molecular biology)|priming]] (green/orange), and a [[helicase]] to unwind RNA (downstream). ]]\n\nA number of the nonstructural replication proteins coalesce to form a [[Protein complex|multi-protein]] replicase-transcriptase complex (RTC).<ref name=\":3\" /> The main replicase-transcriptase protein is the [[RNA-dependent RNA polymerase]] (RdRp). It is directly involved in the [[DNA replication|replication]] and [[Transcription (biology)|transcription]] of RNA from an RNA strand. The other nonstructural proteins in the complex assist in the replication and transcription process.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\nThe protein nsp15 is a [[Exoribonuclease|3'-5' exoribonuclease]] which provides extra fidelity to the replication process. The exoribonuclease provides a [[Proofreading (biology)|proofreading]] function to the complex which the RNA-dependent RNA polymerase lacks. Similarly, proteins nsp7 and nsp8 form a hexadecameric sliding clamp as part of the complex which greatly increases the [[processivity]] of the RNA-dependent RNA polymerase.<ref name=\":1\" /> The coronaviruses require the increased fidelity and processivity during RNA synthesis because of the relatively large genome size in comparison to other RNA viruses.<ref name=\"SextonSmith2016\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Sexton NR, Smith EC, Blanc H, Vignuzzi M, Peersen OB, Denison MR|date=August 2016|title=Homology-Based Identification of a Mutation in the Coronavirus RNA-Dependent RNA Polymerase That Confers Resistance to Multiple Mutagens|journal=Journal of Virology|volume=90|issue=16|pages=7415\u201328|doi=10.1128/JVI.00080-16|pmc=4984655|pmid=27279608|quote=Finally, these results, combined with those from previous work (33, 44), suggest that CoVs encode at least three proteins involved in fidelity (nsp12-RdRp, nsp14-ExoN, and nsp10), supporting the assembly of a multiprotein replicase-fidelity complex, as described previously (38).}}</ref>\n\nOne of the main functions of the replicase-transcriptase complex is to transcribe the viral genome. RdRp directly mediates the [[transcription (biology)|synthesis]] of  negative-sense subgenomic RNA molecules from the positive-sense genomic RNA. This is followed by the transcription of these negative-sense subgenomic RNA molecules to their corresponding positive-sense [[Messenger RNA|mRNAs]].<ref name=\":5\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc |quote=See section: Corona Life Cycle \u2013 Replication and Transcription}}</ref>\n\nThe other important function of the replicase-transcriptase complex is to replicate the viral genome. RdRp directly mediates the [[DNA replication|synthesis]] of negative-sense genomic RNA from the positive-sense genomic RNA. This is followed by the replication of positive-sense genomic RNA from the negative-sense genomic RNA.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n\nThe replicated positive-sense genomic RNA becomes the genome of the [[viral shedding|progeny viruses]]. The various smaller mRNAs are transcripts from the last third of the virus genome which follows the reading frames ORF1a and ORF1b. These mRNAs are translated into the four structural proteins (S, E, M, and N) that will become part of the progeny virus particles and also eight other accessory proteins (orf3 to orf9b) which assist the virus.<ref>{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc | quote = See Figure 1. }}</ref>\n\n=== Assembly and release ===\n\n[[Translation (biology)|RNA translation]] occurs  inside the [[endoplasmic reticulum]]. The viral structural proteins S,  E and M  move along the secretory pathway into the [[Vesicular-tubular_cluster|Golgi intermediate compartment]]. There, the M proteins direct most protein-protein interactions required for assembly of viruses following its binding to the nucleocapsid.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite book | vauthors = Fehr AR, Perlman S | title = Coronaviruses | chapter = Coronaviruses: an overview of their replication and pathogenesis | volume = 1282 | pages = 1\u201323 | date = 2015 | pmid = 25720466 | pmc = 4369385 | doi = 10.1007/978-1-4939-2438-7_1 | publisher = Springer | isbn = 978-1-4939-2438-7 | series = Methods in Molecular Biology | editor-first = Helena Jane | editor-last = Maier | editor2-first = Erica | editor2-last = Bickerton | editor3-first = Paul | editor3-last = Britton | name-list-format = vanc |quote=See section: Coronavirus Life Cycle \u2013 Assembly and Release }}</ref>\n\nProgeny viruses are released from the host cell by [[exocytosis]] through secretory vesicles.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Coronavirus disease 2019}}\n*[[Bat SARS-like coronavirus WIV1|SARS-like coronavirus WIV1]] (SL-CoV-WIV1)\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{Refbegin|2}}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Peiris JS, Lai ST, Poon LL, Guan Y, Yam LY, Lim W, Nicholls J, Yee WK, Yan WW, Cheung MT, Cheng VC, Chan KH, Tsang DN, Yung RW, Ng TK, Yuen KY | display-authors = 6 | title = Coronavirus as a possible cause of severe acute respiratory syndrome | journal = Lancet | volume = 361 | issue = 9366 | pages = 1319\u201325 | date = April 2003 | pmid = 12711465 | doi = 10.1016/s0140-6736(03)13077-2 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Rota PA, Oberste MS, Monroe SS, Nix WA, Campagnoli R, Icenogle JP, Pe\u00f1aranda S, Bankamp B, Maher K, Chen MH, Tong S, Tamin A, Lowe L, Frace M, DeRisi JL, Chen Q, Wang D, Erdman DD, Peret TC, Burns C, Ksiazek TG, Rollin PE, Sanchez A, Liffick S, Holloway B, Limor J, McCaustland K, Olsen-Rasmussen M, Fouchier R, G\u00fcnther S, Osterhaus AD, Drosten C, Pallansch MA, Anderson LJ, Bellini WJ | display-authors = 6 | title = Characterization of a novel coronavirus associated with severe acute respiratory syndrome | journal = Science | volume = 300 | issue = 5624 | pages = 1394\u20139 | date = May 2003 | pmid = 12730500 | doi = 10.1126/science.1085952 | bibcode = 2003Sci...300.1394R }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Marra MA, Jones SJ, Astell CR, Holt RA, Brooks-Wilson A, Butterfield YS, Khattra J, Asano JK, Barber SA, Chan SY, Cloutier A, Coughlin SM, Freeman D, Girn N, Griffith OL, Leach SR, Mayo M, McDonald H, Montgomery SB, Pandoh PK, Petrescu AS, Robertson AG, Schein JE, Siddiqui A, Smailus DE, Stott JM, Yang GS, Plummer F, Andonov A, Artsob H, Bastien N, Bernard K, Booth TF, Bowness D, Czub M, Drebot M, Fernando L, Flick R, Garbutt M, Gray M, Grolla A, Jones S, Feldmann H, Meyers A, Kabani A, Li Y, Normand S, Stroher U, Tipples GA, Tyler S, Vogrig R, Ward D, Watson B, Brunham RC, Krajden M, Petric M, Skowronski DM, Upton C, Roper RL | display-authors = 6 | title = The Genome sequence of the SARS-associated coronavirus | journal = Science | volume = 300 | issue = 5624 | pages = 1399\u2013404 | date = May 2003 | pmid = 12730501 | doi = 10.1126/science.1085953 | bibcode = 2003Sci...300.1399M }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Snijder EJ, Bredenbeek PJ, Dobbe JC, Thiel V, Ziebuhr J, Poon LL, Guan Y, Rozanov M, Spaan WJ, Gorbalenya AE | display-authors = 6 | title = Unique and conserved features of genome and proteome of SARS-coronavirus, an early split-off from the coronavirus group 2 lineage | journal = Journal of Molecular Biology | volume = 331 | issue = 5 | pages = 991\u20131004 | date = August 2003 | pmid = 12927536 | doi = 10.1016/S0022-2836(03)00865-9 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.319.7007 }}\n* {{cite journal | vauthors = Yount B, Roberts RS, Lindesmith L, Baric RS | title = Rewiring the severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus (SARS-CoV) transcription circuit: engineering a recombination-resistant genome | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 103 | issue = 33 | pages = 12546\u201351 | date = August 2006 | pmid = 16891412 | pmc = 1531645 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0605438103 | bibcode = 2006PNAS..10312546Y }}\n* {{cite book | veditors = Thiel V | title = Coronaviruses: Molecular and Cellular Biology | edition = 1st | publisher = Caister Academic Press | year = 2007 |  isbn =  978-1-904455-16-5 }}\n* {{cite book | vauthors = Enjuanes L, Sola I, Z\u00fa\u00f1iga S, Almaz\u00e1n F |year=2008 |chapter=Coronavirus Replication and Interaction with Host |title=Animal Viruses: Molecular Biology |publisher=Caister Academic Press |isbn= 978-1-904455-22-6 | veditors = Mettenleiter TC, Sobrino F}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikispecies}}\n\n* [http://www.who.int/mediacentre/releases/2003/pr31/en/ WHO press release identifying and naming the SARS virus]\n* [http://www.bcgsc.ca/bioinfo/SARS/ The SARS virus genetic map]\n* [http://www.sciencemag.org/site/feature/data/sars/ ''Science'' special on the SARS virus] (free content: no registration required)\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050301194019/http://www.health.library.mcgill.ca/resource/sars.htm |date=1 March 2005 |title=McGill University SARS Resources }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160412085632/http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/sars/ U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) SARS home]\n* [http://www.castanet.net/news/Canada/80872/World-Health-Organization-on-alert World Health Organization on alert]\n\n{{SARS}}\n{{Viral diseases}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q278567}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Severe acute respiratory syndrome-related coronavirus}}\n[[Category:Sarbecovirus]]\n", "name_user": "Widefox", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:MOS italics/acro", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Severe_acute_respiratory_syndrome-related_coronavirus"}
{"title_page": "Al-Hakam II", "text_new": "{{For|the caliph of Cairo|Al-Hakim II}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|name= Al-Hakam II<br>({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062d\u06a9\u0645 \u062b\u0627\u0646\u06cc}})\n|image=MonAlhakenII01.jpg\n|succession   = 2nd [[Caliphate of C\u00f3rdoba|Caliph of C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|birth_date= January 13, 915\n|birth_place=[[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain|Cordoba]]\n|death_date= {{death date and age|976|10|16|915|1|13}} \n|death_place=[[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain|Cordoba]]\n|father= Abd-ar-Rahman III\n|reign= 15 October 961 \u2013 16 October 976\n|predecessor= [[Abd-ar-Rahman III]]\n|successor= [[Hisham II]]\n| house           = [[Banu Umayya|Umayyad]]\n| house-type      = Dynasty\n| mother = Murjan \n}}\n'''Al-Hakam II''' ({{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064e\u0627\u0635\u064d \u0627\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064f\u0633\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0646\u0652\u0635\u0650\u0631\u0650 \u0628\u0650\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647\u0650 \u0627\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064f\u0643\u0652\u0645\u0650 \u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0639\u064e\u0628\u0652\u062f\u0650 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064e\u0651\u062d\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0646\u0650}}); January 13, 915 \u2013 October 16, 976) was an [[Arab]] Caliph of [[Caliphate of C\u00f3rdoba|C\u00f3rdoba]]. He was the second ''Umayyad'' [[Caliph of C\u00f3rdoba]] in [[Al-Andalus]], and son of [[Abd-ar-Rahman III]] and Murjan. He ruled from 961 to 976.\n\n==Early rule==\n[[File:Golden dinar al hakam ii 21341.jpg|thumb|Dinar of al-Hakam II c. 969 AD]]\n[[File:AlHakemII dirhem MedinaAzahara.jpg|thumb|Dirham of ''Emir'' al-Hakam II]]\nAl-Hakam II succeeded to the Caliphate after the death of his father Abd-ar-Rahman III in 961. He secured peace with the [[Catholicism#Catholic Church use|Catholic]] kingdoms of northern Iberia, and made use of the stability to develop agriculture through the construction of irrigation works. Economic development was also encouraged through the widening of streets and the building of markets.\n\n==Patron of knowledge==\nHakam himself was very well versed in numerous sciences. He would have books purchased from [[Damascus]], [[Baghdad]], [[Constantinople]], [[Cairo]], [[Mecca]], [[Medina]], [[Kufa]], and [[Basra]]. His status as a patron of knowledge brought him fame across the Muslim world to the point that even books written in [[Persia]], which was under [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasid]] control, were dedicated to him. During his reign, a massive translation effort was undertaken, and many books were translated from [[Latin]] and [[Greek language|Greek]] into [[Arabic language|Arabic]]. He formed a joint committee of [[Muladi]] Muslims and [[Mozarabs|Mozarab]] Catholics for this task.<ref name=\"The History of Islam\">{{cite book|last=Najeebabadi|first=Akbar|title=The History of Islam V.3|year=2001|publisher=Darussalam|location=Riyadh|isbn=978-9960-892-93-1|pages=145}}</ref>\n\nHis personal library was of enormous proportions. Some accounts speak of him having more than 600,000 books. However, Hitchcock (2014: 91-92) argues that any number in excess of 600 is \"inconceivable\".<ref name=\"Muslim Spain reconsidered\">{{cite book|last=Hitchcock|first=Richard|title=Muslim Spain reconsidered|year=2014|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|location=Edinburgh|isbn=978-0-7486-3960-1|pages=91\u201392}}</ref> The catalogue of library books itself was claimed to be 44 volumes long. According to Hitchcock (ibid.), this may be because \"volume\" and \"page\" were confused. Of special importance to Al-Hakam was history, and he himself wrote a history of al-Andalus.<ref name=\"The History of Islam\"/> Following his death, ''[[Hajib]]'' [[Almanzor]] had all \"ancient science\" books destroyed.<ref>Ann Christy, ''Christians in Al-Andalus:711-1000'', (Curzon Press, 2002), 142.</ref>\n\nThe mathematician [[Lubna of C\u00f3rdoba]] was employed as Al-Hakam's private secretary. She was said to be \"thoroughly versed in the exact sciences; her talents were equal to the solution of the most complex geometrical and algebraic problems\".<ref name=\"History of the Moorish Empire in Europe Vol. 3\">{{cite book|last=Scott|first=Samuel Parsons|title=History of the Moorish Empire in Europe Vol. 3|year=1904|publisher=Lippincott|pages=447|url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofmoorish03scotuoft#page/446/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nThe famous [[physician]], [[scientist]], and [[surgeon]] [[Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi]] (Abulcasis) was also active in Al-Hakam's court during his reign.\n\n==Construction projects==\n[[File:Salon Rico 1.jpg|320px|thumb|[[Medina Azahara]], completed by Al-Hakam II]]\nHis building works included an expansion of the main mosque of [[C\u00f3rdoba, Andalusia|C\u00f3rdoba]] (962\u2013966), the [[Mosque\u2013Cathedral of C\u00f3rdoba|Mezquita]], and the completion of the royal residence [[Medina Azahara]] (976), which his father had begun in 936.\n\n==Military conflict in North Africa==\nWhilst the internal administration was left increasingly to [[Vizier|vizir]] Al-Mushafi,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN9788489569850|title=Almanzor|last=Bariani|first=Laura|date=2003|publisher=Editorial NEREA|year=|isbn=9788489569850|location=|pages=66|language=es}}</ref> general [[Gh\u0101lib ibn \u02bfAbd al-Ra\u1e25m\u0101n]] was gradually gaining influence as leader of the army in North Africa. He was chiefly preoccupied with repulsing the last [[Normans|Norman]] attacks (c. 970),<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xd5VonTOppMC|title=E. J. Brill's First Encyclopaedia of Islam 1913 - 1936 Volume III|last=Brill|first=E. J.|date=1993|isbn=9004097899|pages=223}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Vikings raids on the Spanish Peninsula|url=http://revistas.ucm.es/index.php/MILT/article/view/MILT9696110067A/3416|access-date=2018-10-05|last=Scheen|first=Rolf|journal=Militaria. Revista de culturea militar|publisher=[[Complutense University of Madrid]]|pages=72|date=1996}}</ref> and with the struggle against the [[Zirid dynasty|Zirids]] and the [[Fatimid Caliphate|Fatimids]] in northern [[Morocco]]. The Fatimids were defeated in Morocco in 974, while Al-Hakam II was able to maintain the supremacy of the caliphate over the Catholic states of [[Kingdom of Navarre|Navarre]], [[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]] and [[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n|Le\u00f3n]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAl-Hakam married [[Subh of Cordoba]], a [[Basques|Basque]] [[Concubinage|concubine]]. She held sway and strong influence over the court. It is said that al-Hakam nicknamed her with the masculine name Ja'far.<ref name=Ruggles>{{Cite journal| volume = 34| issue = 1| last = Ruggles| first = D. Fairchild |authorlink=D. Fairchild Ruggles| title = Mothers of a hybrid dynasty: Race, genealogy, and acculturation in al-Andalus| journal = Journal of Medieval and Early Modern Studies| date = 2004| url = https://muse.jhu.edu/article/53027/summary|page=73}}</ref> She bore him two sons, the first is Abd al-Rahman,<ref name=muqarnas /> who died young, and the second is [[Hisham II]].<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Routledge| isbn = 978-1-136-12730-4| last = Christys| first = Ann Rosemary| title = Christians in Al-Andalus 711-1000| date = 2013-01-11|page=106}}</ref> \n\nAccording to [[\u00c9. L\u00e9vi-Proven\u00e7al]], the phrase ''\u1e24ubb al-walad'', as found in [[al-Maqqari]]'s ''Naf\u1e25 al-\u1e6dayyib'',<ref>Al-Makkari, [https://archive.org/details/analectessurlhis21maqq/page/n64/mode/1up ''Analectes sur l'histoire et la litt\u00e9rature des Arabes d'Espagne''], vol.2, p.59)</ref> is a reference to al-Hakam's [[homosexuality]] or \"preference for boys\".<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Espasa-Calpe| last = L\u00e9vi-Proven\u00e7al| first = Evariste| title = Espa\u00f1a musulmana hasta la ca\u00edda del Califato de C\u00f3rdoba (711-1031 de J.C.)| date = 1957|page=447-8|quote=Hay, indudablemente, algo de verdad en la alusi\u00e9n que un cronista musulm\u00e1n (apud Maqqari, ''Analectes'', II, 59) hace a la \u00abpaidofilias\u00bb (''hubb al-walad'') de al-Hakam II, antes de su accesi\u00e9n al trono. En todo caso es evidente que s\u00f3lo despu\u00e9s de su adveni- miento fu\u00e9 cuando se preocup\u00f3 de tener un hijo susceptible de sucederle. \u00bfHabr\u00e1 que creer, seg\u00fan el mismo cronista, que fu\u00e9 la practica de este vicio, tan corriente en la Espa\u00f1a musulmana en todas las \u00e9pocas, el que occasion\u00f3 la paternidad tan tard\u00eda de al-Hakam II? V\u00e9ase, sin embargo, Ibn Hazm, ''Tawg al-hamama'', p\u00e1g. 6, a prop\u00f3sito de la pasi\u00f3n que sent\u00eda el califa por su concubina Subh.}}</ref><ref name=muqarnas /> The fact that he did not produce a suitable heir before the age of 46 has been ascribed either to him being [[homosexual]],<ref>[[\u00c9variste L\u00e9vi-Proven\u00e7al]], ''Histoire de l'Espagne musulmane'', Paris, 1950</ref> although this is only reported euphemistically in the sources,<ref name=muqarnas>{{Cite journal| volume = 14| pages = 19\u201341| last = Prado-Vilar| first = Francisco| title = Circular visions of fertility and punishment: caliphal ivory caskets from al-Andalus| journal = Muqarnas| date = 1997| jstor = 1523234}}</ref> or because he was too absorbed with his books to care for sensual pleasures.<ref name=Ruggles />\nHis wife, Subh, is said to have dressed as a [[ghulam]] or a young man to make herself more attractive to al-Hakam (adopting a short haircut and wearing trousers). Although it is also possible she also did this in order to gain better access to the male-dominated royal court.<ref>Ibtissam Bouachrine, ''Women and Islam'', Lexington Books, 2014, pp. 5, 22</ref>\n\n==Death and succession==\nAl-Hakam II suffered a [[stroke]] near the end of his life that curtailed his activities and may explain why he was unable to properly prepare his son for leadership.<ref>''Al-Hakam II, Caliph of Cordoba'', Marilyn Higbee Walker, '''Encyclopedia of Medieval Iberia''', ed. Michael Gerli (New York: Routledge, 2003), 377.</ref> Modern scholars have speculated that, based on the historical descriptions of his death, it was another [[cerebral circulation|cerebrovascular]] stroke, possibly brought on by the cold weather, that claimed his life in October 976.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Arjona-Castro|first=A.|title=Cerebrovascular stroke, the cause of the death of the caliph al-Hakam II|journal=Neurologia|date=February 1997|volume=12|issue=2|pages=78\u201381}}</ref>  He was succeeded by his son, [[Hisham II]] al-Mu'ayad, who was 11 years old at the time and was a nominal ruler under Almanzor.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Islam|Spain|LGBT|Biography|History}}\n*[[Moors]]\n*[[Islam in Spain]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource author}}\n{{Commons category|Al-Hakam II}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040814210621/http://history.al-islam.com/names.asp?year=366#n1771 Arabic biography]\n*[http://www.stirnet.com/genie/data/continent/hijk/iberia04.php#cord1 Stirnet: Iberia04] {{subscription required}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Banu Umayya]]|||||[[Quraysh tribe|Banu Quraish]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Abd ar-Rahman III]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Caliph of C\u00f3rdoba]]|years=961\u2013976}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hisham II]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Umayyads}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hakam 02}}\n[[Category:10th-century caliphs of C\u00f3rdoba]]\n[[Category:915 births]]\n[[Category:976 deaths]]\n[[Category:Umayyad caliphs of C\u00f3rdoba]]\n[[Category:10th-century Arabs]]\n[[Category:10th-century Muslims]]\n[[Category:Medieval LGBT history]]\n[[Category:Medieval LGBT people]]\n[[Category:LGBT Muslims]]\n[[Category:Gay royalty]]\n[[Category:LGBT heads of state]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the caliph of Cairo|Al-Hakim II}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n|name= Al-Hakam II({{lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062d\u06a9\u0645 \u062b\u0627\u0646\u06cc}})\n|image=MonAlhakenII01.jpg\n|succession   = 2nd [[Caliphate of C\u00f3rdoba|Caliph of C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|birth_date= January 13, 915\n|birth_place=[[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain|Cordoba]]\n|death_date= {{death date and age|976|10|16|915|1|13}} \n|death_place=[[C\u00f3rdoba, Spain|Cordoba]]\n|father= Abd-ar-Rahman III\n|reign= 15 October 961 \u2013 16 October 976\n|predecessor= [[Abd-ar-Rahman III]]\n|successor= [[Hisham II]]\n| house           = [[Banu Umayya|Umayyad]]\n| house-type      = Dynasty\n| mother = Murjan \n}}\n'''Al-Hakam II''' ({{lang|ar|\u0623\u064e\u0628\u064f\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u0652\u0639\u064e\u0627\u0635\u064d \u0627\u0644\u0652\u0645\u064f\u0633\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0646\u0652\u0635\u0650\u0631\u0650 \u0628\u0650\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647\u0650 \u0627\u0644\u0652\u062d\u064f\u0643\u0652\u0645\u0650 \u0628\u0652\u0646 \u0639\u064e\u0628\u0652\u062f\u0650 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u064e\u0651\u062d\u0652\u0645\u064e\u0646\u0650}}); January 13, 915 \u2013 October 16, 976) was an [[Arab]] Caliph of [[Caliphate of C\u00f3rdoba|C\u00f3rdoba]]. He was the second ''Umayyad'' [[Caliph of C\u00f3rdoba]] in [[Al-Andalus]], and son of [[Abd-ar-Rahman III]] and Murjan. He ruled from 961 to 976.\n\n==Early rule==\n[[File:Golden dinar al hakam ii 21341.jpg|thumb|Dinar of al-Hakam II c. 969 AD]]\n[[File:AlHakemII dirhem MedinaAzahara.jpg|thumb|Dirham of ''Emir'' al-Hakam II]]\nAl-Hakam II succeeded to the Caliphate after the death of his father Abd-ar-Rahman III in 961. He secured peace with the [[Catholicism#Catholic Church use|Catholic]] kingdoms of northern Iberia, and made use of the stability to develop agriculture through the construction of irrigation works. Economic development was also encouraged through the widening of streets and the building of markets.\n\n==Patron of knowledge==\nHakam himself was very well versed in numerous sciences. He would have books purchased from [[Damascus]], [[Baghdad]], [[Constantinople]], [[Cairo]], [[Mecca]], [[Medina]], [[Kufa]], and [[Basra]]. His status as a patron of knowledge brought him fame across the Muslim world to the point that even books written in [[Persia]], which was under [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasid]] control, were dedicated to him. During his reign, a massive translation effort was undertaken, and many books were translated from [[Latin]] and [[Greek language|Greek]] into [[Arabic language|Arabic]]. He formed a joint committee of [[Muladi]] Muslims and [[Mozarabs|Mozarab]] Catholics for this task.<ref name=\"The History of Islam\">{{cite book|last=Najeebabadi|first=Akbar|title=The History of Islam V.3|year=2001|publisher=Darussalam|location=Riyadh|isbn=978-9960-892-93-1|pages=145}}</ref>\n\nHis personal library was of enormous proportions. Some accounts speak of him having more than 600,000 books. However, Hitchcock (2014: 91-92) argues that any number in excess of 600 is \"inconceivable\".<ref name=\"Muslim Spain reconsidered\">{{cite book|last=Hitchcock|first=Richard|title=Muslim Spain reconsidered|year=2014|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|location=Edinburgh|isbn=978-0-7486-3960-1|pages=91\u201392}}</ref> The catalogue of library books itself was claimed to be 44 volumes long. According to Hitchcock (ibid.), this may be because \"volume\" and \"page\" were confused. Of special importance to Al-Hakam was history, and he himself wrote a history of al-Andalus.<ref name=\"The History of Islam\"/> Following his death, ''[[Hajib]]'' [[Almanzor]] had all \"ancient science\" books destroyed.<ref>Ann Christy, ''Christians in Al-Andalus:711-1000'', (Curzon Press, 2002), 142.</ref>\n\nThe mathematician [[Lubna of C\u00f3rdoba]] was employed as Al-Hakam's private secretary. She was said to be \"thoroughly versed in the exact sciences; her talents were equal to the solution of the most complex geometrical and algebraic problems\".<ref name=\"History of the Moorish Empire in Europe Vol. 3\">{{cite book|last=Scott|first=Samuel Parsons|title=History of the Moorish Empire in Europe Vol. 3|year=1904|publisher=Lippincott|pages=447|url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofmoorish03scotuoft#page/446/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nThe famous [[physician]], [[scientist]], and [[surgeon]] [[Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi]] (Abulcasis) was also active in Al-Hakam's court during his reign.\n\n==Construction projects==\n[[File:Salon Rico 1.jpg|320px|thumb|[[Medina Azahara]], completed by Al-Hakam II]]\nHis building works included an expansion of the main mosque of [[C\u00f3rdoba, Andalusia|C\u00f3rdoba]] (962\u2013966), the [[Mosque\u2013Cathedral of C\u00f3rdoba|Mezquita]], and the completion of the royal residence [[Medina Azahara]] (976), which his father had begun in 936.\n\n==Military conflict in North Africa==\nWhilst the internal administration was left increasingly to [[Vizier|vizir]] Al-Mushafi,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?vid=ISBN9788489569850|title=Almanzor|last=Bariani|first=Laura|date=2003|publisher=Editorial NEREA|year=|isbn=9788489569850|location=|pages=66|language=es}}</ref> general [[Gh\u0101lib ibn \u02bfAbd al-Ra\u1e25m\u0101n]] was gradually gaining influence as leader of the army in North Africa. He was chiefly preoccupied with repulsing the last [[Normans|Norman]] attacks (c. 970),<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xd5VonTOppMC|title=E. J. Brill's First Encyclopaedia of Islam 1913 - 1936 Volume III|last=Brill|first=E. J.|date=1993|isbn=9004097899|pages=223}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Vikings raids on the Spanish Peninsula|url=http://revistas.ucm.es/index.php/MILT/article/view/MILT9696110067A/3416|access-date=2018-10-05|last=Scheen|first=Rolf|journal=Militaria. Revista de culturea militar|publisher=[[Complutense University of Madrid]]|pages=72|date=1996}}</ref> and with the struggle against the [[Zirid dynasty|Zirids]] and the [[Fatimid Caliphate|Fatimids]] in northern [[Morocco]]. The Fatimids were defeated in Morocco in 974, while Al-Hakam II was able to maintain the supremacy of the caliphate over the Catholic states of [[Kingdom of Navarre|Navarre]], [[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]] and [[Kingdom of Le\u00f3n|Le\u00f3n]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAl-Hakam married [[Subh of Cordoba]], a [[Basques|Basque]] [[Concubinage|concubine]]. She held sway and strong influence over the court. It is said that al-Hakam nicknamed her with the masculine name Ja'far.<ref name=Ruggles>{{Cite journal| volume = 34| issue = 1| last = Ruggles| first = D. Fairchild |authorlink=D. Fairchild Ruggles| title = Mothers of a hybrid dynasty: Race, genealogy, and acculturation in al-Andalus| journal = Journal of Medieval and Early Modern Studies| date = 2004| url = https://muse.jhu.edu/article/53027/summary|page=73}}</ref> She bore him two sons, the first is Abd al-Rahman,<ref name=muqarnas /> who died young, and the second is [[Hisham II]].<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Routledge| isbn = 978-1-136-12730-4| last = Christys| first = Ann Rosemary| title = Christians in Al-Andalus 711-1000| date = 2013-01-11|page=106}}</ref> Additionally, Subh may have dressed as a [[ghulam]] or a young man to make herself more attractive to al-Hakam (adopting a short haircut and wearing trousers). Although it is also possible she did this in order to gain better access to the male-dominated royal court.<ref>Ibtissam Bouachrine, ''Women and Islam'', Lexington Books, 2014, pp. 5, 22</ref>\n\nAccording to [[\u00c9. L\u00e9vi-Proven\u00e7al]], the phrase ''\u1e24ubb al-walad'', as found in [[al-Maqqari]]'s ''Naf\u1e25 al-\u1e6dayyib'',<ref>Al-Makkari, [https://archive.org/details/analectessurlhis21maqq/page/n64/mode/1up ''Analectes sur l'histoire et la litt\u00e9rature des Arabes d'Espagne''], vol.2, p.59)</ref> is a reference to al-Hakam's [[homosexuality]] or \"preference for boys\".<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Espasa-Calpe| last = L\u00e9vi-Proven\u00e7al| first = Evariste| title = Espa\u00f1a musulmana hasta la ca\u00edda del Califato de C\u00f3rdoba (711-1031 de J.C.)| date = 1957|page=447-8|quote=Hay, indudablemente, algo de verdad en la alusi\u00e9n que un cronista musulm\u00e1n (apud Maqqari, ''Analectes'', II, 59) hace a la \u00abpaidofilias\u00bb (''hubb al-walad'') de al-Hakam II, antes de su accesi\u00e9n al trono. En todo caso es evidente que s\u00f3lo despu\u00e9s de su adveni- miento fu\u00e9 cuando se preocup\u00f3 de tener un hijo susceptible de sucederle. \u00bfHabr\u00e1 que creer, seg\u00fan el mismo cronista, que fu\u00e9 la practica de este vicio, tan corriente en la Espa\u00f1a musulmana en todas las \u00e9pocas, el que occasion\u00f3 la paternidad tan tard\u00eda de al-Hakam II? V\u00e9ase, sin embargo, Ibn Hazm, ''Tawg al-hamama'', p\u00e1g. 6, a prop\u00f3sito de la pasi\u00f3n que sent\u00eda el califa por su concubina Subh.}}</ref><ref name=muqarnas /> However, several historians render it as \"paternal love\", referring instead to him choosing his young son as a successor.<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = By W.H.Allen And Company.| last = De Gayangos| first = Pascual| title = The History Of The Mohammedan Dynasties In Spain Vol II| date = 1843| pages=176-7| url = https://archive.org/details/historyofthemoha032395mbp/page/n193/mode/2up | quote=Ibn Bessam, copying Ibn Hayyan, says, \"Among other virtues Al-hakem possessed that of paternal love in such a degree that it blinded his prudence and induced him to appoint a son of his, who was then a child, to be his successor, in preference to any of his brothers or nephews, all men of mature age, well versed in the management of affairs and in the command of the armies, capable of making their mandates obeyed, and of maintaining themselves in power.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite encyclopedia | publisher = \u00c1rabes Fundaci\u00f3n Ibn Tufayl de Estudios \u00c1rabes| volume = 7| pages = 591| last = al-Wasif | first = M. F.| title = Mustansir, al-Hakam | encyclopedia = [[Biblioteca de al-Andalus]] | date = 2012 |isbn = 978-84-934026-0-0|quote=Cabe se\u00f1alar, por \u00faltimo, que ser\u00eda bastante dif\u00edcil dar credibilidad a la cuesti\u00f3n de la \"paidofilia\" de al-Hakam II en un pasaje de Ibn Hayy\u0101n tomado por al-Maqqar\u012b -y viene m\u00e1s claro en el ''Daj\u012bra''-, en el cual figura ''\u1e25ubb al-walad'' en el contexto de una cr\u00edtica de Ibn \u1e24ayy\u0101n dirigida a al-\u1e24akam II por haberse dejado llevar por el amor al hijo (''\u1e25ubb al-walad'') que le impuls\u00f3 a nombrar y tomar juramento de fidelidad a su hijo menor en calidad de presunto heredero del califato, acto que tuvo lugar el 1 de Jum\u0101da II del 365 (=5 febrero 975) en el Alc\u00e1zar de C\u00f3rdoba, La misma cr\u00edtica basada en dicho argumento, la hace tambi\u00e9n Ibn al-Ja\u1e6d\u012bb en sus ''A\u02bfm\u0101l''. Y no vamos a insistir in la evidencia de que el t\u00e9rmino ''waled'' significa \"hijo\", empleado en muchas ocasiones en los textos andalus\u00edes para referirse a un infante Omeya, y no \"efebo/s\" (''gulam''/''gilm\u0101n''), y \u00e9ste precedido por \"hubb\" indicar\u00eda lo que se ha dicho antes.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| last = Garc\u00eda-Sanju\u00e1n| first = Alejandro| title = Legalidad isl\u00e1mica y legitimidad pol\u00edtica en el califato de C\u00f3rdoba: la proclamaci\u00f3n de Hisham II (360-66/971-76)| journal = Al-Qantara XXIX-1 (2008)| url = https://www.academia.edu/468044/Legalidad_isl%C3%A1mica_y_legitimidad_pol%C3%ADtica_en_el_califato_de_C%C3%B3rdoba_la_proclamaci%C3%B3n_de_Hisham_II_360-66_971-76_ |page=70|quote=Ibn Hayyan, quien no duda en condenar la actuaci\u00f3n de al-Hakam sobre su sucesi\u00f3n, acus\u00e1ndolo de haberse dejado llevar en exceso por el amor hacia el hijo (''k\u0101na mimman istahw\u0101-hu \u1e25ubb al-walad wa-afra\u1e6da f\u012b-h\u012b'') y descartando as\u00ed como heredero a alg\u00fan adulto, bien fuese alguno de sus hermanos u otro miembro del linaje Omeya que pudiese haber desempe\u00f1ado el imamato \u00absin favoritismos\u00bb (''bi-l\u0101 mu\u1e25\u0101b\u0101'').}}</ref> The fact that he did not produce a suitable heir before the age of 46 has been ascribed either to him being more attracted to men,<ref>[[\u00c9variste L\u00e9vi-Proven\u00e7al]], ''Histoire de l'Espagne musulmane'', Paris, 1950</ref> although this is only reported euphemistically in the sources,<ref name=muqarnas>{{Cite journal| volume = 14| pages = 19\u201341| last = Prado-Vilar| first = Francisco| title = Circular visions of fertility and punishment: caliphal ivory caskets from al-Andalus| journal = Muqarnas| date = 1997| jstor = 1523234}}</ref> or because he was too absorbed with his books to care for sensual pleasures.<ref name=Ruggles />\n\n==Death and succession==\nAl-Hakam II suffered a [[stroke]] near the end of his life that curtailed his activities and may explain why he was unable to properly prepare his son for leadership.<ref>''Al-Hakam II, Caliph of Cordoba'', Marilyn Higbee Walker, '''Encyclopedia of Medieval Iberia''', ed. Michael Gerli (New York: Routledge, 2003), 377.</ref> Modern scholars have speculated that, based on the historical descriptions of his death, it was another [[cerebral circulation|cerebrovascular]] stroke, possibly brought on by the cold weather, that claimed his life in October 976.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Arjona-Castro|first=A.|title=Cerebrovascular stroke, the cause of the death of the caliph al-Hakam II|journal=Neurologia|date=February 1997|volume=12|issue=2|pages=78\u201381}}</ref>  He was succeeded by his son, [[Hisham II]] al-Mu'ayad, who was 11 years old at the time and was a nominal ruler under Almanzor.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Islam|Spain|LGBT|Biography|History}}\n*[[Moors]]\n*[[Islam in Spain]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource author}}\n{{Commons category|Al-Hakam II}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040814210621/http://history.al-islam.com/names.asp?year=366#n1771 Arabic biography]\n*[http://www.stirnet.com/genie/data/continent/hijk/iberia04.php#cord1 Stirnet: Iberia04] {{subscription required}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[Banu Umayya]]|||||[[Quraysh tribe|Banu Quraish]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Abd ar-Rahman III]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Caliph of C\u00f3rdoba]]|years=961\u2013976}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Hisham II]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\